<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--DiaperService     04-06 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Diaper Service,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Berkshire County's Last Diaper Service To Fold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The diaper business has hit bottom, forcing
the last remaining diaper service in Berkshire County to call it
quits.
   Thomas Holzer, vice president of Aladco, said that with more
parents using disposable diapers his customers have dropped from
400 a decade ago to a mere 60 scattered across the county.
   ``We can't operate at that low a volume,'' he said Tuesday.
   Holzer said he had hoped negative publicity about disposable
diapers choking landfills would slow the trend, but that didn't
happen.
   Toward the end, he found that he couldn't even give away his
business.
   People declined, even when diaper service was offered as a gift,
Holzer said.
   And so, in May, the Adams company, which also operates a
laundry, dry cleaning and linen and uniform rental business, is
dropping its diaper division.
</TEXT>
