<FIRST>r i PM-SexAid     04-06 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sex Aid,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sex Aid: ``We Just Want Their Money''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sex Aid. Keep a little tin box by the bed, and
donate 25 pence every time, uh, you know, whenever you do. Wink
wink, nudge nudge.
   The campaign announced by Marie Stopes International, a charity
which supports family planning in the Third World, sounds like a
publicity stunt.
   It is a publicity stunt.
   Patricia Hindmarsh, fund-raising manager for the charity, said
Wednesday that it has been working away quietly for 20 years,
``talking earnestly to people _ and it hasn't done the trick.''
   ``We now realize that we need more hype like Band Aid and Comic
Relief to draw people's attention to the problem, so we are asking
people to make love and save the world.''
   At the suggested rate of 25 pence (43 cents), Ms. Hindmarsh said
the average British couple could give 12.50 pounds (about $21.25) a
year.
   ``They can save it up or write us a check every six months or
put it in a little tin by the bed,'' Ms. Hindmarsh said.
   ``We don't really care how they do it,'' she confessed. ``At the
end of the day we just want their money.''
   There is a serious point too: ``I think it will help people
focus on the fact that they have the freedom to make love without
producing another mouth to feed,'' she said.
</TEXT>
