<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Life     04-06 0803</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Life,0832</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Huddle In Bunkers During Shelling Duels</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The murderous bombardment in Beirut, the
worst in four years, has squeezed people's daily lives to four
hours of scurrying about their business and 20 hours underground.
   When Syrian and Christian artillery gunners rest at daybreak,
thousands of trapped residents cautiously emerge from bunkers.
   Their first order of business is to hurriedly buy fresh supplies
of food, water, candles, gas lamps, decks of cards and sleeping
pills.
   Just before the antagonists resume the deadly duel that began
three weeks ago, they rush back to shelters on both sides of the
Green Line that divides the city into Moslem and Christian sectors.
   Most nightclubs, bars, restaurants, cafes and movie houses are
closed. So are schools and universities. Banks operate haphazardly
for two or three hours a day, depending on the ferocity of the
shelling.
   ``The only thing that matters nowadays is self-preservation,''
said Amin Trad, a pharmacist in Christian East Beirut's Ashrafiyeh
district. ``Survival is the name of the game.''
   He did not recall a similar stampede for sleeping pills in
Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   ``I don't have statistics. But if this continues, we will soon
run out of tranquilizers,'' said Trad, whose pharmacy is shielded
by tall sandbag walls.
   There are no severe shortages at present. Wholesalers try to
monopolize goods in order to raise prices, and stores order new
stock during lulls in the fighting.
   Some residents manage to joke about the shelling.
   ``Tell my friends in west Beirut not to worry about me,'' said
Bahjat Jaber, a police reporter who lives in east Beirut's
Maameltein suburb. Like many others, he commuted between Beirut's
two sectors before the latest round of fighting.
   ``I have all the fireworks. Some 200 shells explode around my
apartment nightly. The house is always shaking like a swing, and I
am swinging,'' quipped Jaber, 55.
   A Greek Catholic bachelor, Jaber does not use the basement
shelter of his seaside apartment building because his 92-year-old
mother can hardly move. ``I simply can't leave her alone.''
   When a missile detonated a large gas storage tank at Beirut
port, winds blew the flame and smoke in the direction of his house,
10 miles north of Beirut.
   ``I'm lik a roasted chicken,'' he joked to friends on the
telephone.
   The fighting pits army commander Gen. Mily
Christian units against an alliance of Syrian troops and Druse
Moslem militiamen.
   It was touched off by an air-and-sea blockade Aoun clamped on
militia-run illegal ports on March 6 in a bid to reinstate
government authority. Aoun heads a Christian Cabinet in the
fractured nation's dual government.
   The Syrians and Mosmilitia allies, who recognize the rival
Moslem Cbinet of former Prime Minister Salim Hoss, retaliated by
sealis to the Christian enclave and blockading
its 1 million inhabitts with their bato the sea.
   Ensuing bouts of savage bombardment have blown 
hundreds of houses, wrecked power plants, destroyed city water
pipes and threatened to crush the nation's infrstructure.
   Police statistics show an average of 3,000 shells fell on the
city and its environs every day of the past three weeks, killing
more than 150 people and wounding 500.
   Mor than 90 have been killed and 300 wounded in easnd
the adjoining Christian hinterland. The other casulaties were in
the city's Moslem sector and Druse-controlled hills.
   Nabil Haddad, 38, a Christian grcer, said he has been surviving
with his wife aong with 40 neighbors in the
candle-lit basement of their 6-story apartment building.
   ``I death so close. I give up,'' he said at the doorstep
of their shelter in east Beirut's poor Einrict.
``We're suffocating. I don't think we're e.''
   Haddad opens his store only during morning lulls in shelling.
   Shukri Lahhoud, a banker who lives  posh, hilltop Rabieh
district on east Beirut's northern flank, was more optimistic.
   ``We'to make it,'' he said. ``I don't think the world
is going to al the annihilation of 1 million Christians. Thisng to stop.''
   Lahhoud said he and his neighbors while away the hours in
running games of poker and backgamloor
underground shelter, which houses a power generator.
   The city's Moslem sector is virtually a ghost town. Tens of
thousands of residents have fled to relative safety in east and
south Lebanon.
   Those who stayed behind also spend nights in shelters as
soldiers with multibarreled mobile rocket launchers roam around,
firing off a barrage, then moving quickly before retaliatory fire
comes. Civilians take the punishment.
   ``It's a dirty trick but no one dares protest it,'' ident who requested
anonymity.
</TEXT>
