<FIRST>r a AM-ThinBlueLine 1stLd-Writethru a0838 04-06 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0838,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Who Led Fight Against Adams' Release Is Fired</HEAD>
<UNK>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with district attorney confirming
report; INSERTS 1 graf after 12th graf pvs, `Vance said ...' No pickup.</UNK>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The assistant district attorney who led the fight
to keep ``The Thin Blue Line'' defendant Randall Dale Adams behind
bars was fired Wednesday.
   Winfield Scott was dismissed for violating policies, Dallas
County District Attorney John Vance said. Scott was the third
prosecutor involved in the case to leave the office this week.
   Scott did not return repeated calls from The Associated Press.
Other officials at the office declined comment.
   Over Scott's objections, Adams was released from prison March
22, a few weeks after a state court overturned his conviction for
the 1976 slaying of a Dallas policeman. Adams had spent more than
12 years in prison.
   The case was examined in Errol Morris' 1988 documentary, ``The
Thin Blue Line,'' which questioned evidence in the case.
   Scott, who served as an assistant district attorney in Dallas
for 21 years, participated in the original prosecution of Adams.
   Adams was ordered released after the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals said evidence had been suppressed and at least two
witnesses lied on the stand.
   In fighting Adams' release, Scott said state District Court
Judge Larry Baraka and eight of the nine appellate judges were
biased in Adams' favor. He asked that Baraka be removed from the
case.
   Scott's arguments held up Adams' release for one night before
another state judge ruled in Adams' favor.
   The day after Adams' release, Vance said evidence to retry him
was lacking, and the murder charge was dropped.
   Vance said he'd investigate Scott's behavior as a personnel
matter.
   In his remarks Wednesday night, Vance said he had nothing but
admiration and respect for Scott. ``I found we had a conflict
regarding current office policies that simply could not be resolved
any other way,'' Vance said.
   Earlier this week, John Creuzot and Leslie McFarlane resigned.
Both had been with the office about six years and worked on Adams'
case.
   Neither would specify their reasons for resigning, but said they
planned to go into private practice.
</TEXT>
