<FIRST>r a AM-Shoreham     04-06 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shoreham,0248</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shoreham Nuclear Power Plant A Step Closer To Dismantling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH EDWARDSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York's Public Service Commission on
Wednesday approved an agreement allowing the state to buy the $5.4
billion Shoreham nuclear power plant for $1 and dismantle it.
   In approving the deal, worked out earlier this year by Gov.
Mario Cuomo and officials of the Long Island Lighting Co., which
owns the plant, the commission authorized rate increases that could
result in New York's Long Island residents paying the highest
electric rates in the nation.
   The panel made permanent a 5.4 percent rate increase granted
earlier this year, approved a 5 percent rate increase to go into
effect in December, and authorized another 5 percent increase for
December 1990.
   The agreement to close Shoreham still must be be approved by the
New York Power Authority and the Long Island Power Authority by
April 15. Then it is subject to approval by the utility's
shareholders and board of directors.
   The higher rates would give Long Island Lighting a shot at
regaining the financial stability it lost in recent years because
of the burdens imposed on it by the ill-fated Shoreham project.
   Public Service Commission members, who approved an earlier
agreement worked out by Cuomo and the utility only to the see that
deal die because of state legislators' refusal to approve it, said
they hoped they were putting the controversial plant behind them.
</TEXT>
