<DOCNO> AP890406-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CastleHeir     04-06 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Castle Heir,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Adopted Baron Misses Deadline For Keeping Castle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FERRYSBURG, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was no happy ending to the fairy
tale-like life that Richard Hemmelsbach has lived since being
adopted last summer by a childless West German baron.
   On Wednesday, Hemmelsbach missed a bank's deadline for coming up
with $3 million to keep the baron's 1,429-year-old castle in the
family. The West German bank that has a lien on the 150-room castle
and 970-acre estate plans to put the property up for sale.
   As the adopted son of 76-year-old Baron Freiherr Theodore
vonLiebieg, Hemmelsbach stood to inherit the castle and surrounding
vineyards on the Mosel River at the foot of the Eifel Mountains in
southwestern West Germany.
   The value of the castle and estate is estimated at $10 million.
   But Hemmelsbach said he has something more important than a
castle.
   ``I still have this wonderful birthright and a wonderful father
and I plan to be a good baron and good son,'' Hemmelsbach said
Wednesday. ``I think we're all disappointed, but the baron has
never asked about the castle. He only wants to know when I am
coming back to visit.''
   VonLiebieg selected Hemmelsbach, in part because of his German
heritage, from more than 10,000 people worldwide who responded to
the baron's televised plea for an heir on the syndicated show ``A
Current Affair'' last June.
   Hemmelsbach didn't know at the time that he would be asked to
save the family's deteriorating estate, which was taken over by the
bank when a German businessman who had purchased the castle from
vonLiebieg defaulted on a loan.
   The baron has not lived in the castle for more than a dozen
years. He lives with his wife in a nearby villa.
   Hemmelsbach, a 57-year-old businessman, said he will continue to
work to purchase the castle for as long as it remains for sale, but
about 18 private and corporate investors, including a German hotel
chain have lined up to purchase the estate from the bank.
   ``I've been a rainbow chaser all my life,'' said Hemmelsbach,
who lives in the Lake Michigan town of Ferrysburg. ``I guess I'll
always continue to do that _ I'm too old to do otherwise.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
