<FIRST>r w PM-US-Gorbachev     04-06 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Gorbachev,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Skeptical of Gorbachev Position</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration, disappointed that
Mikhail S. Gorbachev is not withdrawing military support from
Nicaragua, is accusing the Soviet president of empty rhetoric
regarding Central American peace.
   ``While his words about not exporting revolution are welcomed,
they are not matched by deeds which would give those words
credence,'' White House Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said
Wednesday, referring to Gorbachev's denunciation of the export of
revolution.
   Gorbachev's comments in his speech in Havana on Tuesday
conflicted with the policy of Cuban President Fidel Castro, who
supports the spread of revolutionary movements.
   But, in a written statement read by Fitzwater, the White House
called on Gorbachev to back up his statements about wanting
demilitarized peace zones in Central America, by discontinuing
military assistance to the leftist government of Nicaragua.
   ``Today, we call upon the Soviets to cut off their
half-billion-dollar annual military aid to Nicaragua. The Soviets
continue to pour arms into Nicaragua, a country whose army is
already larger than those of all their neighbors combined,'' he
said.
   Fitzwater said continued Soviet activity in Central America will
affect U.S.-Soviet relations, but declined to specify how the
administration might express its displesure.
   ``We've never made linkage threats,'' he said. ``But we have
always said these are the kinds of things that influence the
relationship between the United States and the Soviet Union.''
   A day earlier, Fitzwater had said Soviet spokesman Gennady
Gerasimov's statements against the export of revolution appeared to
be a positive sign. But on Wednesday he was more resng, ``We can hold out
a little optimism on the basis of the
words,'' but that the administration is looking for deedsto back
them up.
   U.S. officials looked to the Soviet leader's visit to Cuba as an
opportunity for him to change direction in Central America. Bush
had written him urging Soviet withdrawal of military support from
the leftist Nicaraguan government, and a halt to Cuban and
Nicaraguan support for leftist guerrillas in El Salvador.
   But Gorbachev, in his Tuesday speech to the National Assembly in
Havana, said Moscow will not has support for Nicaragua as long United States
continues military assistance to other
governments in the region.
   Fitzwatert
comparable to the Soviet assistance because the U.S.-backed nations
``are not involved in subversion of their neighbors.''
   U.S. officials estimate the Soviets shipped more than $500
million in military aid last year to Nicaragua and gave Managua the
same amount in economic asse the United States has
bankrolled the Contra rebels fighting to oust the Sandinistas.
Bush's shift to a diplomatic course means U.S. aid to the Contras
is now non-military.
   U.S. aid to El Salvador this decade totals some $3.5 billion,
and the administration accuses the Soviets of supporting the
Salvadoran rebels through Cuba and Nicaragua. Critics of the
administration policy, meanwhile, cite widespreder the U.S.-backed regime.
</TEXT>
