<FIRST>r w PM-Budget     04-06 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Budget,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Budget Talks Stuck on Capital Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee says President Bush's insistence on cutting the capital
gains tax is a ``thorn in our negotiations'' as White House and
congressional bargainers try to complete a budget agreement.
   ``I think we're confused,'' Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., said
Wednesday night, after a meeting with Treasury Secretary Nicholas
Brady and Richard Darman, director of the Office of Management and
Budget.
   ``We're a room of good intentions,'' he said, but, ``there's a
difficult thorn in our negotiations and that's capital gains.''
   Brady and Darman have been meeting with key members of Congress
to craft a plan for meeting the goal of a $100 billion deficit in
fiscal 1990, which begins Oct. 1.
   About $28 billion in either new revenues or spending restraint
would be needed to meet that goal, according to White House
estimates.
   As part of the deficit reduction plan in his fiscal 1990 budget,
President Bush proposed cutting the tax rate on capital gains to 15
percent, about in half.
   The president contends the rate cut would raise about $4.8
billion in revenue. However, congressional estimates show the
reduction would be a big revenue loser in the long run and,
Democrats contend, the rich would benefit the most from the tax
break.
   Although his own budget included several billion dollars in tax
increases and new user fees, Bush contends those did not violate
his campaign pledge against any new taxes.
   With Democrats opposing the capital gains scheme, coming up with
a deficit-reduction plan has proven difficult since alternative tax
revenues or more spending cuts would be needed.
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., the House Budget Committee
chairman, has proposed in the talks that half the deficit
reduction, about $14 billion, come from revenues _ a combination of
taxes, sales of government assets, and new user fees. Bush's
revenue proposals produced about the same amount, but included the
claimed capital gains influx.
   He said Wednesday that resolution of the tax issue is crucial to
the success of the talks.
   Rostenkowski said he was not discouraged, but it would be
difficult.
   ``We're going to continue to talk ... but I don't know that
we're going to meet any of the deadlines,'' he said.
   Congress has an April 15 deadline for completing the budget.
   Brady and Darman declined to comment on the specifics of the
meeting.
   ``It's just part of the budget process,'' Brady said. Asked if
he had brought something new to discuss, he said, ``I didn't bring
a thing.''
</TEXT>
