<FIRST>r w PM-TransportationPosts     04-06 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Transportation Posts,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transportation Chiefs Selected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An academician and a mass transit
administrator are President Bush's choices to become the respective
heads of the Federal Highway Administration and the Urban Mass
Transit Administration, sources say.
   The White House has told the Department of Transportation and
lawmakers that it intends to appoint Thomas Larson, 60, a professor
who was secretary of the Pennsylvania Department of Transportation
under former Gov. Dick Thornburgh, to run the FHWA, department and
congressional officials said Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, the White House has told the same lawmakers and DOT
officials that Brian Clymer, vice chairman of the Southeastern
Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, will be named administrator
of UMTA.
   Clymer, 41, an accountant in Swarthmore, is on the policy-making
board of SEPTA, which oversees buses, trolleys, subways and
commuter lines for an average daily ridership of 1.2 million
passengers in the five-county Philadelphia area.
   Larson was Pennsylvania transportation secretary for eight years
under Thornburgh, now the U.S. attorney general. Responsible for
the nation's fourth largest highway system, Larson oversaw an
agency with roughly 12,500 employees and a $3 billion annual budget.
   A favorite of Thornburgh's, Larson began a $1 billion bridge
repair program and used merit hiring and a goal-oriented management
style to try to rebuild a department scarred by scandal from the
administration of former Gov. Milton Shapp.
   Larson left state government with Thornburgh in 1986, and is now
a special assistant for economic affairs to the president of
Pennsylvania State University, where he had previously been a
faculty member and administrator for 17 years.
   Larson declined to comment on the federal post, and SEPTA
officials said Clymer was in a board meeting and unavailable for
comment.
   The highway administration monitors the federal aid program for
highway construction, administers a bridge replacement program, and
oversees safety programs. UMTA assists state and local governments
in improving mass transportation systems.
   FHWA and UMTA are the last two major federal transportation
posts to be filled. The announcement is expected within a week.
</TEXT>
