<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Gorbachev-MilitaryAid     04-06 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gorbachev-Military Aid,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Analysts Disappointed by Gorbachev Speech</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev's call for an end to the
``export of revolution and counterrevolution'' to Latin America
disappointed U.S. analysts who were hoping for a stronger sign that
the Kremlin would curtail its military aid to Cuba.
   Bush administration officials, pursuing a more conciliatory
Central American policy than President Reagan, agreed with
congressional leaders last month not to seek military aid for the
Contra guerrillas of Nicaragua.
   They hoped that in response, Gorbachev would curtail the
estimated $6 billion in aid the Kremlin sends to Cuba, the $1
billion in Soviet aid to Nicaragua, and East bloc assistance to
leftist guerrillas in El Salvador.
   ``While his words about not exporting revolution are welcome,
they are not matched by deeds which would give his words
credence,'' White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday.
   Gorbachev, meeting in Havana with Cuban leader Fidel Castro,
scolded Western media for reporting a Cuban-Soviet rift and gave no
indication that the Kremlin would be cutting its aid to the
Caribbean island, estimated at about $6 billion a year.
   ``As in the past, the Soviet Union and Cuba have a common
approach to the key problems of international affairs,'' Gorbachev
said. ``The most immediate task is to solve so-called regional
conflicts.
   ``We are resolutely against any theories and doctrines
justifying the export of revolution or counterrevolution, and all
forms of interference in the affairs of sovereign nations,''
Gorbachev said.
   On Tuesday, Fitzwater had said that the United States would
welcome ``the reduction of Soviet military support in Nicaragua or
if they mean that Soviet surrogates would cease supporting''
insurgents in El Salvador.
   Instead, Gorbachev condemned American ``meddling in Afghan
affairs.'' The United States has been sending an estimated $500
million a year in covert aid to the anti-communist guerrillas of
Afghanistan, helping secure the negotiated withdrawal of Soviet
troops last February.
   Many Americans have engaged in ``wishful thinking,'' hoping that
Gorbachev would seek to ease economic problems at home by
curtailing aid to revolutionary movements abroad, particularly
Latin America, said Howard Wiarda, a political scientist at the
University of Massachusetts.
   But ``there is no evidence whatsoever that the Soviets have
started to reduce military aid to Nicaragua or to the rebels in El
Salvador,'' said Wiarda.
   Although Gorbachev may be pressuring Castro in private meetings
to tone down his revolutionary rhetoric, and may ultimately curtail
Soviet aid to leftist insurgencies, ``I think it unrealistic to
expect Gorbachev to change those policies quickly,'' said Wiarda.
   The chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee applauded
Gorbachev's statement on the export of revolution, while at the
same time criticizing Castro's past policies.
   ``I hope Castro follows Gorbachev's advice,'' said Sen.
Claiborne Pell, D-R.I. ``Certainly, much of our trouble in Central
America comes from Cuban activities. If they can be closed down,
this will help peace to come to that troubled region.''
   A former Cuban diplomat now living in the United States, Juan
Benemelis, said American ``expectations were too high for this
meeting.''
   ``I think there is definitely conflict between Gorbachev and
Castro, but that it will take some time'' to become public, said
Benemelis, who worked in Africa for Castro before defecting in 1980.
   Benemelis has seen hints that Gorbachev will reduce aid to Cuba
as well as pressure Castro to curtail military interference in
other countries, but doesn't think the trend will become obvious
until both countries enter their next five-year economic period in
1991.
   ``Since Gorbachev took power, the Soviets have been asking the
Cubans to fulfill their annual trade agreements. Castro has had
problems, for example, filling his sugar quota. He has not been
doing it,'' he said.
   Castro, who opposes the type of political reforms Gorbachev is
pressing in the Soviet Union, said Tuesday that no such changes are
needed in Cuba.
   ``But if Soviet aid was reduced, Castro would face a political
crisis,'' said Benemelis.
   The Cuban leader, who has developed strong ties to the Soviet
military and intelligence agencies over the decades, may be biding
his time, hoping that conservatives in those organizations will
force Gorbachev from power, said Benemelis.
   ``Castro is betting on the opposition,'' said Benemelis.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Bryan Brumley covers national security affairs
for The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
