<SECOND>PM-Atwood Confirmation,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Defense Nominee Makes `Extraordinary' Stock Divestment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Atwood, a General Motors Corp.
executive tapped for deputy defense secretary, is promising to sell
his more than $3 million in company stock to avoid any conflict of
interest.
   The vice chairman of the giant automaker also said Wednesday
that he took out an insurance policy to guarantee his GM pension
should the company fail, to protect against any suggestion he would
use his government office to protect the company for the sake of a
pension.
   ``This is way beyond what is remotely reasonable,'' Sen. Trent
Lott, R-Miss., member of the Senate Armed Services Committee, said
in praise of Atwood's efforts.
   ``You've done an extraordinary thing,'' said Sen. Carl Levin,
D-Mich., a member of the Senate Armed Services Committee. ``You've
probably gone overboard ... you've done it at a great expense to
yourself.''
   Atwood, 64, owns about $1.4 million in restricted GM stock
options and about $1.2 million in Class E common stock as well as
other types of common stock estimated at over $750,000, according
to congressional sources.
   In addition, Atwood owns between $5,000 to $15,000 in AT&amp;T stock
and between $50,000 to $100,000 in Exxon stock, the sources said.
Financial disclosure forms only require listing a range of assets.
   Atwood, a member of the board of directors of General Motors
since May 1987, made his unusual financial promises just one month
after the Senate rejected John Tower, President Bush's first choice
for defense secretary.
   Senators cited allegations of excessive drinking and womanizing
as well as the appearance of conflict of interest in voting against
Tower. The former Texas senator had received more than $1 million
in consulting fees from defense contractors after leaving
government service.
   The Senate later confirmed Bush's second nominee for defense
secretary, Rep. Dick Cheney of Wyoming.
   On the opening day of hearings, Levin and Richard Lugar, R-Ind.,
introduced Atwood to the Senate Armed Services Committee with Levin
noting that ``anybody who can master GM's bureaucracy has a
fighting chance at the Pentagon.''
   The panel's chairman, Sen. Sam Nunn, D-Ga., indicated that
Atwood would likely win confirmation.
   Atwood has 90 days to sell his holdings but said he hoped to
receive an extension. When he accepted Bush's offer, Atwood said he
was told that Tower would be confirmed by the third week in January
and that he would win approval by the second week in Febary.
   ``Between the first week in February and now there has been a
gradual erosion in the stock market and a gradual erosion in auto
stock,'' Atwood said.
   On other issues, Atwood expressed his support for purchasing
commercial products if they are available at lower costs than those
manufactured by defense contractors.
   The nominee also told Nunn that the departmet's top defense
priorities are a national secur under way, the Pentagon's acquisition system
and the
ethics problems in the wake of the ``Ill Wind'' procurement scandal.
   ``We don't just issue a pamphlet (on ethics),'' Atwood said.
``We have to makee that they have the training.''
</TEXT>
