   In some countries _ Argentina and Chile of the 1970s are
examples _ renegades like mysteriously disappeared or
were shot outright.
   Here, he has been able to work, raise three children, se
son graduate from college and, with notable exceptions that have
left him understandably embitered, lead a reasonably stable
existence.
   believes Cuba needs change.
   Almost all critics of the syste, suffered
imprisonment because they trespasseds or simply
opted for silence.
   Almost nobody chooses to trto change things through the
electoral process. Bahamonde, an agricultural engineer, is an
exction.
   He has a number of gripes about the sallowed to be self-employed, that
press censorship should
end a with food rationing and that Cuba should allow es to compete with
the Communist Party.
   The points he wanted to make that Tuesday night
in March when he joined his neighbors for an elect state
assembly seat.
   On March 21, the Comrge of the
proceedings refused Bahamonde permission to read his platform. The
party stalwart st, according to standard procedures, voters
are permitted to spavor or against the candidates once
the nominating process is completed.
   The candidates themselves cannot campaign.
   The establishment candidate was Gerardo Aldama, a decorated
26-year veteran of the Interior Miniry who served in Angola. In a
country that honors citizens who sacrifice themselves for the
revolution, Aldama is a man of distinction.
   During a sometimes tense period in which Bahamonde's credentials
were discussed that evening, he found his controversial past
