<FIRST>r w PM-ForeignTravel-Trips     04-06 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Foreign Travel-Trips,0630</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0441, changing cycle designator.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Zaire Pays for Congressman's Investigative Trip</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Foreign Travel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Mervyn Dymally was in France visiting
Zaire's president last September when the African leader suggested
Dymally travel to Zaire personally to investigate a human rights
matter on which members of Congress had expressed criticism.
   ``I said I didn't have any way to get there, and he said, `Why
don't you take Air Zaire,''' Dymally, D-Calif., said in an
interview.
   So the government of Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko picked
up the tab for Dymally's two-day trip from Nice, France to Zaire,
via Belgium.
   Dymally was one of eight House members and two senators who
reported receiving travel expenses from foreign governments in
1988. At least a handful of others didn't report their expenses,
despite a federal law requiring such reports.
   A member of the House Foreign Affairs Committee, Dymally flew to
Kinshasa then traveled by ground transportation to visit opposition
leader Tshisekedi wa Mulumba. In May, 58 members of the U.S.
Congress had protested banishment of Tshisekedi to a remote
up-country area.
   But Dymally said he found the former interior minister living in
an apartment and driving a Mercedes. ``He'd been out partying the
night before,'' the congressman said.
   Tshisekedi was in internal exile between April and Sept. 17,
1988. He was released after Dymally's visit.
   Here are details of other trips taken by members of Congess on
which foreign governments paid expenses:
   _ Rep. Bill Frenzel, R-Minn., and his wife were flown from
Taipei, Taiwan, to Hong Kong at the expense of the Hong Kong
government. They stayed two nights. Frenzel said he discussed trade
and foreign policy issues with officials. Rep. Michael G. Oxley,
R-Ohio, took a similiar trip from Taiwan to Hong Kong, and Rep. Rod
Chandler, R-Wash., accepted a helicopter tour of Hong Kong, paid
for by the Hong Kong Economic and Trade Office. All three filed
reports on the expenses.
   _ Rep. Thomas Downey, D-N.Y., was vacationing in New Zealand
when officials of that country's foreign ministry flew him and his
wife to Wellington, the capital, and then to Auckland. Downey said
he had dinner with Prime Minister David Lange, and discussed issues
such as nuclear arms control and the docking of American ships. He
filed a report.
   _ Reps. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas; Robin Tallon, D-S.C.; Roy
Rowland, D-Ga., and Jerry Huckaby, D-La., and their wives took a
12-day trip to Australia and New Zealand during which the
congressmen discussed international trade and export issues. The
trip was sponsored by ``private, quasi-private and foreign
government entitites,'' according to Stenholm.
   They included Qantas Airways, the Australian Meat and Livestock
Corp., the New Zealand Dairy Board, the New Zealand Wool Board and
the New Zealand Apple and Pear Marketing Board. Stenholm and Tallon
didn't file reports; Rowland and Huckaby did.
   _ Rep. Douglas Bereuter, R-Neb., and Sen. William Cohen,
R-Maine, were guests of the East German government at a conference
on East-West security in Potsdam, East Germany, in June 1988. The
conference was arranged by the Institute for East-West Security
Studies, a non-profit group in New York. Jonathan Bach, an
institute spokesman, said the host country picked up the expenses.
Bereuter filed a report; Cohen didn't.
   _ Ses. James Exon, D-Neb.; Howell Heflin, D-Ala., Larry
Pressler, R-S.D.; Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and former Sen. John Melcher,
D-Mont., went on a U.S.-funded trip to Guam, the Philippines,
Australia and New Zealand in January.
   While in New Zealand, they traveled on a jet belonging to that
country, and were also provided transportation by the Australian
government, according to Heflin's spokesman, Tom McMahon. Heflin
filed a report; the others didn't.
</TEXT>
