<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-06 0175</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shares Plunge On Tokyo Market, Dollar Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged Thursday on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange, while the U.S. dollar firmed against the Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
48.54 points to a record 33,360.79 on Wednesday, lost 365.01
points, or 1.1 percent, to finish trading at 32,995.78.
   The dollar closed at 132.15 yen, up 0.78 yen from the previous
day's 131.37-yen finish. The currency opened at 131.93 yen and
moved in a range of 131.75-132.25 yen.
   Traders said the dollar's rise followed overnight gains in New
York.
   Trading was slow as participants exercised caution ahead of the
announcement of the U.S. jobless rate Friday, said a dealer at a
commercial bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The Nikkei had risen for the last seven trading days, gaining a
total of more than 1,800 points since March 28.
   ``Participants slowed their buying after the consecutive gains,
and some speculators are selling for profit-taking,'' said an
analyst with Nomura Securities in Tokyo.
</TEXT>
