<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     04-06 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Najib Declares Truce; Kabul Attack Kills 10; Pakistanis Sentenced
For Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Najib's government declared
a cease-fire in its war against the U.S.-backed Moslem guerrillas
for Ramadan, the Islamic holy month of fasting.
   Najib said the unilateral cease-fire would begin at midnight
today. If the rebels refused to observe the sanctity of the fasting
month, he said, government troops would retaliate.
   It was at least the fourth cease-fire declared by Najib since
January 1987. The first truce was disregarded by both sides, and
the guerrillas ignored all subsequent calls.
   The latest cease-fire was broadcast Wednesday by the official
Kabul Radio.
   Earlier, guerrilla rockets slammed into downtown Kqabul, killing
six people and wounding 23, a government official said on condition
of anonymity. Kabul Radio said 10 people were killed and 39 wounded.
   On Tuesday, at least six people were killed and eight wounded by
rockets that hit residential neighborhoods.
   Meanwhile, a special security court convicted two Pakistanis of
spying. Sgt. Mohammad Ashraf was sentenced Wednesday to 18 years
imprisonment and Cpl. Mohammad Afzal was sentenced to 16 years.
   Ashraf, 35, and Afzal, 25, confessed to spying for Pakistani
intelligence agencies. Judge Obaid Sakhi said they could have been
sentenced to death but he and the other two judges hearing the case
had acceded to their requests for leniency.
   Sakhi said the sentences could be appealed.
   Ashraf and Afzal said they worked for Pakistani intelligence
agencies and were ``forcibly sent'' to Afghanistan by their
superior officers. Ashraf said he received a $1,000 bonus, while
Afzal said he was promised $200 upon his return.
   Pakistan has regularly denied sending any nationals into
Afghanistan.
   In Islamabad, a Pakistan Foreign Ministry official questioned
Wednesday whether the pair were Pakistanis, saying no proof of
their identity had been supplied to Pakistan's mission in Kabul.
The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Afghan government said the men were captured March 10 in
Kandahar province, which borders Pakistan.
   Most of the Afghan guerrillas are based in Pakistan.
   They have received support from the United States, China,
Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and other countries in their decade-old war
against the Soviet Union's protege government in Kabul. The Red
Army ended its nine-year involvement in Afghanistan Feb. 15, but
Moscow is still supplying the Najib government.
   The rocket attacks on Kabul Tuesday and Wednesday were the
biggest attacks on the capital since March 14, when at least five
rockets hit the airport, injuring two people.
   Wednesday's rockets spewed shrapnel and debris as they hit a
small park next to the Kabul Hotel and a commercial district
several blocks away. The rockets, which landed four to 10 blocks
from the Foreign Ministry, were fired before noon, when sidewalks
and marketplaces are crowded with pedestrians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0540EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Honduras     04-06 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Honduras,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Honduras Approves New U.S. Military Training Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers have agreed to let U.S.
military forces continue joint training exercises with Honduran
troops in this Central American country that borders Nicaragua and
El Salvador.
   In a separate action, the legislature also approved new measures
for cooperating with the United States to fight drug trafficking.
   The military exercises agreement was approved by a 132-2 vote on
Wednesday. The lawmakers who voted no said the measure could hurt
regional peace efforts.
   The two countries have engaged in more than 80 joint military
training exercises involving at least 60,000 U.S. and 20,000
Honduran troops during the past 38 years.
   The exercises were stepped up in 1982 when relations between
Honduras and the leftist Sandinista government in Nicaragua
deteriorated and the United States built an air base in Honduras.
   Honduras also has served as a refuge, training ground and
staging base for Nicaraguan rebels, about 11,000 of whom have lived
with their families in camps near the Nicaraguan border since the
U.S. government cut off military aid to them in February 1988.
   An estimated 1,100 American troops currently are stationed at
the Enrique Soto Cano U.S. Air Force Base, about 50 miles northeast
of Tegucigalpa.
   The base is considered among the most important centers of U.S.
military operations in Central America. Washington has been
supporting the government of El Salvador in its nine-year war
against leftist rebels.
   Under the drug agreement, Honduran officials said they will work
with the United States to crack down on drug production and
trafficking. Both nations are to share information and human and
technological resources.
   During the past six years, Honduras' Caribbean coast has become
a transfer point for drug shipments from Colombia to the United
States.
   In the most-publicized local case, reputed drug baron Juan Ramon
Matta returned home to Honduras in 1986 after escaping from a
Colombian prison.
   His arrest in April 1988 at his home in Tegucigalpa and rapid
deportation to the United States touched off riots. Extradition of
Hondurans is prohibited by the constitution.
   Matta remains jailed at the federal prison in Marion, Ill.,
serving a three-year sentence for escaping from a Florida prison in
1971.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
