<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Romanov     04-06 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Romanov,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Princess Natasha Romanov</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princess Natasha Galitzine Romanov,
whose husband was a nephew of Russia's last czar, Nicholas II, has
died. She was 82.
   She died March 28 in nearby Woodside.
   Her father was a doctor in Moscow when she was born. After the
Bolshevik Revolution, the family fled to China, then to Seattle and
eventually to Hollywood where she acted in silent films.
   Her roles included that of Josephine in a movie about Napoleon.
   ``But when talking films came, because of her deep voice and
heavy accent, she didn't continue,'' said Albert Bartridge, her
attorney.
   She met Prince Vasili Romanov in New York and they moved to
Woodside in the 1930s.
   According to Bartridge, the two helped gather much of the
collection on imperial Russia that is housed at the Hoover
Institution at Stanford University.
   Survivors include her husband, their daughter, Marina Beadleston
of Aspen, Colo., and four grandchildren.
   A funeral service was held March 30 at the Russian Orthodox
Church of the Nativity of the Holy Virgin in Menlo Park. A memorial
service was held Wednesday.
</TEXT>
