<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Markets     04-06 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall; Dollar Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's main index plunged
today, ending seven days of gains, while the dollar rose
substantially against the Japanese yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which rose 48.54 points to a
record high on Wednesday, shed 365.01 points, or 1.1 percent, to
finish trading at 32,995.78. It was the index's second-largest
decline this year, following a 366.21-point drop on March 20, when
it finished at 31,654.80.
   Stocks fell almost across the board as participants expressed
concern about the recent rapid rise in the Nikkei index, which had
gained more than 1,800 points since last Tuesday, said a dealer
with a major securities firm in Tokyo.
   Uncertainty over possible political instability caused by a
widening stock-profiteering scandal also discouraged participants,
the dealer said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``The scandal has been continuing for some time, but speculators
are very concerned now about the situation,'' he said.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, whose party is under fire for
its links to Recruit Co., the information services conglomerate at
the center of the scandal, suffered a major blow Wednesday with
reports he had received $380,000 from the firm at fund-raising
parties in May 1987.
   In the scandal, the company reportedly sold hundreds of
thousands of unlisted shares of a real-estate subsidiary at
discount prices to about 150 influential public and business
figures. The recipients of the shares made substantial profits
after over-the-counter trading began and the stocks quickly rose in
value.
   Takeshita's public support ratings have plunged to about 10
percent and he now faces strong pressure from the political
opposition to resign.
   ``Investors' second-largest concern is inflation, which made
them either step off to the sidelines or sell issues because of the
upcoming release of the U.S. unemployment rate,'' the dealer said.
The U.S. jobless rate for March is to be announced Friday in
Washington.
   Inflation and subsequent interest rate hikes to slow the economy
could discourage stock investment.
   Trading was active, with volume on the first section estimated
at 1.1 billion shares, down from Wednesday's 1.8 billion shares.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 132.15 yen,
up 0.78 yen from Wednesday's 131.37-yen finish. The U.S. currency
started trading at 131.93 yen and ranged between 131.75 and 132.25
yen.
   A trader with Mitsubishi Bank said the dollar-yen exchange rate
changed little during the day as investors stayed on the sidelines
trying to avoid major moves ahead of the release of the U.S.
unemployment rate.
   ``Basically, the market has more demand for the dollar than the
yen, mainly because of the higher interest rates in the United
States,'' said the trader, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   For currency investors, higher U.S. interest rates make the
dollar more attractive than the yen.
</TEXT>
