<FIRST>r p PM-ChicagoMayoral     04-06 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Say They Will Hold Daley to `Open Door' Promise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor-elect Richard M. Daley's promise that the
doors of his office would remain open to blacks was greeted with
guarded optimism by many of the political leaders who lost control
of City Hall.
   The promise highlighted Daley's Tuesday night victory speech. A
day later, acting Mayor Eugene Sawyer told reporters, ``You heard
him say it. We'll make sure he sticks to it.''
   Also helping hold Daley to his word, Sawyer said, is the
practical matter of having to face re-election in 1991.
   ``I'm sure he'll be extremely careful. They've got a short time.
You've got to have continuity in government. You can't just go in
there and clean out all the blacks,'' said Sawyer, who is black.
   Daley's victory over chief rival Timothy C. Evans, the lone
black in Tuesday's election, earned him the right to complete the
final two years of the late Harold Washington's second term.
   And Daley invoked the memory of Washington as well as his
political boss-father, the late Richard J. Daley, in promising that
``The City That Works'' will work first to unite an electorate
deeply divided along racial lines.
   ``The openness and fairness that the late Mayor Harold
Washington talked about will be in my administration in the city of
Chicago,'' said Daley, whose victory ended six years of black
political control in the nation's third-largest city.
   ``A mayor today has to bring people together from one end of
this city to the other,'' he added, ``to accomplish the things that
are necessary to give people a good quality of life.''
   During a round of interviews, the 46-year-old Daley said he
planned to leave soon for a brief vacation and would make few moves
until his transition team completed its report. His inauguration is
set for April 24 _ his 47th birthday.
   But before rushing off to attend to business that has stacked up
in his state's attorney's office during the four-month campaign, he
proposed several programs reminiscent of the shirt-sleeve
professionalism that earned Chicago, in his father's days, the
moniker of ``The City That Works.''
   ``I will bring out the best of my father _ he knew city
government,'' Daley said. ``He knew state and federal government.
He loved this city and worked very hard for this city and I'll try
to be like him.''
   Evans' most prominent supporter, Jesse Jackson, called for party
unity and for blacks to move beyond the rivalry between Sawyer and
Evans.
   ``The basic Harold Washington coalition has remained a bit too
divided and when we unite we will win,'' Jackson said, pointing
out, ``there are only 18 months before the next election.''
   Unofficial totals showed Daley finishing with 55 percent of the
vote, to 43 percent for Evans and 3 percent for Republican Edward
Vrdolyak.
   Daley was helped to victory Tuesday by overwhelming white
support, low black turnout, and clear majorities among liberal,
lakefront voters and Hispanics.
</TEXT>
