<FIRST>r a PM-Brother'sKilling     04-06 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Brother's Killing,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>12-Year-Old To Be Tried As Adult in Brother's Strangulation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 12-year-old girl who told police
she was overwhelmed by her baby-sitting duties will be tried as an
adult in the strangling of her 2-year-old brother and choking of
her 15-month-old sister.
   A Broward County grand jury indicted fifth-grader Arva Betts as
an adult on charges of second-degree murder and aggravated child
abuse. The grand jury could have sent the case to juvenile court.
   Her lawyer said Arva's age and the fact that she had no history
of violent behavior and no criminal record should have supported a
juvenile charge.
   ``We're disappointed and shocked that the grand jury decided to
indict her,'' said attorney Johnny McCray Jr. ``There was little if
any evidence put on to support trying her as an adult.''
   Investigators were initially baffled when Arva's mother, Sally
Butterfield, woke up the morning of March 14 and found Andrew
Caesar dead and his sister, Tiffany Caesar, injured at their home
in nearby Wilton Manors.
   Arva, who was 11 years old at the time, was taken into custody
when it was determined that Andrew had been strangled.
   Police said the child confessed to the attack and said she was
overwhelmed by the responsibility of watching her half brother and
half sister from when she got home from school until 11 at night.
Her mother worked two jobs to support the family.
   Tiffany is hospitalized in critical condition at Memorial
Hospital in Hollywood. Doctors say she could be permanently
disabled.
   Arva remained at the county's Juvenile Detention Center
Wednesday night and was to be transferred today to the Broward
County Jail. But McCray said he would ask the court to let her
remain in the custody of the state Department of Health and
Rehabilitative Services.
   ``Society would not benefit by placing her among adults,''
McCray said.
   No charges have been filed against Ms. Butterfield, but Casey
said she is being investigated by Health and Rehabilitative
Services officials for possible neglect charges.
</TEXT>
