<HEAD>Radio Moscow Reports Legalization of Polish Union Activity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio Moscow's English-language service today
reported on the legalization of trade unions in Poland and an alert
listener could realize that the free trade union movement
Solidarity was included.
   The news report said Solidarity had taken part in the two-month
round-table talks, which concluded Wednesday with the signing of
historic accords that reinstates Solidarity after a seven-year ban.
   Radio Moscow said the talks had produced a number of political
agreements including one ``which states trade union pluralism.''
   The announcer said the participants also agreed on
``establishment of a two-chamber parliament and the post of a
president with broad powers.'' It said nothing about the
government's agreement to allow the first free elections since the
postwar Communist takeover.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass reported that the talks had
ended, without giving the results. The brief announcement did,
however, mention that Solidarity chairman Lech Walesa had taken
part.
   Soviet media have reported on many of the reforms in Eastern
Europe in the past eight months, but typically days or weeks after
the event.
