<FIRST>r a PM-ThinBlueLine     04-06 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Thin Blue Line,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Who Led Fight Against Adams' Release Is Fired</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor who tried to keep a man imprisoned
after his conviction in a police killing was overturned has been
fired. His boss cited policy conflicts for the dismissal.
   Assistant District Attorney Winfield Scott is the third
prosector involved in the case of Randall Dale Adams to leave the
office this week.
   ``I found we had a conflict regarding current office policies
that simply could not be resolved any other way,'' said Dallas
County District Attorney John Vance. He would not elaborate on
Wednesday's firing.
   Scott did not return repeated calls from The Associated Press.
Other officials at the office declined comment.
   Over Scott's objections, Adams was released from a Texas prison
March 22, less than a month after a state court overturned his
conviction for the 1976 slaying of a Dallas police officer.
   Adams spent more than 12 years in prison. His case was
chronicled in the documentary ``The Thin Blue Line,'' in which a
key prosecution witness recanted his testimony that Adams was the
triggerman.
   Adams' attorney, Randy Schaffer, said Wednesday that Scott's
actions were deplorable but added that he was being made a
scapegoat for following the office's ``marching orders.''
   Scott, who served as assistant district attorny in Dallas for 21
years, participated in the original prosecution of Adams and helped
choose a jury for the 1977 trial.
   In fighting Adams' release, Scott said state District Court
Judge Larry Baraka and eight of the nine appellate judges were
``liberal'' and biased in Adams' favor. He asked that Baraka be
removed from the case.
   The day after Adams' release, Vance said there wasn't enough
credible evidence to retry him, and the murder charge was dropped.
At the time, Vance said he would investigate Scott's behavior as a
personnel matter.
   Earlier this week, prosecutors John Creuzot and Leslie McFarlane
left, saying they were going into private practice. Both had been
with the office about six years and had worked on the Adams' case.
</TEXT>
