<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed in a narrow range in quiet
European trading late this morning, and dealers said they expected
the U.S. currency to remain stable until Friday's release of the
U.S. unemployment report for March.
   Gold prices also were mixed, rising in Europe but falling in
Hong Kong.
   The opening of the U.S. market might cause a ripple through the
market later today, but no major changes were expected until after
Friday's 1:30 p.m. release of the latest U.S. unemployment
statistics, dealers said.
   One Rome trader said the dollar was ``still well bid, but the
underlying sentiment is fundamentally neutral.''
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.78 yen to a closing 132.15 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 132.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8700 West German marks, up from 1.8695
   _1.6410 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395
   _6.3115 French francs, down from 6.3150
   _2.1103 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1125
   _1,371.80 Italian lire, down from 1,372.50
   _1.1925 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1895
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.7015, compared with
$1.7028 Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $383.50 a troy ounce,
unchanged from late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $384.20.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $383.60, up from $383.35 bid late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.86 to close at a bid $385.56.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.82 a troy
ounce, down from Wednesday's $5.83.
</TEXT>
