<FIRST>r i PM-Burundi-Libya     04-06 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Burundi-Libya,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burundi Expels All Libyans, Severes Diplomatic Ties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burundi has broken diplomatic relations
with Libya and given Libyans until Friday to leave the country,
Radio Burundi announced.
   The state-controlled radio said the tiny, land-locked central
Africa nation also has recalled its diplomats from Libya, which
early this year granted asylum to ousted Burundi President
Jean-Batiste Bagaza.
   ``The decision was reached because of Libya's involvement in
activities which undermine our security ...,'' state-owned radio
quoted Foreign Minister Cyprian Mbonimpa as saying.
   ``In recent days, Libyan diplomats are turning out in a
destabilizing campaign, which has seriously compromised peace and
unity in our country,'' the radio said without elaboration.
   The broadcast, monitored Wednesday night in Uganda's capital,
Kampala, said the decision to break ties with Libya was reached by
the Military Commitee for National Salvation in an emergency
meeting Wednesday.
   The meeting was led by President Pierre Buyoya, who formed the
committee after ousting Bagaza in a bloodless coup in October 1987.
   A Burundian diplomat in Kampala, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the expulsion order affected between 70 and 80
Libyans.
   A statement by the Libyan Foreign Ministry, carried by the JANA
news agency and monitored in Rome, said Libya was ``astonished ...
and considers this decision unjustified.''
   It said the allegations were false and the result of
``reactionary and colonialist pressures'' on the Burundi
government. It did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
