<SECOND>PM-Brussels-Imam Threat,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Replaced Brussels' Slain Imam Threatend, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new spiritual leader of Moslems in
Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg _ whose predecessor was
slain in Brussels' main mosque _ has received death threats, police
said today.
   ``We are taking this very seriously,'' a police official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the threats that Imam
Samir Rahdi received over the telephone apparently stemmed from his
moderate views.
   The previous imam, Abdullah Ahdal, was killed along with his
librarian after Ahdal failed to support the death sentence
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini issued Feb. 14 against author Salman
Rushdie for his novel ``The Satanic Verses,'' which some claim
insults Islam. Ahdal also had received threats.
   Like Ahdal, Rahdi is a Saudi national. Ahdal also was a former
student of Rahdi's. ``It is somewhat logical that there are new
threats since he has the same views as his predecessor,'' the
police official said.
   The official would not specify when the threats were made. But
Belgian newspapers reported they were made in calls on Saturday and
Tuesday.
   On Friday, a pro-Iran fundamentalist group in Beirut claimed
responsibility for the murders. The group, Soldiers of Justice,
said it carried out ``God's verdict'' by killing the imam and his
librarian, Salim Behir.
   Both were shot in the head and neck from close range. Security
around Brussels' main mosque was increased after the latest
threats, police said.
</TEXT>
