<FIRST>r a PM-ElderlyCrimefighter     04-06 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly Crimefighter,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Octogenarian Wards Off Intruder With Revolver</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 81-year-old widow who chased an intruder
from her back door by firing at him twice with a revolver says she
fears for her safety and wants police to return her gun.
   Police said Wednesday that Annie Ryan heard a noise on her porch
Monday night, called police, and then went to investigate. As she
opened the door, the stranger forced it open and pushed her
backward.
   Mrs. Ryan retreated to her bedroom and retrieved the Smith &amp;
Wesson five-shot revolver from under her pillow. She told police
that when the gunman advanced, she aimed at the floor and fired the
gun to frighten him.
   She said she fired a second shot as he headed out the back door,
nicking the corner of the door frame, said Sgt. Robert Orlowski.
   Mrs. Ryan said the intruder stopped in the backyard, turned
toward her, and asked her how many bullets she had left. Police
then arrived and the intruder fled on foot, Orlowski said.
   ``When the officers came in, she was still holding the weapon
with two spent rounds and three live rounds in it,'' Orlowski said.
``They took the gun from her.''
   Police said they believe the gun is unregistered. If it turns
out to be a legal weapon, they'll return it to her and if not, they
may allow her to register it, police said.
   Mrs. Ryan says she needs her gun back for protection.
   ``What could I have done if I didn't have it? You can see what
could happen. I want my gun back,'' Mrs. Ryan said. She has lived
in the inner-city neighborhood since 1952, and said the gun
belonged to her husband, who died in 1979.
   Mrs. Ryan said she thought she hit the intruder with one shot.
Police found no blood at the scene, but were investigating whether
a man treated at a hospital early Tuesday could have been the
suspect.
</TEXT>
