<FIRST>r a PM-Police-Gays     04-06 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Police-Gays,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Booking Form Asks Question About Homosexuality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The form filled out by police when booking
suspects includes a question about whether the arrested person is
homosexual, a newspaper reported today.
   The 41-line form includes questions about a person's physical
description and the presence of distinguishing marks such as
tattoos. In a section on ``other identifying data,'' the form
includes a box for checking marked ``homosexual.''
   New York Newsday said it obtained a copy of the form from a
staff member of the Legal Aid Society in Brooklyn. The matter
became an issue as a result of arrests last week at a demonstration
for increased AIDS funding.
   A police spokesman, Sgt. John Clifford, said the form is meant
to gather information.
   ``No one is obligated to answer these questions,'' he said.
``It's certainly not intended to be discriminatory.''
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said the question violated the constitutional
right to privacy.
   He said he would demand that Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward
order the question on homosexuality removed and that police stop
asking suspects about their sexuality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
