<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0916EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-China     04-06 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Twaiwan To Send Official Delegation To China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taiwan will send an official delegation to
China for the first time to attend the annual meeting of the Asian
Development Bank in Beijing next month, the government announced
today.
   The government said the 12-member delegation will be led by
Finance Minister Shirley Kuo and will include officials from the
Finance Ministry, the Foreign Ministry and government-owned banks.
   The decision, taken by the government Cabinet at a regular
weekly meeting, was regarded as another step in a new Nationalist
inititive to counter Communist China's efforts to isolate Taiwan
internationally.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, Chen Yu-chu, told reporters the
Cabinet's decision did not signal a change in government policies
toward China. He said Taiwan would continue to oppose official
contacts with the rival communists who won a civil war in 1949,
forcing the Nationalists to flee to Taiwan.
   Chen said the delegation would not discuss relations between the
rival governments and that the Cabinet decided to approve the trip
because the annual meeting was being organized by the Asian
Development Bank and not Beijing.
   He said the delegation would attend the three-day meeting, which
begins on May 4, to ensure that Taiwan could ``actively
participate'' in the development bank and also to fulfill Taiwan's
obligations as a founding member of the bank.
   Chang Chung-tung, history professor at the National Taiwan
University, described the government's decision as ``a major
breakthrough'' and said it could lead to further flexibility toward
the mainland.
   He said it was probably intended to pressure the Chinese
communists to accept de facto Nationalist rule over this island.
   The Nationalists continue to claim they are the legitimate
government of all China, and have maintained a policy of no
contacts, no talks, no compromise toward communist China since
their defeat on the China mainland.
   But in the past year, the Nationalists have relaxed their policy
on private contacts between Taiwanese and mainland Chinese and have
allowed an exchange of visits, trade and cultural ties.
   The Asian Development Bank was founded in 1966 to help regional
development. The 47-member organization voted in 1986 to admit
China and changed Taiwan's membership name from the Republic of
China _ the official Nationalist name _ to Taipei, China.
   Nationalist officials protested then, saying the change
relegated Taiwan to a provincial government under China. The
Nationalists boycotted the development bank's annual meetings in
1986 and 1987 but attended last year's meeting in Manila, the
Philippines, where the bank has its headquarters.
   Chen said the Nationalists are still opposed to the Taipei,
China designation. He said the Nationalists would continue to
negotiate with the bank to work out a compromise solution
acceptable to both parties.
   Since the 1970s, Taiwan has been virtually isolated
diplomatically. It is now recognized by only 23 nations, while most
other countries recognize the mainland government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
