<FIRST>r a PM-TalentBank     04-06 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Talent Bank,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Koch Admits Mistakes Made In Hiring But Numbers Small</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Edward I. Koch told a state commission
investigating charges of patronage in city hiring that some
apparently improper procedures amounted to ``peanuts'' when
compared to the city's overall hiring system.
   Koch appeared Wednesday before a commission studying claims that
the Talent Bank, a clearinghouse for city job applicants, was used
to award city jobs to politically connected people.
   The State Commission on Government Integrity has heard testimony
that the Talent Bank had become a patronage operation, contrary to
Koch's intent.
   Koch said the commission's hearings had created the impression
``that there is massive patronage in my administration and that
this massive patronage was hidden behind a `sham' affirmative
action program.''
   ``These charges are false,'' he said.
   Koch called the number of Talent Bank jobs filled under
questionable circumstances from 1983 to 1986 ``peanuts.''
   The Talent Bank placed about 3,000 people in jobs, most paying
less than $20,000 a year.
   ``If I had wanted to have a massive patronage program, I could
have,'' Koch said. ``But I did not want to have, nor did I have, a
patronage operation.''
   In his defense, Koch said testimony had described practices at
the Talent Bank that he would not have approved. Those practices
involved only a part of the Talent Bank's job referral services _
the laborers, deck hands and ferry agents at two agencies, he said.
   ``And the Talent Bank itself was and is a very small part of the
city's hiring program,'' he said.
   Commission Chairman John D. Feerick asked the mayor if he had
failed in his responsibilities because he wasn't aware, among other
things, that the Talent Bank computer listed applicants by who
their political sponsor was; that documents were destroyed to hide
this fact; that job postings were waived so they could be filled
with political appointees.
   Koch said he could only review the city's 42 agencies by
checking results, not by watching day-to-day operations.
   Feerick said the commission would deliver a report to the
governor sometime in May.
   The commission was appointed by Gov. Mario M. Cuomo to
investigate corruption and inefficiency in state and municipal
governments. The commission cannot prosecute but can report its
findings to prosecutors and suggest legislation.
</TEXT>
