<FIRST>r w PM-Ozone-Radiation     04-06 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ozone-Radiation,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Increase in Radiation in Antarctic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Potentially dangerous ultraviolet radiation
streamed through the south polar ozone hole during the antarctic
spring at levels not usually reached until months later, the
National Science Foundation reports.
   While few people reside in Antarctica to be threatened by the
potential for skin cancer and other damage from the radiation,
scientists fear the rise there could presage conditions in other
areas of the world.
   The increased ultraviolet radiation was measured at the United
States' Palmer Station last September through December _ spring in
that part of the world, the foundation reported Wednesday.
   ``This is the first measurement of a clearly significant
enhancement in UV radiation reaching the ground that is linked to
human impact on the ozone layer,'' reported John E. Frederick of
the University of Chicago.
   Scientists there have been studying radiation levels because of
concerns about the depletion in the amount of ozone in the
atmosphere high above the Antarctic. That depletion has come to be
known as an ``ozone hole'' in recent years.
   Ozone, which helps filter out dangerous radiation from the sun,
is damaged by man-made chemicals, and the fear has risen that if it
is depeleted over other parts of the earth, rates of skin cancer
could rise and plants and other animals could also be damaged.
   The antarctic ozone depletion is usually at its worst in the
September-December period, a time when there is generally only
little sunligbt reaching that part of the world.
   Even so, the scientists found that rates of ultraviolet
radiation reaching the ground were typical of those usually found
in mid-summer in that region, a time of much more intense sunlight.
   The researchers are hoping to determine if the changes in
radiation will affect the food chain in the region. Ultraviolet
radiation can kill plankton, which form the basis of the food chain
in the ocean, but the effect diminishes with the depth of the water.
   Early indications were that there was no immediate threat, the
researchers said, but they plan to continue their studies.
   In a parallel experiment last fall, scientists working over the
north polar region determined that an ozone hole has not appeared
there, but they said conditions are ripe for depletion of the
protective gas in that region also.
   A northern ozone hole could pose a much greater threat, since
the bulk of the world's population lives in the northern hemisphere.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
