<FIRST>u i PM-Korea-Spring 2ndLd-Writethru a0428 04-06 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Spring, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0428,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protests Continue In Korea After Crackdown On Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with protests, Roh meeting. No pickup.
^By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers and radical students
demonstrated for the seventh straight day today to protest the
police assault that broke a strike at South Korea's largest
shipyard. At least 12 people were reported arrested.
   Government officials said the unrest in Ulsan was becoming a
showdown between authorities and ``labor movement forces,'' and
President Roh Tae-woo met with security officials to discuss the
protest.
   ``The most urgent task facing us now is to safeguard the
nation's free democratic system from leftist forces,'' Roh told the
meeting at the presidential residence in Seoul.
   In Ulsan, 150 miles southwest of the capital, hundreds of
striking workers hurled rocks and firebombs at police in the
streets around the strike-plagued Hyundai shipyard, news reports
said. Police responded with tear gas, they said.
   The news reports said 2,000 striking workers demonstrated.
   In the last two days, about 200 police, workers and citizens
were injured in the street battles, the news agency Yonhap said. It
said a house and 38 cars were burned by firebombs thrown by
striking workers.
   Protests broke out after police raided the shipyard March 30,
arresting 700 workers and ending a strike that had left 400 people
injured since Dec. 12. Most of those arrested were released, but
formal charges have been filed against 10 union leaders.
   About 3,000 police guarded the shipyard. Company officials said
60 percent of the shipyard's 19,500 employees reported to work.
   Police today arrested about a dozen strikers who attacked
non-striking workers on their way to work, Yonhap said. Hundreds of
police were deployed around residential areas to protect
non-striking workers, it said.
   ``The government's authority is being tested, and we will not
back down,'' said a senior government official in Seoul.
   The three main opposition parties dispatched investigative teams
to Ulsan today to look into the situation. Before departure, they
urged the government to stop using forceful means and try to settle
the problem through dialogue.
   Prosecutor-general Kim Gi-chun today called for stern measures
to stop violent protests and said the government was prepared for a
``major showdown'' with leftist groups.
   On Wednesday, the government ordered an investigatation of 25
leading dissident and labor groups which have either sought contact
with North Korea for talks on national unification or spearheaded
anti-government rallies.
</TEXT>
