<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1006EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-FarmScene 1stLd-Writethru a0462 04-06 0927</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Farm Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0462,880</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tentative Projection Shows 35 Percent Wheat Crop Boost</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS date from May 1 to June 1 in 9th graf, Despite the,
and 11th graf, As a.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``highly tentative'' projection by the
Agriculture Department shows that 1989 wheat production could be
about 2.45 billion bushels, a 35 percent boost from last year's
drought-shriveled harvest.
   If the harvest turns out to be that much, it would be the
largest U.S. wheat output since 1984, when production was almost
2.6 billion bushels.
   Wheat production dropped in later years as tighter acreage
restrictions were imposed to help curb rising grain surpluses. And
drought took its toll last year as production dropped to 1.81
billion bushels.
   Suddenly, once-large grain inventories were drained off and
market prices rose. The USDA eased planting requirements for 1989
and is looking at possible adjustments for next year.
   The department's Agricultural Stabilization and Conservation
Service has published a ``preliminary regulatory analysis'' of the
current wheat situation to help plan the 1990 program, including
some fresh projections for this year.
   ``The forecasts for the 1989 crop year are highly tentative,''
the report said. ``Production forecasts are subject to wide
variability at this time because winter wheat has not been
harvested and spring wheat has not been planted.''
   Despite such vagaries, the agency's report projected the 1989
wheat acreage for harvest at 65.5 million acres, up nearly a fourth
from 53.2 million acres harvested in 1988. That would be the
largest acreage since 1984 when 66.9 million were harvested.
   The average yield per acre harvested was projected at 37.4
bushels, up from 34 bushels in 1988. That would produce a total
wheat crop this year of 2.45 billion bushels.
   Despite the boost in production, it would leave total U.S. wheat
supplies in the 1989-90 marketing year that will begin June 1 at
only 3 billion bushels, about what they were in the current year.
   Total wheat use in the year ahead was projected at 2.47 billion
bushels, or still more than this the 1989 harvest.
   As a result, the wheat carryover a year from now _ on June 1,
1990 _ would be around 534 million bushels, or the same as it is
expected to be this June 1.
   The report projected the farm price of wheat to average $3.65
per bushel over the 1989-90 marketing year, down 10 cents from a
forecast of $3.75 for the current year.
   Analysts said the projections take into account severe drought
in Kansas where wheat production is expected to be cut sharply this
year.
   Other USDA insider estimates of Kansas wheat production are
ranging from about 190 million bushels to as much as 315 million
bushels this year, compared with 323 million bushels produced in
1988 and a 1986-88 annual average of 342 million.
   Kansas wheat farmers planted 12.4 million acres last fall, up
sharply from 10.2 million planted for the 1988 crop.
   According to one set of jottings, abandonment because of dry
weather might reduce this year's harvest to 10.5 million acres, in
which case yields could average 30 bushels per acre _ a total state
output of 315 million bushels.
   Under another ``scenario,'' however, the Kansas crop might be
reduced to 9.9 million harvested acres, a yield of 25 bushels and a
total output of 250 million bushels. The worst case version calls
for 9.3 million acres harvested, an average of 20 bushels per acre
and a total harvest of 190 million bushels.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department plans to step up
purchases of pork for donation to schools and other institutions to
help bolster sagging hog prices paid to farmers.
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter said Wednesday the
department ``not only has bought more pork this year, but it also
has bought a greater variety of pork items than in prior years.''
   Frozen hams and canned pork are the main items bought by USDA
for distribution to schools and other domestic feeding programs. In
addition, the department soon will begin buying canned luncheon
meat, including pork, he said.
   Farmers have marketed ``unusually high'' numbers of hogs in
recent months, which have helped depress market prices, Yeutter
said. Since last July 1, the beginning of the current purchasing
year, USDA has spent more than $96 million for pork, compared with
$30 million the previous year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the Soviet
Union has bought an additional 200,000 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery this year under a long-term supply agreement.
   More than 2.3 million tons have been purchased since the Soviets
resumed buying U.S. corn on March 28 after a layoff of almost three
months.
   The corn is scheduled for delivery by Sept. 30, the end of the
sixth year of a long-term grain supply agreement between the Soviet
Union and the United States.
   Officials said Wednesday the latest sales brought total corn
sold to the Soviets for 1988-89 to more than 12.5 million tons.
Additionally, sales include 4 million tons of wheat, 450,000 tons
of soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal, and 507,400 tons of
grain sorghum.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 200,000 tons of
corn would be about 7.9 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.46 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the latest USDA five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $20 million.
</TEXT>
