<FIRST>r a PM-SoCalHeat     04-06 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SoCal Heat,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Letup in Record Heat Blistering Southern California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of thousands of city dwellers
seeking to escape from a record heat wave found the beaches too hot
to handle. Even Death Valley had cooler readings.
   ``It's hotter than sin,'' said Seal Beach lifeguard Steve
Cushman. ``People are even jumping into the showers with their
clothes on out here.''
   And forecasters said there's more heat ahead.
   Wednesday's 105 degrees at the Los Angeles Civic Center
surpassed by a whopping 15 degrees the record of 90 for April 5,
set in 1971. It was the hottest reading ever posted in April,
breaking the 100-degree mark set April 23, 1910, and tied on
Tuesday.
   Forecasters said today's predicted high of 102 degrees downtown
will easily eclipse the record 91-degree peak set April 6, 1939.
   The spring heat wave was spawned by a high-pressure system
expected to linger over the West for several more days, said
National Weather Service forecaster Michael Lewis.
   More than 250,000 people fled to the beach Wednesday seeking
relief from the spell of arid weather, but mercury levels topping
100 degrees wilted the throng of cool-seekers on the sun-roasted
sands.
   It was cooler in the desert, but not by much. The mercury hit
103 in Death Valley and 104 in Palm Springs.
   The suburban community of Ontario registered the nation's
highest temperature, with a sizzling 109 degrees.
   Electricity consumption _ 14,282 megawatts at 4 p.m. Wednesday _
was the highest ever for an April day, but still shy of the peak
15,987 megawatts used on Sept. 6, 1988, when the temperature
downtown was 110 degrees, said Paul Klein of Southern California
Edison.
   Despite the moisture-sapping heat, the Los Angeles County Fire
Department said the wildfire season was still months away because
hillsides were still green from winter rains.
</TEXT>
