<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru   04-06 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0486,0562</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Ignore Truce, Reportedly Attack Three Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with missile attacks on Afghan cities.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas today ignored a
cease-fire declared by the government and fired missiles and
rockets at Kabul and three other cities, witnesses and the
government said.
   A missile blew up a fuel truck parked near a petroleum tank
depot on the northern edge of Kabul. Several trucks parked nearby
also exploded.
   A cloud of black smoke, visible over the city of 2 million,
drifted from the site. There was no immediate word on casualties.
   An Afghan truck driver who said he was part of a convoy hauling
fuel down the Salang Highway from Hayratan, on the Soviet border,
said guerrillas tried to hijack some of the trucks a few miles
north of Kabul.
   The driver, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
hijackers got about a mile before they were attacked by two
government helicopters.
   The Foreign Ministry said guerrillas fired rockets and cannons
at the cities of Jalalabad, Kandahar and Sarobi. Ministry spokesman
Mohammad Nabi Amani said government troops held their fire. He had
no information on casualties.
   His report could not be confirmed.
   Kabul's military command announced a unilateral cease-fire
Wednesday night on the eve of Ramadan, the Islamic holy month.
   President Najib told the British Broadcasting Corp. that the
government would retaliate with renewed force if the U.S.-backed
guerrillas broke the cease-fire.
   Amani said guerrillas fired 32 rockets and cannon rounds today
at the southern city of Kandahar, where government forces have been
besieged for the past year.
   Fewer than 100 rounds were fired at Jalalabad, he said. In the
past two weeks, the government has accused the guerrillas of firing
as many as 12,000 rounds a day at the city, which is 75 miles east
of Kabul.
   Amani said he had no indication how many rounds were fired at
Sarobi, midway between Kabul and Jalalabad.
   The Ramadan cease-fire was at least the fifth unilateral
cessation of hostilities declared by Najib since January 1987. None
has succeeded.
   The guerrillas have ignored every government-declared
cease-fire, and the government itself usually quickly follows suit.
   Amani said Foreign Minister Abdul Wakil, who left Kabul on
Monday, still was waiting for a U.S. visa in Moscow. He wants to
appeal to the United Nations to hold a special Security Council
session on the Afghan fighting.
   On Wednesday, guerrilla rockets slammed into downtown Kabul,
killing six people and wounding 23, a government official said on
condition of anonymity.
   Official Radio Kabul said 10 people were killed and 39 wounded.
   Most of the Afghan guerrillas are based in Pakistan. They have
received support from the United States, China, Pakistan, Saudi
Arabia and other countries in their decade-old war against the
Soviet Union's protege government in Kabul. The Red Army ended its
nine-year involvement in Afghanistan Feb. 15, but Moscow is still
supplying the Najib government.
   Wednesday's rockets spewed shrapnel and debris as they hit a
small park next to the Kabul Hotel and a commercial district
several blocks away. The rockets, which landed four to 10 blocks
from the Foreign Ministry, were fired before noon, when sidewalks
and marketplaces are crowded with pedestrians.
</TEXT>
