<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0524 04-06 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0524,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Dies of Gunshot Wound; Shamir Reported Considering Withdrawal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Palestinian dying, details on shooting,
army saying two wounded. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian died today of a gunshot wound
sustained in earlier violence, and an Israeli soldier shot and
critically wounded a teen-age protester in Bethlehem, witnesses and
Arab news reports said.
   Six other Palestinians _ a woman and five teen-agers _ were
reportedly wounded in two other clashes in Israeli-occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israel's army said it was checking the reports.
   An Israeli newspaper reported from Washington, meanwhile, that
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir may order a withdrawal of troops from
some of the heavily populated areas in the occupied territories.
   Israeli editorial writers responded with satisfaction to results
of Shamir's meeting Wednesday with Secretary of State James A.
Baker III, who called the Israeli leader's peace ideas ``very
encouraging.''
   Editors wrote it was an indication Shamir's meeting today with
President Bush would not turn into a confrontation.
   In the West Bank village of Deir Salah, 200 Palestinians
chanting ``PLO! Israel No!'' followed the coffin of Salem Ismail
Salah, 27. Arab reports and doctors at Jerusalem's Mukassed
Hospital, where he died today, said Salah was shot in the head
during a March 30 clash with troops.
   In Bethlehem, reporters said they saw a soldier shoot and
critically wound a 17-year-old Palestinian. The incident began when
100 Palestinians threw stones and empty bottles near Manger Square,
the reporters said.
   Four soldiers arrived, chased fleeing demonstrators and fired
live ammunition at them, according to the reporters.
   One soldier ran after Nassar, knelt on the ground, took aim and
shot the youth twice from about 40 yards away, the reporters said.
Mukassed Hospital doctors said the youth was critically wounded.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, a 38-year-old woman and a
17-year-old boy were shot and wounded when troops opened fire on a
protest against Israeli occupation. ``Shamir is no good!'' some
youths shouted.
   Troops also wounded four teen-age boys in the arms and legs when
they opened fire on stone-throwing protesters at Khan Yunis refugee
camp in Gaza Strip, Arab reports said. The army said it wounded two
youths there.
   Arab reports said other confrontations occurred in Gaza City and
the West Bank city of Hebron, but there were no injuries.
   The violence occurred a day after the army freed 465 Palestinian
prisoners as a goodwill gesture for the Moslem month of Ramadan,
which starts tonight.
   The releases also coincided with Shamir's talks in Washington on
reviving the Middle East peace process.
   Hadashot newspaper reported the prime minister was considering
three other moves to satisfy U.S. demands for eased tensions. One
possibility is ``a symbolic withdrawal of Israeli forces from
several heavily concentrated population centers,'' it said, adding
this did not mean a full pullback.
   Two other gestures included opening West Bank schools shut
through most of the uprising and freezing deportation orders
against 13 Palestinians.
   Since the uprising began in December 1987, Israel has deported
to Lebanon 45 Palestinians accused of inciting riots. The United
States had condemned such expulsions. At least 420 Palestinians
have been killed in the rebellion. Eighteen Israelis also have died.
</TEXT>
