<FIRST>r a PM-Fraternity-Nazi     04-06 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fraternity-Nazi,0206</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fraternity Charged In Nazi Uniform Incident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Trinity University fraternity has been
charged with violating the school's anti-hazing policy after a
Jewish pledge wore a Nazi uniform on campus.
   Representatives of the Triniteers fraternity have a week to
defend the practice before a dean. If found guilty, penalties could
involve revocation of the fraternity's charter, mandatory community
service or probation limiting the fraternity's social activities.
   The president of the fraternity, Pete Sturdivant, said the
incident ``is being blown completely out of proportion'' and that
punishment is not warranted.
   The student, Andy Ellenthal, dressed as a Nazi soldier with a
swastika armband on March 30 as part of a fraternity tradition
requiring pledges to wear costumes. He did not wear the costume to
class.
   Ellenthal, 18, said he selected and purchased the outfit
himself, adding that it was intended only as a joke.
   After the matter is resolved, dean Coleen Grissom intends to
bring together fraternity and sorority members, professors and
other students to discuss the implications of the incident.
   ``She wants to convey that certain images and symbols are
unacceptable,'' Trinity spokeswoman Sharon Jones said.
   The independent-religious college has about 2,700 students.
</TEXT>
