<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1059EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FilmFlap     04-06 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Film Flap,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>High School Principal Suspended Over Nude Film Demands Reinstatement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palisades Park principal has been
suspended by the school board for allowing a movie with nudity to
be filmed at his high school two years ago.
   Nicholas S. Rotonda said Wednesday that the suspension was
``political'' and demanded to be reinstated.
   Rotonda was suspended Saturday for letting New York-based
Upfront Productions use the school to make a movie that shows
actresses, posing as teachers and students, briefly exposing their
breasts.
   Rotonda said the district school board had approved the movie,
``Senior Week,'' which the filmmakers had told him would be a spoof
on spring break. He said the movie, made in the summer of 1987, was
filmed on weekends and at night when he was not present to
supervise.
   The school board has denied knowing anything about the agreement
with the movie company.
   Dozens of students marched Monday at Palisades Park High School
to protest Rotonda's suspension, and teachers approved a resolution
backing him and calling for his reinstatement.
   The existence of the film was made public a few days before
Tuesday's school board election in which a board president opposed
by Rotonda was seeking re-election. Board President Janette
Zuckerman and five of her supporters were defeated in the balloting
to fill six vacant seats on the nine-member board.
   ``I'm just trying to get my name cleared at the moment and have
them put me back in the school,'' said Rotonda, 51, who has been
principal at the high school for six years. ``They lost the
election. Let's just get back to business.''
   ``As a result of a political battle I was being used as a
scapegoat,'' Rotonda said. He said he was denied due process and
was considering what action to take with his lawyer.
   School Superintendent George Fasciano, who suspended Rotonda
until the board could meet and investigate the matter, was in the
hospital Wednesday and unavailable for comment.
   Ms. Zuckerman, vice president of the board when the film was
made, said she asked to have Rotonda suspended after finding his
name on an agreement with Upfront Productions that the school board
knew nothing about.
</TEXT>
