<FIRST>r w PM-FCCChairman 1stLd-Writethru a0463 04-06 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FCC Chairman, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0463,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Departing Chairman Patrick Says Deregulation Will Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs graf 13, James Billingsley, to CORRECT Billingsley's title.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dennis R. Patrick says the deregulatory
approach he took toward the broadcasting and telephone industries
during his two years as head of the Federal Communications
Commission will continue after his departure.
   Patrick, who on Wednesday announced his resignation from the
commission, said there was no discussion of a possible successor
when he turned in his resignation at the White House the previous
day. He said he was not pressured to leave his post.
   Among those mentioned as possible replacements was Sherrie
Marshall, a former Patrick aide who was on loan to the White House
during the unsuccessful confirmation proceedings for Defense
Secretary-designate John Tower.
   Washington attorneys Susan Wing and Jim Smith also have been
mentioned, along with Alfred Sikes, head of the Commerce
Department's National Telecommunications and Information
Administration.
   At a news conference, Patrick said he was confident the next FCC
chairman would carry on an agenda seeking deregulation. He said
there would be ``no substantial slowing of progress.''
   ``It is not a static (telecommunications) market and the
regulatory response will not be static,'' he said.
   Patrick thanked President Bush ``for his continuing support''
despite rumors he had been on the skids since Bush took office.
Calling his resignation ``absolutely voluntary,'' Patrick said,
``The White House has been absolutely supportive of me since day
one.''
   Patrick said he would return to private industry but would
remain in his job until a replacement was named. The 37-year-old
former California attorney said he has no plans, has conducted no
job interviews and would not excuse himself from any pending FCC
decisions.
   Until he leaves the FCC, ``it will be business as usual,''
Patrick said.
   ``We have accomplished substantially all'' his agenda, and now
``I desire and am very anxious to return to the private sector.''
   One of Patrick's congressional foes, Rep. Edward Markey,
D-Mass., said he looked forward to a better ``balance'' between
consumer and business interests under a new FCC chairman. He said
deregulation under Patrick had turned into ``deregulation for
deregulation's sake.''
   But Patrick was praised widely by industry representatives.
   James Billingsley, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.'s senior
vice president _ federal regulation, said Patrick ``has been an
enthusiastic and forceful proponent of fundamental changes in
regulation that will greatly serve the public interest and our
industry long after he has left the commission.''
   Edward O. Fritts, president of the National Association of
Broadcasters, said Patrick was ``a man of principle and dedication
who has made his mark on communications policy.''
   William L. Weiss, chairman of the Ameritech phone company, said
he was ``optimistic a successor will be selected who will build on
Mr. Patrick's contributions to a progressive regulatory framework
for the information age.''
   Patrick was named to the FCC by then-President Reagan in 1983,
after working in the White House personnel office, and was named
chairman, succeeding Mark S. Fowler, in April 1987.
   Among his major accomplishments, Patrick successfully proposed
the change in the way long-distance rates are set by AT&amp;T and led
the FCC's repeal of the Fairness Doctrine, which required
broadcasters to air opposing views on controversial issues.
   Under Patrick, the commission also has moved to change the way
broadcasters are licensed, guaranteed exclusive licenses to
syndicated TV programs, made a preliminary ruling on standards for
high-definition television and generally has followed the
deregulatory approach of the Reagan administration.
   The commission has been two members short of its normal
five-member complement since last year. Nominations to fill the two
vacant seats were held up because of Senate displeasure with
Patrick's policies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
