<FIRST>u a PM-PrisonCrowding     04-06 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prison Crowding,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Fined For Prison Overcrowding</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FLIPPEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today fined the state
$164,250 for prison overcrowding and ordered that the money be used
to set up a bail fund for indigent defendants.
   U.S. District Judge Raymond J. Pettine ruled the state was in
contempt of court for failing to limit to 250 the number of
prisoners awaiting trial in an intake unit.
   Overcrowding at Rhode Island's only jail for inmates awaiting
trial has been a problem for years, but mushroomed last year after
the Legislature passed laws allowing drug defendants to be held
without bail.
   The Corrections Department, under pressure from Pettine, opened
two annexes to the intake unit, but has been unable to keep up with
the exploding population. Construction of a new prison building has
been stalled by local opposition in Cranston, where the Adult
Correctional Institutions complex is located.
   Last fall, Pettine gave the state until Feb. 20 to reduce the
population at the intake unit to 250. As of Monday, the population
was 464, said Joseph A. DiNitto, state Corrections Department
spokesman.
   Pettine imposed fines of $50 per extra inmate per day from Feb.
20 to March 13, and said further fines up to $289,000 or more would
be imposed if necessary to meet his order to reduce crowding.
   ``I think that's just what was needed to ensure this problem is
taken care of,'' said Steven Brown, executive director of the Rhode
Island chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union. The ACLU sued
the state 13 years ago over prison conditions.
   Pettine ordered the state to turn over the money within 15 days
to the Corrections Department, but stayed the order to give state
officials a chance to appeal.
   DiNitto said he had not yet seen the ruling and would not
comment on it.
   The governor said the decision will be appealed.
   Pettine praised the state for submitting long-range plans to
alleviate overcrowding, but said the state should be fined because
it ignored options such as the bail fund proposed by the ACLU.
   Any prisoner being held on $5,000 or less cash bail will be
eligible to have bail paid by the fund. Pettine recommended that
maximum use be squeezed from the money by bailing first those
prisoners being held on $1,000 bail or less before those being held
on higher amounts.
   ``These pre-trial detainees are in jail only because they are
too poor to make bail,'' Pettine wrote.
</TEXT>
