<FIRST>r a PM-Navajos-MacDonald 1stLd-Writethru a0554 04-06 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navajos-MacDonald, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0554,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navajo Police Chief Ordered from Reservation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to CORRECT TO Kellogg, sted Kellog; Picks
up 6th graf, `In other ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDOW ROCK, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Navajo tribal judge has banned the
tribe's police chief from the reservation for failing to enforce
court orders related to embattled Chairman Peter MacDonald's
struggle to retain power.
   Window Rock District Judge Robert Yazzie signed an order
Wednesday excluding Police Chief Wilbur Kellogg from the
reservation pending a hearing on Monday.
   An anti-MacDonald majority of the Tribal Council has voted to
place MacDonald on leave, but the flamboyant head of the nation's
largest Indian tribe has resisted.
   ``For the last two months, I've just been a football back and
forth between the two factions,'' said Kellogg, who remained at his
office late Wednesday.
   Kellogg was found in contempt and fined $500 by the Tribal
Supreme Court earlier this week for having failed to enforce a
court order barring J. Tonny Bowman, an appointee of the
pro-MacDonald Advisory Council, from taking over Yazzie's court.
   In other developments Wednesday:
   _Tribal Controller Bobby White, confronted by 50 angry MacDonald
appointees and others, handed over 31 paychecks that had been
withheld by order of the anti-MacDonald majority of the Tribal
Council.
   _The general manager of tribal radio station KTNN said the
tribal attorney general's office told him in a memorandum that
MacDonald, because of a temporary restraining order issued by
tribal court, should not be allowed to use the station's air time
to make the weekly ``Chairman's Report.''
   KTNN General Manager Freddie Howard said the station would have
to disobey because of concerns about fairness, free speech and
Federal Communications Commission requirements. Howard said the
station would not drop either MacDonald's report or one made by
Leonard Haskie, the interim chairman selected by the Tribal Council.
   ``This borders on trying to censor somebody,'' Howard said.
``It's just like telling a newspaper what to print or what not to
print.''
   Howard also said, ``I can't allow politics to jeopardize our
good standing with the FCC. The issue isn't MacDonald or Haskie.''
   MacDonald was placed on paid administrative leave by the Tribal
Council after witnesses before a U.S. Senate committee testified he
received gifts and kickbacks in connection with tribal business
dealings.
   MacDonald, who has denied such wrongdoing, has maintained the
council's action was invalid and illegal. He has tried to retain
his authority by firing opponents and those who attempt to remain
neutral.
</TEXT>
