<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Election     04-06 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Election,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leningrad Officials Bemoan Election Rout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some Communist Party leaders in Leningrad blamed
psychological attacks and malicious press coverage for the
humiliating defeat of 12 city officials in last month's elections,
a newspaper reported Thursday.
   But others at a special meeting called to discuss the election
disaster said the party itself was responsible for the ``crisis of
confidence'' in its abilities, said Sovietskaya Rossiya, the
Russian republic's official party and government newspaper.
   The meeting, the first extraordinary session of the Leningrad
party organization in 30 years, came four days after some party
members demanded the resignation of the Leningrad leadership, the
newspaper said.
   Leningraders on March 26 rejected every one of local officials
running for seats in the Soviet Union's new parliament, the
newspaper said.
   Yuri Solovyev, a candidate member of the party's ruling
Politburo and regional party chief, ran unopposed and still lost
because more than half the voters crossed out his name on the
ballot. He characterized the results as ``depressing,'' Sovietskaya
Rossiya said.
   Sovietskaya Rossia said Tuesday's meeting ``occurred in an
atmosphere of openness, honesty and toughness of evaluation, and
impartial criticism, which we have dreamed about since the
beginning of perestroika.''
   The newspaper concluded that if such a meeting had occurred
previously, the party might not have suffered so in the elections.
   ``Leningraders are not satisfied with the tempo and path of
perestroika in the city,'' the newspaper quoted V.P. Smirnov as
saying. ``They don't feel that the leadership of the city defends
the interests of the population, of the working class or the
intelligentsia,'' said Smirnov, a radio controller and member of
the regional party leadership.
   Clearly, ``a crisis of confidence has been outlined,'' he said.
   But the newspaper said many speakers blamed the loss on
``malicious press, strongly creating a negative stereotype of the
party bureaucrats.''
   It listed four party leaders who ``spoke with alarm about the
psychological attack being carried out against the party. And isn't
it strange that some organs of the press united with forces which
are extremely far from the ideas of Marxism-Leninism.''
   The report did not give examples of what they regarded as
``malicious'' press coverage.
   ``We insufficiently evaluated the ideological prejudice and
bourgeois illusions which have been spreadly recently, and the
dissatisfaction of the people with the growth of the deficit,
inflation, crime, miscalculations in the organization of the
cooperative movement,'' the newspaper said, paraphrasing the four
officials.
   It identified the four as Y.A. Petrosyan, the director of an
institute; Y.A. Sidorenko, an official of Leningrad's Higher Party
School; S.B. Petrov, director of a sewing factory; and V.A.
Yefimov, party leader of Leningrad's Lenin region.
   Sovietskaya Rossiya said the turning point of the meeting came
when general contractor I.D. Spassky warned that if the party
doesn't start showing it can solve citizens' problems, it can
expect more of the same.
   ``People want to live better today,'' he said. ``The process of
renewal of the economy at the least must move in parallel with
political changes, but the prosperity of the people should outstrip
it. Only then will the people believe us. And in the meantime, they
wait for years and lose faith in perestroika.''
   Across the nation in the Soviet Far East, Khabarovsk Communist
Party chief V.S. Pasternak blamed his loss on the late President
Leonid I. Brezhnev and his corrupt cronies. In an interview with
Izvestia, Pasternak said people were sick of commands, and looked
at all party leaders with the same distrust.
   Pasternak said a leaflet was circulated in Khabarovsk that said,
``A vote for Pasternak means a vote for the party which led our
motherland into this dead end and now with the help of demogogic
subterfuges, is trying to convince people it can lead them out of
this situation.''
</TEXT>
