<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Soviet     04-06 0536</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Soviet,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Praises Polish Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government newspaper Thursday praised Poland's
communist authorities and Solidarity for displaying common sense in
an agreement that it said legalizes the union while challenging it
to act constructively.
   ``Common sense came out on top,'' the newspaper Izvestia said,
telling its readers that in Poland the ``participation of the
opposition in the official political life of the country has become
a fact.''
   The Soviet Union has watched the legalization of opposition
forces in its allies Hungary and Poland while its own Communist
Party continues to tolerate no challengers. One controversial
figure, former Moscow party boss Boris N. Yeltsin, is under
investigation by the party on charges that he supports a multiparty
system.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh, asked about the
developments in Poland, said the Soviet Union was watching a
process it considered an internal Polish affair.
   ``We wish that dialogue to lead to results or developments that
could improve the situation in Poland so that the life of the
Polish people can be brought back to normal,'' Gremitskikh said.
   The conclusion of negotiations in Poland was reported by Radio
Moscow and by the Tass news agency, but Izvestia gave its millions
of readers a much more detailed account that included the formation
of a second chamber of the parliament, legalization of Solidarity
and other key changes.
   The agreement, reached Wednesday, gives Poland its first
democratic elections since World War II.
   It said the agreement would not have been possible without
reforms carried out by the Polish Communist Party in the last eight
years, but that Solidarity also showed a realistic attitude.
   The agreement ``would not have been possible without the
political will which the opposition began to show at last during
the middle of last year,'' Izvestia said.
   ``The opposition has taken on a new role for itself, one that is
quite difficult psychologically. Up to now its main strength was
negative, resisting the system, criticizing all and everything.''
Izvestia said.
   ``Now, in the conditions of legal activity it has to clearly
formulate its program, speak out with concrete ideas, be in full
view, consistently, become an object of evaluation and criticism,''
it said.
   ``It is one thing to be able to destroy, instigate strikes and
interfere with reforms, and something else entirely to create, to
assist in the framework of general responsibility, positive
processes,'' it said.
   Izvestia said it still was not clear whether Solidarity was
inclined to cooperate with authorities.
   Earlier, Radio Moscow reported the agreement in an
English-language news broadcast, but only an alert listener could
realize that Solidarity's legal status had been restored.
   The news report said Solidarity had taken part in the
negotiations and they produced a number of political agreements,
including one ``which states trade union pluralism.''
   The announcer said the participants also agreed on
``establishment of a two-chamber parliament and the post of a
president with broad powers.'' It did not mention that the
parliament would be the result of the first democratic elections
since World War II.
   The Tass news agency said only the talks involving Walesa had
ended and gave no further details of the agreement.
</TEXT>
