<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Africa-Debt     04-06 0183</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Africa-Debt,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foreign Ministers Open Debt Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African finance ministers seeking
an alternative to harsh Western prescriptions for their ailing
economies opened a four-day conference Thursday on a gloomy note.
   Adebayo Adedeji, head of the U.N. Economic Commission for
Africa, said that unless dramatic measures are taken to lift the
continent from its economic doldrums, Africa will suffer another
decade of ``economic retrogression and unmitigated disaster.''
   The conference is being held under the commission's auspices at
its headquarters in Ethiopia'a capital and will consider a draft
proposal of an African alternative to the conventional structural
adjustment programs of the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund.
   The African alternative would place more emphasis on social
programs, an emphasis underdeveloped nations long have sought. Many
argue that demands for austerity by Western lending institutions
lead to the kind of social upheavals that hit Venezuela last month.
   Africa claims 28 of the world's poorest and least developed
countries, nations whose per capita debt almost equals their per
capita income. The continent's external debt grew to $230 billion
in 1988.
</TEXT>
