<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Korea-Tomb     04-06 0134</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Korea-Tomb,0137</SECOND>
<HEAD>Body Buried 400 Years Ago Unearthed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a woman buried about 400
years ago has been found preserved in a wood coffin with documents
and clothing intact, according to officials in a provincial city.
   Kwak Byong-man, 40, was moving the casket of an ancestor to a
new burial site when he discovered the centuries-old coffin, said
officials in Taegu, south of Seoul.
   The coffin had a two-layered lid that required six men to pry
open, officials said. It contained a well-preserved female body,
officials said, as well as traditional Korean clothing and
documents written in both Korean Hangul and Chinese characters.
   Officials said the discovery of the documents was particularly
meaningful to scholars, and they will be used to study customs of
the time.
</TEXT>
