<FIRST>r w PM-AfghanEnvoy 1stLdWritethru a0444 04-06 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghan Envoy, 1st Ld Writethru, a0444,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Presidential Envoy to Afghanistan Resistance Named</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 3 grafs new with confirmation of post, reaction. Picks up
3rd graf pvs, Tomsen will report.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration has chosen Peter
Tomsen, deputy chief of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, as a special
presidential envoy with the rank of ambassador to the Afghanistan
resistance, adminstration sources said today.
   Tomsen will be stationed in Washington, said the official, who
spoke on condition he not be named.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh
said reports that the United States named an envoy to Afghan rebels
showed that U.S. officials planned to break relations with
Afghanistan and recognize a rebel government-in-exile.
   Tomsen will report to senior State Department officials rather
than Robert Oakley, the U.S. ambassador in Pakistan, who had sought
to maintain responsibility for Afghan as well as Pakistani affairs,
said a report on the envoy published in The Washington Post.
   Department officials had sought to win the job for an area
specialist, the report said.
   Sen. Gordon J. Humphrey, R-N.H., the leading congressional
advocate of naming such an envoy, told the Post he was generally
pleased with the decision by Secretary of State James A. Baker III
even though his own candidate for the job _ Zalmy Khalilzad, an
Afghan-born scholar now with the Rand Corp. _ was not named.
   ``Anything is better than nothing,'' said Humphrey. ``Time is of
the essence now. All the bold (diplomatic) strokes are coming from
the Kabul government. We've got to gain the initiative.''
</TEXT>
