<FIRST>u i PM-Salvador 1stLd-Writethru   04-06 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0497,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Army Headquarters; Six Reported Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with attacks on army headquarters, casualties
reported. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCOS ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas today
attacked the 4th army brigade headquarters and the headquarters of
army engineers. At least six people died and 10 were wounded,
authorities said.
   Col. Ciro Lopez Roque, commander of the 4th brigade in El
Paraiso, 40 miles north of San Salvador, said three soldiers and
three guerrillas were killed in the pre-dawn attack. Lopez said
five soldiers were wounded.
   He said the rebels did not penetrate the brigade's perimeter but
that several of their mortars landed inside.
   The rebel's clandestine Radio Venceremos said the attack lasted
two hours and was ``a success.'' It did not mention casualties.
   Guerrilla troops also attacked the headquarters of the military
engineers in Zacatecoluca, 35 miles southeast of San Salvador.
   Col. Benjamin Canjura, post commander, said five civilians were
wounded when homemade guerrilla artillery fell short of the
military installation. He said there were no military casualties.
   Both he and Lopez spoke in telephone interviews with The
Associated Press.
   An air force helicopter and an O-2 ``push-and-pull''
reconnaissance aircraft fitted with machine guns and rockets for
air support attacked retreating guerrilla forces on the slopes of
Chinchontepec Volcano north of the city, witnesses said.
   In another development, a man who identified himself as an urban
guerrilla of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front called
the local Sonora radio station Wednesday to claim responsibility
for the assassination on Tuesday of a police officer in the capital.
   The caller, who claimed to speak for the Juan Castro Urban
Commandos, said the group ``would remain vigilant'' to the actions
of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, judges and members
of the Supreme Court in connection with a case implicating military
men and businessmen in an early 1980s kidnap-for-profit ring.
   The caller said guerrillas ``would take the appropriate action''
if they found anyone acting in support of those implicated in the
rightist ring.
   One of the suspects was freed Friday on orders of an outgoing
judge. The order was overturned Monday by the judge's successor.
   The suspects in the case are friends and associates of Roberto
D'Aubuisson, founder of the Alliance, which is known by its Spanish
acronym, Arena.
   The rebels have waged a nine-year war against the U.S.-supported
government. More than 70,000 Salvadorans, most of them civilians,
have been killed.
   They have stepped up attacks recently to protest the recent
election of right-wing businessman Alfredo Cristiani to the
presidency.
   They threatened to present Cristiani with ``an ungovernable
country'' when he takes office June 1. Cristiani was the candidate
of Arena in the March 19 election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
