<FIRST>r i AM-Gorbachev-Crowd     04-06 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Crowd,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Stops to Win Crowd Outside Abbey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev hopped from
his limousine outside Westminster Abbey on Thursday to chat and
shake hands with cheering onlookers who had waited 90 minutes in
the cold rain to see him.
   ``I was the first person to shake his hand,'' said Tim Haggarty
of Londonderry, Northern Ireland. ``This is the best day in my
entire life. He's a hero.''
   Gorbachev sent his security men dashing in all directions when
he decided, apparently on impluse, to stop his motorcade only a few
yards from the abbey's Great West Door and greet about a dozen
people in the crowd of several hundred waiting across the street.
Many were encouraging him with shouts of ``Mikhail!''
   Haggarty, 23, said he studied the Soviet leader's schedule for
his 40-hour visit to Britain and concluded the only opportunity
Gorbachev would have to meet the people would be after laying a
wreath at the Tomb of the Unknown Warrior.
   ``I think he must really know that we love him,'' Haggarty said.
``What he's doing is so wonderful. He's trying to create peace in
the world. He has to be treated like the hero he is.''
   Gorbachev and his wife, Raisa, also spoke with Mark Frankham of
Croydon on the southern outskirts of London, and told the
13-year-old: ``Thank you very much for the reception.''
   Mark, who was with his mother, Gloria, said: ``I never expected
him to come over as there were so many police around. He was
already in his car but he got out and came across. I am thrilled.
It will be something to tell my school friends.''
   In a 15-minute ceremony inside the 900-year-old abbey, Gorbachev
and two Soviet soldiers laid the wreath of red carnations on the
tomb containing the remains of an uknown British soldier killed in
France in World War I.
   ``This has been a very significant event here,'' Gorbachev told
a Soviet journalist. His remarks were translated into English for
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher who accompanied him.
   ``It reminds all of us of our common responsibilities. It
reminds all of us that we should do our best in order to prevent
new victims so that all the sacrifice of our people may not have
been in vain _ I mean particularly the soldiers fallen in those
battles.''
   The dean of Westminster Abbey, the Very Rev. Michael Mayne,
welcomed Gorbachev, saying: ``All those who long for the day when
the barriers of fear and injustice which divide nations are no
more, greatly welcome and admire what you have already achieved by
way of perestroika together with the new openness in international
affairs.''
   Mayne prayed for peace and for the victims of December's
earthquake. Gorbachev canceled his trip to Britain in December when
the earthquake struck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
