<DOCNO> AP890406-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1241EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Korea-Dissident     04-06 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Dissident,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Korea Chides Seoul's Move to Arrest Dissident Leader</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea's official media on Thursday warned
South Korea not to arrest a dissident clergyman who secretly
visited the communist country for talks on reunifying the Korean
peninsula.
   The Seoul government ``should know clearly what consequences ...
its foolish scheme to arrest and punish Rev. Moon Ik-hwan (will)
bring on its lot,'' said a commentary in the Workers (Communist)
Party newspaper Rodong Sinmun.
   North Korea on Wednesday threatened to break off an already
fractured dialogue with Seoul if Moon is arrested when he returns
home from an unauthorized, nine-day visit to Pyongyang via Japan
and China.
   Moon, an adviser to South Korea's main dissident United National
Democratic Movement, arrived Wednesday in Tokyo and said he plans
to return home by April 14.
   His visit, the first by a South Korean dissident, broke
regulations requiring South Koreans to obtain government permission
before they travel to North Korea.
   South Koreans were angered by televised scenes of Moon hugging
North Korean leader Kim Il Sung, whom they blame for the 1950-53
Korean War. Korea was divided at the end of World War II in 1945.
   Seoul officials say Moon helped Pyongyang discredit their
government's authority.
   Moon told reporters in Tokyo he went to Pyongyang to contribute
to unification through non-governmental contacts. But he also said
he met only communist leaders and some of his relatives living in
the north.
   Rodong Sinmun said: ``As Rev. Moon Ik-hwan already stated, his
Pyongyang visit this time was aimed at deepening trust between the
people in the North and the South, jointly seeking a reasonable way
of reunification and promoting peace.''
   Moon's arrest would ``deliberately aggravate North-South
relations and lay a new obstacle in the way,'' it said.
   The nations are involved in a variety of contacts ranging from a
possible non-aggression pact to trade and cultural exchanges. Some
have stalled over North Korean protests about recently concluded
U.S.-South Korean military exercises.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
