<DOCNO> AP890406-0102 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-Panama     04-06 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Panama,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Plans To Extend Economic Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush plans to extend for one year
the economic sanctions President Reagan imposed on the Panamanian
government controlled by military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega, an
administration source said today.
   The current economic, trade and military sanctions expire on
April 8. Bush was expected to act as early as today or Friday to
keep them in place for year.
   In the package that is currently being prepared for Bush's
signature, the sanctions remain the same as the ones already in
place.
   ``After the election we'll take a look at the situation there
and see if there's any cause for change,'' said the source, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The sanctions imposed under executive order by Reagan a year ago
involve restrictions on U.S. businesses who have developed a
flourishing business with Panama, as well as a cutoff of military
aid to the Central American nation.
   The sanctions include blocking assets of the government of
Panama in the United States and prohibiting tax payments by U.S.
organizations to the Noriega regime.
   The administration is closely looking to Panama's upcoming
elections which are scheduled for May 7.
   It is anticipated that Noriega, who is accused in a federal drug
running case in Miami, will control the process because he controls
the electoral tribunal and the media that otherwise might provide
opposition candidates a better chance to get their messages out.
   Noriega as chief of the Defense Forces is de facto ruler of
Panama.
   ``If the Panamanian people have a chance to express their will
in a free and open manner, we're confident Noriega will go,'' said
the source, who acknowledged however, that prospects for that
appeared rocky.
   The military promised the opposition Authentic Panamanian Party
that the elections will be clean.
   The Democratic Alliance, a coalition of the opposition
Democratic Christian, Liberal and Liberal Republican Nationalist
Movement parties, has Guillermo Endara as its presidential
candidate.
   Noriega has been Panama's de facto leader since February 1988,
when he orchestrated the ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
The president had tried to fire Noriega as military leader after
Noriega was indicted in Florida on U.S. drug trafficking charges.
Noriega denied the charges.
   Washington continues to recognize Delvalle as president and
imposed economic sanctions against Panama in an effort to force
Noriega out.
</TEXT>
