<HEAD>Train Derails, Chemical Fumes Force Evacuation Of Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRINCETON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train derailed today and hit tanks
containing farm pesticides and fertilizers, releasing chemical
fumes that forced evacuation of 1,300 students from nearby schools
and injured one person, police said.
   The train, carrying grain, ran off the tracks at 8:30 a.m. at
Princeton Fertilizer, said police officer Dorothy Mowery.
   The spreading fumes forced the precautionary evacuation of
Princeton Community High School and Brumfield Elementary School,
less than one-half mile downwind, superintendent Ed Swan said.
   Homes within two miles of the site were also evacuated, Mowery
said.
   A female employee of the adjacent Cargill Grain Elevator,
Princeton Fertilizer's parent company, was being treated at Gibson
General Hospital, emergency room nurse Judy Morgan said.
   ``She's suffering from skin irritation, mucus membrane
irritation and eye irritation,'' Morgan said. The woman's name was
not released.
   The students, taken to Princeton Middle School, were told at
10:30 a.m. that it was safe to return.
