<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Armenia,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Donate School for Armenian Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain will build a school in Armenia to replace
one of the many lost in December's earthquake, Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher said Thursday after talks with Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The school, which will be designed to withstand earthquakes,
will be built for 400 children between age six and 16 in Leninakan,
one of the towns hardest hit by the Dec. 7 earthquake.
   Signing memoranda of understanding with Gorbachev, Mrs. Thatcher
announced ``the gift of a school to the people of Armenia who
suffered so much in the earthquake.
   ``As you probably know, 5,000 children were killed ... during
that earthquake and of course thousands and thousands were left
without schools,'' she said.
   ``When we asked the people of Armenia what they would like as a
gift, they said a school,'' Mrs. Thatcher said following more than
two hours of talks with Gorbachev.
   She and Gorbachev signed the papers in front of several
industrialists whose companies, along with a charity called Aid
Armenia and the Department of Education, financed the project.
   Upon his departure from Mrs. Thatcher's official residence,
Gorbachev told reporters he wanted to thank the British ``for
reaching out to the people of Armenia ... in those days (after the
earthquake).''
   ``That tragic situation also showed that we can be together,
that we can work together when there is understanding, where there
is trust, when there is a good atmosphere in relations between the
two nations,'' he said.
   Work on the school is to begin next month and it is to be
completed by the 1990-91 school year.
   It will cost about $7 million, said an education spokesman,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``I am delighted that British skills and technology are being
used in this way to the benefit of the people hit by this terrible
disaster,'' said Education Secretary Kenneth Baker.
   Companies contributing to the school included British Petroleum
Co. PLC., British Steel Corp., Cable and Wireless PLC., Coloroll
Group PLC., GEC Ltd. and Imperial Chemical Industries Ltd.
