<FIRST>r i AM-Hess     04-06 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hess,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Spandau Guard Convicted of Stealing Goods from Rudolf Hess</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A court on Thursday convicted a former guard at
Spandau Prison of stealing valuables from the late Nazi war
criminal Rudolf Hess at the prison.
   Stephen Timson, a former guard at the Allies' prison in West
Berlin, also was found guilty of attempting to coerce money from
Hess' son, Munich architect Wolf Ruediger Hess, by demanding the
equivalent of $267,000 for the return of the goods.
   Timson, of Britain, was given a suspended two-year sentence with
probation but was told he would have to serve a year in jail if he
violated terms of the probation.
   His British brother-in-law, Paul Warman, was fined about $1,070
for involvement in the attempts to sell the valuables.
   Timson, 33, admitted taking Hess' World War II flight uniform,
watches, and other valuables dating back to the Nazi era while a
guard at Spandau.
   But Timson also maintained he ``found'' the items stashed in a
blue garbage bag in a prison storage room.
   He told the court, ``It was a stupid idea from beginning to end.
I won't do anything like this ever again.''
   Timson and Warman were arrested in a Hamburg hotel on Dec. 10,
1988, as they met with Hess' son to close the deal.
   Rudolf Hess, former deputy to Nazi leader Adolf Hitler, died in
Spandau Prison on Aug. 17, 1987. at the age of 93 while serving a
life sentence. His death was ruled a suicide.
</TEXT>
