<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Labor     04-06 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Labor,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employers' Group Calls For Importation of Labor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federation of Hong Kong employers urged the
government Thursday to import foreign laborers to ease Hong Kong's
acute labor shortage.
   The group, called the Joint Associations Working Group, said it
was essential to import contract laborers to avoid inflation and
falling economic competitiveness.
   Hong Kong needs about 50,000 imported workers, most of them
unskilled, to help fill an estimated 200,000 job vacancies, it said.
   The group's chairman, Martin Barrow, an executive at Jardine
Matheson Holdings Ltd., said there was danger Hong Kong could lose
it ``competitiveness in the manufacturing sector, the hotel
industry and elsewhere'' because of the shortage of workers.
   The government said Tuesday it is considering easing
restrictions on employment of foreign laborers. Under current
policy, only foreign workers with skills not available locally are
allowed to work in the colony.
   Hong Kong's low unemployment rate, currently 1.3 percent, is
considered a key factor behind the economy's growth slowing to an
expected 6 percent this year, less than half the 1987 rate.
   The labor shortage is due to tight immigration laws and a steady
drain of talent as the colony approaches its return to Chinese
sovereignty in 1997.
   The report said the government should encourage automation and
productivity through tax breaks and reducing red tape. It said
bringing in workers on six-month to two-year contracts, similar to
practices in Singapore, would provide relief.
   The group also suggested the possibility of Hong Kong using
workers who would commute daily from China.
</TEXT>
