<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-AgentOrange Bjt   04-06 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Agent Orange, Bjt,0718</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grant Will Help Veterans Pay Living Expenses While Under Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MAJOR HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Until now, Vietnam veterans who came
here to be treated for post-traumatic stress disorder were likely
to encounter another kind of stress _ figuring out how to pay for
living expenses during their seven-week stay.
   That's about to change.
   The Mid-Rio Grande chapter of the American Red Cross has been
awarded more than $100,000 to help veterans and their families from
New Mexico, Arizona and parts of Texas pay rent and food costs
while they are treated at an outpatient clinic at the Veterans
Administration Medical Center here.
   The Red Cross hopes to serve about 70 veterans and their
families during the one-year project, said Marjorie Waters, the Red
Cross chapter's administrator of emergency services and disaster
programs.
   ``I want it to be the tip of the iceberg kind of thing, where it
could be increased,'' said Mrs. Waters, who hopes the grant will be
renewed.
   ``We can reach them and help them into this (treatment) program
that they would not be able to take part in if they had to worry
about paying the rent or that basic kind of thing,'' she said.
   The Red Cross was one of eight agencies nationwide awarded Agent
Orange Class Assistance grants totaling more than $581,000 to help
them serve Vietnam veterans and their families.
   The March 30 awards were the first disbursements to service
agencies from the settlement of a 1978 lawsuit against seven
manufacturers of Agent Orange. In their class-action lawsuit,
veterans alleged they got cancer and other illnesses because of
exposure to the defoliant used by the military in Southeast Asia in
the 1960s.
   The $240 million settlement, upheld by the U.S. Supreme Court
last year, provides $170 million to be paid directly to U.S.
veterans or their survivors; $52 million to agencies that serve
veterans and their families; plus lesser amounts for veterans of
other countries who served in Vietnam and for legal and
administrative fees.
   The grants to service agencies were designed to reach veterans
and their families who do not meet the eligibility requirements for
direct payments, which are reserved for disabled veterans. The
grants are not limited to agencies that treat Agent Orange-related
problems.
   The $52 million fund for agencies is expected to grow with
interest to $70million over the seven- to 10-year life of the
program.
   Mrs. Waters said the idea for rental and food assistance came
because veterans from outside Albuquerque contacted the local Red
Cross for money to pay living expenses while in the city seeking
treatment.
   ``It's been in my mind for a couple of years because we helped
veterans when we could from Red Cross funding when they were here
for the program,'' she said. ``They came and said they were taking
part in the program and didn't have any more money for rent or gas
or food.''
   She said the grant ``really was a godsend'' because the Red
Cross wasn't able to meet all the needs of the veterans it heard
from.
   The chapter applied for $102,000 based on an estimate of
veterans in the clinic and the chapter's experience in paying rent
and food costs for homeless people, Ms. Waters said.
   Diane Castillo, coordinator of the VA treatment program, said
she expects the grant will increase the number of veterans in the
program from outside the Albuquerque area.
   ``A major problem with any guys coming in from anywhere was the
need for them to commute daily,'' she said.
   The clinic, which began operating in 1987, combines individual
and group psychotherapy. Staff members try to avoid using
medication because chemicals are only an artificial way of dealing
with anxiety, Castillo said.
   ``We directly address the patient's traumatic experience, bring
back that event to the patient, then work through the feelings
they've suppressed for the last 20 years,'' she said.
   The program, which she described as ``fairly intense,'' also
includes counseling for married couples, anger management, problem
solving and social skills, Castillo said.
   The clinic has treated about 150 veterans and can handle 85 to
100 a year, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0112 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Spill-Captain 4thLd-Writethru a0582 04-06 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Captain, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0582,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fired Captain Released After Bail Reduced to $25,000</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Hazelwood released; Picks
up 5th graf, `The amount ...'; ^With PM-Tanker Spill, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fired captain of the Exxon Valdez
walked out of jail today after a judge reduced his bail from $1
million to $25,000, calling the higher amount ``unconstitutionally
excessive.''
   Capt. Joseph Hazelwood posted bail, walked out of the Suffolk
County jail at 12:59 p.m. and got into a waiting car with attorney
Thomas Russo and another lawyer. He did not speak and showed no
emotion as he walked off.
   On Wednesday, another judge set bail for Hazelwood at $1 million
bond or $500,000 cash, comparing the effect of the oil tanker wreck
in Alaska to the atomic bombing of Hiroshima.
   Justice Thomas Stark, the supervising judge of Suffolk County
Criminal Court, today reduced the bail to $25,000 bond or cash.
   ``The amount of bail is not commensurate with the seriousness of
the crime or the effect of the crime on the community,'' Stark said
of the figure that had shocked even prosecutors.
   ``We can't take out our wrath on one individual,'' said District
Attorney Patrick Henry, whose office originally had requested
$25,000 bail.
   Hazelwood, who faces three misdemeanor charges in Alaska, is
accused of being drunk when he relinquished command of the Exxon
Valdez to an uncertified seaman. The vessel then hit a reef March
24, gushing 10.1 million gallons of crude oil into Prince William
Sound and creating North America's worst oil spill.
   Judge Kenneth Rohl, a naturalist who comes from a family of
professional seamen, set Hazelwood's bail Wednesday at $1 million
bond or $500,000 cash.
   ``These misdemeanors are of such a magnitude that has never been
equaled, at least in this country,'' Rohl said. ``He's got to think
about that. We have a man-made destruction that has not been
equaled, probably, since Hiroshima.''
   The U.S. bombing of Hiroshima at the end of World War II killed
or injured nearly 130,000 people and leveled 90 percent of the
Japanese city. No human life has been lost in the oil spill.
   Dean Guaneli, Alaska's assistant attorney general, said the bail
order ``expresses the nation's outrage at what has happened.''
   A pale, shaken Hazelwood, whose lawyer had sought $5,000 cash
bail, was led from Rohl's courtroom in handcuffs after his
arraignment on the fugitive warrant.
   ``It was tough for our client to hear,'' said defense attorney
Michael Chalos. ``It was very harsh, we thought.''
   Hazelwood was taken to the Suffolk County Jail. He was granted
30 days to prepare for an extradition hearing.
   Authorities in Alaska have charged him with operating a ship
while drunk, reckless endangerment and negligent discharge of oil.
He faces 2\ years in prison if convicted.
   Hazelwood, 42, of Huntington, N.Y., was fired by Exxon last week
after the National Transportation Safety Board said tests taken
about nine hours after the Good Friday disaster showed he was under
the influence of alcohol.
   Rohl said that even though Hazelwood faces only misdemeanors,
``We are not talking about someone breaking someone's windshield.
We are talking about a global catastrophe.''
   Russo said his client was no fugitive because ``he left Alaska
before any charges had been filed against him.''
   ``No one is saying this is not a tragedy,'' Russo said, but
added: ``Captain Hazelwood is not guilty of these crimes. He did
not commit any criminal acts in this affair.''
   Hazelwood, who had shaven off his beard, appeared pale and
despondent after the judge's tongue-lashing. When officers put
handcuffs on him his hands were sweating and shaking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1332EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TaxCompliance     04-06 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Compliance,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Many Taxpayers Not Adjusting to New Law, IRS Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many taxpayers are having trouble giving up
lucrative deductions that were repealed or curtailed by the 1986
tax overhaul.
   A spot check by the Internal Revenue Service of returns filed
last year and early this year shows evidence of widespread
non-compliance with parts of the new law. These include limitations
on writing off investment and personal interest, on miscellaneous
deductions such as union dues and on the treatment of rental losses.
   The IRS made the disclosure in announcing Thursday that it has
broadened efforts to gauge how well taxpayers understand and comply
with the new law.
   ``Recognizing that the 1986 act represents the most
comprehensive change to the federal tax system in a quarter century
and contained changes affecting almost every taxpayer, the IRS will
use the studies to assist taxpayers to better understand the new
laws and help determine to what extent taxpayers are trying to
circumvent various provisions of the new law,'' the agency said.
   The IRS is so concerned about public reaction to the new law
that it has set up teams in each of its 10 regional service centers
to spot check returns as they are filed. Without such checks, the
agency would have to wait until 1991 for comprehensive information
from a sizable number of returns.
   A check of several thousand returns filed in 1988, the first
year affected significantly by the new law, disclosed that many
taxpayers did not follow tougher rules on treatment of losses from
passive investments, rental losses, investment interest expenses
and miscellaneous itemized deductions.
   Rick Hayes, head of audit planning for the IRS, said those
issues were chosen as targets of the new effort because they
involve large amounts of revenue, show up on many returns and were
all changed significantly by the 1986 law.
   The first of about 150,000 returns filed this year that are
expected to undergo spot checks show those same errors are being
repeated. In addition, Hayes said in an interview, many returns
being filed this year attempted to avoid the reduction in the
writeoff of consumer interest, in the deduction for
business-related meals and entertainment and in depreciation of
automobiles.
   In the past, the IRS generally would discover such
non-compliance only through a formal audit, which usually would
come about two years after a return was filed. With the new effort,
the agency hopes to spot trends of non-compliance early and follow
quickly with a campaign to educate the public.
   If the effort is successful, the IRS expects to see fewer
taxpayers making these mistakes and fewer returns being audited on
those issues.
   ``We want to fix as many of these things as we can without doing
audits on people,'' Hayes said. ``If we can do these as part of
(returns) processing, that's what we want to do.''
   The IRS has not yet estimated how much money is being lost by
the government because of non-compliance with the 1986 tax changes.
Hayes said the spot checks are likely to find numerous cases in
which taxpayers cheated themselves by misreading parts of the new
law. Those taxpayers will be notified, he emphasized.
   Information from the spot checks will be used to determine
whether the IRS needs to change its tax forms, instructions or
publications to clear up confusion resulting from the law changes,
Hayes said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
