<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Economy     04-06 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>1989 Predicted Worst Year Yet For Soviet Economy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is facing its toughest year yet
and could degenerate into ``economic chaos'' without urgent
reforms, a newspaper said Thursday.
   ``The bony hand of hunger for products is quite capable of
strangling perestroika,'' the Soviet program of economic
restructuring, journalist Vasily Selyunin wrote in a front-page
article in the daily Socialist Industry.
   By putting off painful reforms, economists are ruining the
chances for those reforms to succeed, said Selyunin, who
specializes in economic affairs.
   He cited the need to deal urgently with the Soviet budget
deficit and shortages of consumer goods. Selyunin's calls for more
rapid economic change have appeared in other top journals.
   The sooner real reform is introduced the better, ``because
otherwise we'll have to be introducing economic reform under the
conditions of economic chaos,'' he said.
   The government could have begun raising prices on plentiful,
easily substituted items, but it is too late because virtually
everything is in short supply, he said.
   An institute on consumer demand found that 211 food products,
only 23 could be bought freely, he said. The rest require
connections with the sellers, overpayment or are rationed.
   Strategists promise tough reforms after an initial period of
heightened output of consumer goods, but there is no reason to
expect any such increase, Selyunin said.
   ``On the contrary, one can expect that the year 1989 will be the
most unsuccessful of all those we have lived through,'' he said.
   Along with the announced budget deficit of $58 billion and an
additional $102 billion in loans to state enterprises that are
losing money, the unexpected expense of earthquakes in Armenia and
Tadzhikistan will cripple the 1989 economy even further, Selyunin
said.
   He said inflation is running at 4 percent to 5 percent annually,
much higher than official figures.
   ``Today we have to choose between only two realities: either
relatively stable prices with minor inflation of about 6 percent
and empty shelves, or quickly rising prices and goods in the
stores,'' he said.
   Selyunin's prescriptions for fixing the economy included cuts in
military spending, which he placed at nearly 20 percent of national
income, and two or three years of importing giant stocks of goods
from the West.
   The imports could be sold at 10 times their cost and thus both
help to balance the state budget and satisfy consumer demand,
Selyunin proposed.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and other leaders have said they
oppose such massive imports, preferring to spend money on
modernizing industry instead.
</TEXT>
