<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Tennis     04-06 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Tennis,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen, Members of Parliament Will Volley to Aid Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers from Britain and the United States
pronounced themselves fit and ready Thursday for a charity tennis
contest May 19 at which organizers said President Bush may put in
an appearance.
   ``You'll see tennis played like never before,'' Sen. John
Breaux, D-La., said at a news conference here. ``We are a mean,
lean and fit machine.''
   ``We will show no mercy once we're on the courts,'' John Hannam,
a conservative member of the House of Commons from Exeter, said
through a telephone hookup from London. ``We've been training here
in the shadows of Wimbledon.''
   ``I hope the Anglo-U.S. relationship will survive this ordeal,''
said Richard Ralph, a representative of the British Embassy.
   The play will be held in connection with the Dow World Senior
Open for players over 45, sceduled for May 15 to 21 at
Congressional Country Club in suburban Bethesda, Md.
   A contribution will be made to Children's Hospital National
Medical Center in the name of the winning team. The country club is
also making a $5,000 donation to the hospital through a
contribution from Dow Chemical, sponsor of the tounament, officials
of the tournament said.
   Each team will consist of eight lawmakers and two guests, and
play will include five doubles matches between congressional and
parliamentary competitors. The first team to win 13 sets will be
declared winner of the Congress-Parliament Challenge Cup and will
receive a trophy from the archives of Wimbledon, officials said.
   Breaux, the captain of the U.S. team, said members tentatively
scheduled to play include Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell,
D-Maine; Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, the 1988 Democratic vice
presidential nominee; Rep. Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., Rep. Byron L.
Dorgan, D-N.D., and Sen. Timothy Wirth, D-Colo. Although he listed
only Democrats, he said he is still rounding up players and hopes
to have some Republicans. He said he has also been talking to the
White House and thinks it likely that Bush will be on hand.
   Ralph said the British team will include the Marquis of Reading,
the Earl of Kinnoul and Lord St. John of Bletso from the House of
Lords. From the House of Commons it will include Hannam, Michael
Morris of Northampton, Patrick Round of Feltham and Heston, Malcolm
Moss of Cambridgeshire N.E., Tony Steen of South Hams and Tim
Sainsbury of Hove.
   They are all conservatives, but Ralph said, ``I don't think that
was by design.'' Apparently, he said, they are just better tennis
players.
</TEXT>
