<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-Scandal     04-06 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Governing Party Members Seek Resignation of Takeshita</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita faces pressure from
some members of his own party to resign to halt damage to the party
from a stock-profiteering scandal, politicians and news reports
said Thursday.
   Takeshita, who acknowledged receiving nearly $400,000 in
political contributions from the company at the center of the
scandal, has vowed to remain in power despite opposition calls for
his resignation and public opinion polls that show as few as 9
percent of Japanese support his government.
   The news reports said Thursday about 40 influential members of
the governing Liberal Democratic Party have decided to form the
faction, which demands all those linked to the scandal _ including
party leaders _ step down.
   ``The situation has reached a critical stage,'' they quoted
Shizuka Kamei, a leading member of the group, as saying. ``The
present Liberal Democratic Party is not capable of carrying out
self-purification.''
   The group also demands the government call former Prime Minister
Yasuhiro Nakasone for questioning by legislators on possible links
with the Recruit Co., an information conglomerate that allegedly
used stock bargains to seek favors.
   Opposition parties are boycotting parliamentary deliberations on
the budget, which began Saturday, to back their demands for
Nakasone's testimony.
   On Wednesday, a group of 41 junior party members formed a
faction to demand the government push political reforms.
   ``Prime Minister Takeshita and Mr. Nakasone should accept the
guilt and take appropriate measures to satisfy the people,'' said
faction leader Hajime Morita. ``Public distrust toward politics
cannot be easily erased.''
   Some Liberal Democrats have withdrawn from the party, saying
endorsement by the party, which has dominated Japanese politics for
most of the postwar era, now would hurt their chances to win
elections.
   ``Junior politicians ... can lose their political careers unless
the administration takes drastic measures immediately to restore
public support toward the LDP,'' said one governing party
politician Thursday. The member spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Takeshita and party Secretary-General Shintaro Abe have been
linked to the scandal, and another party leader, former Finance
Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, was one of three Cabinet ministers who
resigned because of links to Recruit.
   Takeshita, Abe and Miyazawa have denied personal wrongdoing.
   Prosecutors have arrested 14 bureaucrats and businessmen on
bribery and securities law violation charges.
   Recruit sold bargain-priced unlisted shares in a subsidiary to
about 150 influential people, who reaped large profits when public
trading in the stock began and it rose rapidly in value.
   Takeshita suffered another blow Wednesday with reports, which he
later confirmed, that Recruit contributed $382,000 to two Takeshita
fund-raising parties in May 1987, six months before he became prime
minister.
   His Liberal Democrats hold 297 of the 512 seats in parliament's
lower house, and 143 of the 252 in the upper house. Elections for
half of the upper house seats must be held this summer, and a
series of setbacks in local elections early this year has worried
upper house party candidates.
   A 3 percent sales tax that took effect Saturday, along with cuts
in income taxes and some other taxes, also has contributed to the
Takeshita government's unpopularity in the polls.
</TEXT>
