<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1442EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-People     04-06 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criticism of a lavish lifestyle by
evangelists Oral and Richard Roberts has prompted the sale of their
two California vacation homes, valued at more than $1 million,
Richard Roberts says.
   Roberts said the criticism has resurfaced since his father asked
followers to sell unneeded valuables to help raise $11 million by
May 6 to keep his 41-year-old ministry afloat.
   Richard Roberts said he and his father sold their homes in
Rancho Mirage, Calif., in the past year.
   ``There was a perception that just having the house was bad,''
the younger Roberts said. ``I didn't want to do anything that would
reflect negatively on the ministry.''
   Their homes in Tulsa, both owned by Oral Roberts University,
also are valued at a total of about $1 million, according to Tulsa
County tax records.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The women who will act as strippers in
the movie ``Blaze'' about former Gov. Earl Long's affair with
stripper Blaze Starr include three who strip for a living, says
casting director Dee Cothern.
   ``The others are dancers who were not afraid to wear real tiny
costumes,'' Cothern said Wednesday.
   The movie, to be shot during the next 10 weeks, will star Paul
Newman and Lolita Davidovitch, a Canadian actress.
   Writer-director Ron Shelton plans scenes at the state Capitol
and possibly the old Governor's Mansion, said Louisiana Film
Commission Director Tesa Laviolette.
