<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sun newspaper reported Thursday that it had
handed over to police four stolen letters belonging to Princess
Anne which had been sent anonymously to the paper.
   The racy tabloid, Britain's biggest selling paper with a
national daily circulation of 4.2 million, said the handwritten
letters had been hand-delivered to the 38-year-old daughter of
Queen Elizabeth II without going through the Post Office.
   The paper, which specializes in stories on the royals, said all
four letters were signed by the same person and had been ``spirited
out'' of the Princess's private quarters at Buckingham Palace.
   A Scotland Yard spokesman who in accordance with British
practice declined to be identified confirmed that police had
received four letters from The Sun. ``We are making inquiries about
them. We are not prepared to discuss their origin, destination or
contents,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation is moving away from the
self-interest that marked 1980s as the ``me decade,'' as Americans
again turn toward public purpose over private interest, historian
Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr. says.
   Schlesinger, an assistant to President John F. Kennedy, said
Wednesday in a speech at Miami University that a growing sense of
selflessness fits into a historical rhythm.
   Schlesinger said the 1980s will go down as an era of vulgar
consumption, towering debt, leveraged buyouts and widespread
crookedness in both the private and public sectors, but he
predicted a sharp change in the national mood around 1990.
   ``Already there seems to be the start of revulsion against greed
and the start of a revival of idealism on college campuses, of
community service and a revived concern for social justice,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says there have been too many
delays in the tax evasion trial of billionaires Harry and Leona
Helmsley and jury selection will begin June 26.
   Helmsley, 79, and his 67-year-old wife were indicted last April
on charges that they evaded taxes by disguising about $4 million in
renovations to their Greenwich, Conn., mansion as business expenses.
   The couple head a $5 billion hotel and real estate empire.
   ``This case has taken too long, in my judgment, to get to
trial,'' U.S. District Judge John Walker said Wednesday in setting
the new trial.
   The Helmsleys' trial originally was scheduled to start last
September, but was pushed back until January and delayed again
until May after defense lawyers filed numerous motions to overturn
the indictment or remove one or both of the Helmsleys from the case.
