<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SpaceShuttle     04-06 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Space Shuttle,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Countdown Test Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A two-day practice countdown began
Thursday for the launch of Atlantis on the first space shuttle
planetary mission.
   The exercise was to end Friday, with the five astronauts
assigned to the flight climbing into the spaceship for the final
two hours.
   As the countdown got under way, the astronauts on Thursday
rehearsed emergency procedures on the launch pad.
   NASA is aiming for a liftoff on April 28 but admits the schedule
is tight. Shuttle managers are to meet here April 14 to set a
launch date.
   Once Atlantis reaches Earth orbit, the astronauts are to release
the $378 million Magellan spacecraft on the start of a 466-day
outward journey to Venus. The craft is to orbit the planet and map
its cloud-covered surface with high-resolution radar.
   The crew members, who are to return to Earth after a four-day
flight, are commander Dave Walker, pilot Ron Grabe and mission
specialists Mary Cleave, Mark Lee and Norman Thagard.
