<DOCNO> AP890406-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-US     04-06 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-US,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Which Arena is it in El Salvador?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Alfredo
Cristiani of El Salvador says he represents rightists who think of
themselves as modern conservatives, not exponents of their party's
early neo-fascism.
   As Cristiani meets President Bush on Friday, many question
whether his faction of the Republican Nationalist Alliance is
dominant and whether he can control reputedly sinister elements of
the party. Cristiani takes office June 1.
   The United States, which gives El Salvador about $1.5 million a
day in aid, has said it will keep a close watch on human rights
abuses under the right-wing party, known as Arena. Officials also
have tied continued aid to an improved record.
   Even his antagonists consider Cristiani personally upstanding,
and most accept his avowed commitment to furthering democracy in a
nation ravaged by nine years of civil war.
   He was faced with an important test March 31.
   An outgoing Criminal Court judge ruled that two military men and
a landowner implicated in an kidnap-for-profit ring in the early
1980s were illegally detained and must be freed.
   All three, along with five fugitives absolved by the judge, were
cronies of Roberto d'Aubuisson, a dismissed major of army
intelligence who founded Arena in 1981 and retains great influence
in it.
   Cristiani acted decisively. He brought pressure to bear on the
judiciary, got the judge's order revoked and kept two of the three
suspects in jail.
   New arrest warrants were issued for the man released and for the
five d'Aubuisson associates implicated in the ring.
   A ranking U.S. Embassy official said of Cristiani's first human
rights test: ``He passed with flying colors.''
   Critics of Arena say Cristiani, a wealthy landowner educated at
Georgetown University in Washington, is a pseudo-democratic veneer
on an apparatus linked to rightist death squads that killed tens of
thousands of alleged leftists in the early 1980s.
   Arena's anthem, broadcast incessantly during the campaign, still
says: ``El Salvador will be the tomb where the Reds will all end
up.''
   The president-elect denies being a front man and says
d'Aubuisson, who is an Arena legislator and leads the majority bloc
in the unicameral legislature, will not have a post in the
executive branch.
   ``There should be no doubt that it is I who will run the
government,'' Cristiani said after winning the March 19 election.
He is 41, a coffee-grower, businessman and champion athlete who
came late to politics and rose to prominence in Arena after
d'Aubuisson lost the 1984 presidential election.
   ``Be assured that I entered politics only because of the
country's grave crisis and am not motivated by personal ambition,''
he said in a radio advertisement during his campaign.
   Cristiani campaigned on a platform of ``capitalism for the
masses'' and an end to the civil war.
   He has said he is willing to talk with leftist rebels of the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, but ``we will not
negotiate our political platform, or a share of power. We will not
negotiate democracy.''
   Monsignor Gregorio Rosa Chavez, auxiliary archbishop of San
Salvador, said recently the Arena victory was likely ``to augment
the level of violence, because they are advocates of escalation of
the war.''
   The new president's position is that he will offer the rebels
terms for laying down arms and entering the democratic process, and
will increase military pressure if they refuse.
   Rebel leaders say that amounts to a call for surrender. They say
they will be the ones to intensify the war, showing the country to
be ungovernable without their participation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
