<FIRST>r a AM-People-Garbo     04-06 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Garbo,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Garbo Talks, A Little</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greta Garbo, describing herself as a ``sour
little creature,'' says she's always wanted two lives: ``one for
the movies, one for myself.''
   Comments made over the last 26 years by the reclusive film star,
who hasn't made a movie since 1941, were recorded by a friend and
published in a spring issue of Life magazine.
   ``If somebody gave me a million dollars I wouldn't write
anything about myself,'' she was quoted as saying. ``I wouldn't do
it for anything under the sun. I don't think it's worthwhile. I
don't think it's very interesting.
   ``I don't want any kind of attention from anybody, except that I
know that someone likes me, and that's nice. Otherwise, it's
sickening.''
   The 84-year-old Garbo, who has an apartment in Manhattan, says
she suffers from inertia.
   ``But to run from place to place is not what I'm looking for,''
she says. ``I can't take it. ... You have to show passports, and
someone might say, `Oh, that's the one who used to be in the
movies.' ''
</TEXT>
