<FIRST>r a AM-TankerCaptain     04-06 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Captain,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fired Captain Freed on $25,000 Bail</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Oil Spill-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fired captain of the Exxon Valdez
walked out of jail Thursday after winning reduction of the $1
million bond set by a judge who compared the tanker's oil spill to
the Hiroshima bombing.
   A stone-faced Capt. Joseph Hazelwood, 42, walked past reporters
without comment and climbed into a waiting Jaguar with his lawyers.
   A few hours earlier, a supervising state judge reduced his bail
to $25,000 and called the $1 million figure ``unconstitutionally
excessive.''
   Hazelwood, who was charged with being intoxicated when his
tanker crashed into a reef on March 24, spent one night in jail.
   He turned himself in Wednesday, and state Supreme Court Justice
Kenneth Rohl set bail at $1 million bond or $500,000 cash.
   ``These misdemeanors are of such a magnitude that has never been
equaled, at least in this country,'' said Rohl, who comes from a
family of professional seamen. ``We have a man-made destruction
that has not been equaled, probably, since Hiroshima.''
   Justice Thomas Stark, who heard the bond appeal, said there was
little chance of Hazelwood jumping bail and drastically cut it to
the amount originally requested by prosecutors.
   ``The amount of bail is not commensurate with the seriousness of
the crime or the affect of the crime on the community,'' said Stark
after listening to an emotional appeal from Hazelwood attorney
Thomas Russo.
   Hazelwood has 30 days to prepare for an extradition hearing that
would return him to Alaska, where he faces charges of operating a
ship while intoxicated, reckless endangerment, and negligent
discharge of oil. The charges carry a combined maximum penalty of
2\ years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
   Hazelwood was fired by Exxon last Thursday after the National
Transportation Safety Board said tests taken about nine hours after
the March 24 disaster showed he was under the influence of alcohol.
</TEXT>
