<HEAD>No More Bible Verses Over Intercom, Blytheville School Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLYTHEVILLE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A threatened lawsuit by the American
Civil Liberties Union has brought a halt to a years-old practice of
reading Bible verses each day over the intercom at Blytheville High
School.
   ``We sought legal advice and learned that we would probably not
be on solid legal ground and would probably lose the case,''
Superintendent Frank Ladd said Wednesday.
   Principal Bruce Young had earlier contended the readings,
carried out for at least 17 years, didn't violate the
constitutional separation of church and state. He said students
could ``tune them out'' if they wanted and that no attempt was made
to impose specific interpretations of the verses.
   Jay Jacobson, director of the Arkansas chapter of the ACLU, had
said that group was discussing a lawsuit with a potential client in
the district.
   ``I'm delighted to see that they voluntarily agreed with the
Bill of Rights and will set a fine example for young people that
laws are meant to be obeyed,'' he said.
