<HEAD>State Department Says Stroessner Visa Revoked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department confirmed Thursday that
it has revoked a visa of former Paraguayan leader Gen. Alfredo
Stroessner.
   The Paraguayan strongman, who had ruled his country for 34
years, was ousted in a coup. He arrived in Brazil on Feb. 5 after
being granted political asylum there.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher told reporters only
that Stroessner's visa ``has been revoked.''
   But a department official, who spoke on condition he not be
identified by name, said Stroessner had applied for a visa on
humanitarian and medical grounds several weeks ago, but the request
was denied.
   ``We replied that there are excellent doctors in Brazil,'' the
official said.
   Several members of Stroessner's family, including his wife, have
been given visas and are living in Miami, the official said.
   They were not involved in Paraguayan politics and therefore were
allowed to enter the country, the official said.
