<FIRST>u i AM-Vietnam-Cambodia     04-06 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Cambodia,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sihanouk Urges Conference on Cambodia, China Vows To Keep Arming
Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A resistance leader on Thursday
called for an international conference on Cambodia, and China vowed
to arm the guerrillas until Vietnam fulfills its pledge to end its
10-year military intervention.
   Resistance leaders expressed skepticism over Vietnam's promise
Wednesday to withdraw its estimated 50,000 to 70,000 soldiers from
Cambodia by Sept. 30.
   Vietnam's occupation of Cambodia has been a major stumbling
block to establishing relations with the United States and
improving economic ties with non-communist Southeast Asian nations.
   China has also refused to resume normal relations with the
Soviet Union as long as Vietnamese troops remain. Soviet President
Mikhail Gorbachev is to visit China next month for the first
Chinese-Soviet summit in 30 years.
   On Thursday, Vietnam's official Hanoi Radio reaffirmed the Sept.
30 deadline and urged the international community to prevent the
brutal Khmer Rouge regime from regaining power.
   In December 1978, Vietnam ousted the communist Khmer Rouge,
under whose rule an estimated one-fourth of Cambodia's 8 million
people died from famine and execution since 1975.
   Fears that the Khmer Rouge, the strongest of three insurgent
groups in Prince Norodom Sihanouk's resistance coalition, would
regain power has been a major stumbling block to a negotiated
settlement.
   In a written statement from Beijing, Sihanouk, the former
Cambodian ruler, rejected ``all decisions, all conditions, and all
accords'' announced by Vietnam regarding Cambodia.
   Sihanouk urged French President Francois Mitterrand to convene a
conference including the five permanent U.N. Security Council
members _ China, the Soviet Union, the United States, France and
Britain _ as well as Vietnam, all Cambodian factions and the six
members of the non-communist Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
   He urged Vietnam to pull out of Cambodia as soon as possible
under supervision of the United Nations, which would also supervise
new elections.
   In a separate statement, China, the main supplier to the
insurgents, said it was ``entirely just'' to keep aiding them until
Vietnam makes good on its promise to withdraw.
   Sihanouk's clandestine Voice of the Khmer Radio said the prince
doubted the Vietnamese would carry out the withdrawal. The
broadcast, monitored Thursday in Bangkok, Thailand, also said
Sihanouk rejected Vietnam's proposal that India, Poland and Canada
be invited to witness the pullout.
   Indonesia meanwhile said it would sponsor a meeting between
Sihanouk and Cambodia's Vietnam-backed prime minister, Hun Sen,
next month. A spokeswoman for Sihanouk said he planned to meet with
Hun Sen on May 2 in Jakarta.
   In Wednesday's statement, the governments of Cambodia, Laos and
Vietnam recommended revival of an ``international controls and
supervision commission'' established by the 1954 Geneva Agreement
on Indochina.
   But China said the international monitoring force ``should be
established under the auspices of the U.N. secretary-general
following his consultations and agreement with the countries
concerned.''
   Son Sann, leader of the Khmer Peoples National Liberation Front,
said Vietnam must notify the U.N. secretary-general of its plans,
allow the U.N. Security Council to organize an international
peace-keeping force and ``abstain from diverting the real nature of
an aggression war into a civil war.''
   The front is a non-communist member of the Sihanouk coalition.
   In Paris, Suon Kaset, a spokeswoman for Son Sann's group,
claimed 20,000 Vietnamese troops already had been integrated into
Hun Sen's forces and would not be withdrawn.
   ``This is their so-called withdrawal,'' she said. ``It's a
farce.''
</TEXT>
