<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     04-06 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Blast Cities after Ramadan Cease-Fire Call</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KAB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem guerrillas attacked Kabul and
three other cities with rockets and missiles Thursday, the Foreign
Ministry said, despite a cease-fire called by the government to
mark the holy month of Ramadan.
   It was the fifth time since January 1987 that President Najib
has called a halt to hostilities. None has succeeded.
   A truck driver who said he was part of a convoy hauling fuel
said guerrillas tried to hijack some of the trucks about six miles
from Kabul on the Salang Highway.
   The hijackers got about a mile before being attacked by two
government helicopters, said the driver, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   In the afternoon, a missile blew up a fuel truck parked near a
petroleum tank depot on the northern edge of the capital. Several
trucks parked nearby also exploded.
   There was no word on casualties from that attack or from
reported bombardments in Jalalabad, Kandahar, and Sarobi.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said government
troops withheld their fire in those three areas, despite rocket and
cannon fire from guerrillas. The report could not be confirmed.
   The military command announced the cease-fire in a nationwide
radio broadcast Wednesday night for Ramadan, the Islamic holy month.
   Najib, in an interview with the BBC, said his troops would
retaliate with renewed force if the guerrillas broke the cease-fire.
   Amani said guerrillas fired 32 rockets and cannon rounds at the
southern city of Kandahar, where they have been besieging
government forces for the past year.
   Amani said fewer than 100 rounds were fired at Jalalabad. In the
past two weeks, the government has accused the guerrillas of firing
as many as 12,000 rounds a day at the city 75 miles east of Kabul.
   The spokesman said he had no indication how many rounds were
fired at Sarobi, on the highway midway between Kabul and Jalalabad.
   Amani said only three of the seven Pakistan-based guerrilla
factions were firing at Jalalabad, Sarobi and Kandahar.
   He identified them as the factions led by Yunus Khalis,
Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and Rasul Sayyaf _ the most hard-line
fundamentalists of guerrillas who have been trying for more than a
decade to oust Najib's Soviet-backed government.
   The Soviet Union sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979
but withdrew the last of them in February under a U.N.-mediated
accord.
   In Moscow, a Foreign Ministry official said reports the United
States had named an envoy to Afghan rebels showed that U.S.
officials planned to break relations with Afghanistan and recognize
a rebel government-in-exile.
   Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh told a news briefing the
United States and Pakistan continued to violate the agreement that
led to the withdrawal of Soviet troops and were intentionally
aggravating the situation in Afghanistan.
   Reports published in the United States on Thursday said Peter
Tomsen, deputy chief of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, was appointed
to represent U.S. interests to the rebel movement.
   ``The United States does not want to extinguish the flames in
Afghanistan. They make every effort to topple the government in
Afghanistan. They want to bring pressure to bear on the situation
in Afghanistan,'' Gremitskikh said.

</TEXT>
