<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     04-06 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Report First Battle with Death Squads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National police reported their first
confrontations with death squads and said Thursday they found
documents showing the paramilitary groups are run by drug
traffickers.
   Statements from two police generals said officers killed 10
gunmen and seized 8,800 pounds of cocaine and cocaine paste in two
encounters.
   In another development, the Defense Ministry said it would
permit the U.S. government to install radar in Colombia to track
drug-running aircraft.
   Gen. Miguel Maza Marquez said documents found Tuesday in a raid
on a traffickers' hideout in Bogota established that Israeli and
British mercenaries had been training drug traffickers in use of
weapons. He said one gunman was killed 10 were arrested in the raid.
   Witnesses identified three of those arrested as participants in
the assassination Feb. 27 of Teofilo Forero, secretary-general of
the Patriotic Union party, the general said.
   About 700 members of the leftist Patriotic Union have been
killed since it was formed four years ago. Until this week, no one
connected with the government had indicated there were any clues to
who was behind the killings.
   The same group is suspected in an attack at the Bogota airport
March 3 in which four men firing submachine guns killed Jose
Antequera, a member of the Patriotic Union executive committee,
Maza said. A bodyguard also was killed and eight people were
wounded.
   Documents seized in the Bogota raid showed the death squad to be
run by Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, who the U.S. Justice Department
says is among Colombia's main drug traffickers, the general said.
   A statement by Gen. Octavio Vargas said the other encounter with
a death squad, also on Tuesday, occurred near San Luis village 120
miles north of Bogota.
   Anti-narcotics police were fired upon as they approached a
cocaine laboratory in the jungle and returned the fire, killing
nine drug traffickers and capturing three, he said. Vargas said
four officers were wounded.
   Police found 6,600 pounds of cocaine ready to be shipped and
2,200 pounds of paste, the general said.
   He said documents found at the drug lab connected the men with a
death squad run by Pablo Escobar Gaviria. U.S. authorities say he
runs the Medellin Cartel, which smuggles 80 percent of Colombia's
cocaine into the United States.
   Last year, Fortune magazine described Escobar Gaviria as a
billionaire and among the world's 20 richest men. Fifteen years
ago, he was a pickpocket and car thief in Medellin.
   The radar agreement signed by the Colombian military and U.S.
government was disclosed in a Defense Ministry news release.
   One radar unit will be on San Andres, an island about 500 miles
north of the Caribbean coast, and the other in the Amazon jungle of
southern Colombia, it said. The ministry said the Colombian air
force would operate the radars.
   Although the San Andres radar would be only about 125 miles off
Nicaragua, the ministry said it would not be used to monitor
Nicaraguan air traffic. U.S. officials have said Colombian cocaine
has been flown to Nicaragua en route to the United States.
</TEXT>
