<DOCNO> AP890406-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2147EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Beef-Fat     04-06 0619</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beef-Fat,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Say Beef Industry Responding to Consumer Demands for Less
Fat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumers prefer less fat in their steaks and
hamburger, and the beef industry has responded well to those
demands, two Texas A&amp;M University scientists said Thursday.
   H. Russell Cross and Jeff Savell said further progress can be
expected in the future as attention continues to be drawn to health
issues, notably the dietary linkage between fats and high levels of
blood cholesterol.
   But Savell told a conference sponsored by the National
Cattlemen's Association that if he had to send cattle producers and
the beef industry a note from the teacher, it might say:
``Excellent progress made in making product fit consumers' needs.
Keep working on leanness, convenience and cost, value. Remember to
maintain taste, or consumers will go elsewhere.''
   The beef industry drew praise from Jay Fletcher of the Community
Nutrition Institute, who agreed that less fat is being sold to
consumers.
   ``I think they have done more than many other industries to
recognize the dangers of excessive fat consumption and take steps
to inform consumers about that,'' Fletcher said in a telephone
interview.
   But selling meat is also a business, he said, and ``the beef
industry wants to recover its market share; they have lost it
steadily to chicken and poultry in general over the past 10 years.''
   Fletcher said that occurred ``largely because of consumer
perception of beef as a high-fat food.''
   It was just a year ago that the Agriculture Department released
a study by Texas A&amp;M, led by Cross and Savell, that showed the
trimmable fat on retail cuts of beef had been reduced 27 percent in
two years.
   The $45,000 study, paid for by the beef industry and USDA,
showed that the average thickness of fat on steaks and roasts from
primal cuts, or the major wholesale cuts of beef, was 0.14 inch,
while the average for all cuts, from chuck roast to stew meat, was
0.11 inch, or less than one-eighth of an inch.
   Most retailers have been using a quarter-inch beef fat trim, or
less, since 1985, compared with a standard of half an inch before
that, according to the industry.
   At the conference, Cross said consumers have indicated they
would pay for more closely trimmed beef, preferably with external
fat of less than one-eighth inch.
   Internal fat, or marbling, has been a factor in the taste of
beef, and Cross said this still is important to consumers. The
challenge, he said, is take fat off, not out of beef.
   Cross said that Texas A&amp;M meat scientists are currently working
with human medicine researchers at Baylor College of Medicine and
the University of Texas Southwestern Medical Center on projects
aimed at further improvements in the healthfulness of beef.
   The work includes modification of the fatty acid content of meat
product through changes in cattle feeds and products themselves.
Fatty acids can potentially elevate cholesterol levels in human
blood. But Cross said that even now, only 27 percent of the total
fat in beef is the type of saturated fatty acid that can raise
cholesterol.
   Savell told of recent research on the composition of cooked as
well as raw beef with reduced or no external fat. For example, if a
slice of beef with all the fat trimmed off is cooked, the fat
content of the interior meat is reduced by 20 percent from a slice
with a quarter-inch layer of fat.
   That is because less fat migrates from the outside into the meat
tissue.
   ``When you trim the fat off a steak that has a half inch of fat,
you get rid of half the total cholesterol,'' Savell said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0139 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1639EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0645 04-06 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0645,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Collapses With Shelling Duels In Beirut</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with church reported hit. Pickup
5th pvs, ``A police ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners dueled with
mortars and rockets across Beirut on Thursday, shattering a
short-lived cease-fire and forcing panicked civilians back to
basements and bunkers.
   Gen. Michel Aoun's Christian army claimed its troops held their
fire.
   Police said 15 people were wounded, bringing the toll to 177
people killed and 591 wounded since March 8, when Christian troops
clashed with an alliance of Syrian army and Druse militia forces.
   Police said Syrian gunners fired 50 rockets and mortar rounds
against the Christian enclave east and northeast of Beirut,
starting 11{ hours after the cease-fire was called at midnight.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified in line with
standing rules, said a dozen mortar rounds fired from east Beirut
slammed into residential districts of Moslem west Beirut.
   One Soviet-designed Grad rocket struck the Greek Orthodox church
of St Nicholas in the Ashrafiyeh district, destroying its
furnishings. The church was empty when hit, the spokesman said.
   Christian-controlled television showed rescuers trying to
salvage icons and other valuable objects from heaps of rubble in
the church, built in the 19th century.
   A police spokesman said the Christians kept the peace for nearly
three hours after the bombardment began. Then west Beirut was
shelled from ``emplacements in (Christian) east Beirut.''
   ``It is difficult to say who mans the guns: the army or the
Lebanese (Christian militia) Forces,'' said the spokesman, who
customarily is not identified by name.
   A telephone operator at Lebanese Forces headquarters said
spokesman George Abdelmasih was not available to answer questions.
   Aoun's spokesman insisted, ``The army is not responding to the
Syrian provocation.''
   Thursday's truce was called by Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheik
Sabah Ahmed Sabah, who heads a six-nation Arab League committee on
Lebanon.
   ``We appeal to all the warring Lebanese parties to observe a
cease-fire as of midnight Wednesday,'' Sabah said in Damascus,
Syria, where he met Thursday with President Hafez Assad.
   Sabah left for home later, saying he had not heard from Aoun but
thought the cease-fire was accepted by most Lebanese leaders.
   As the deadly duel resumed, civilians who had emerged from bomb
shelters to stockpile food and assess damage rushed for refuge in
building entrances.
   Several motorists in the crowded Christian suburb of Dora
deserted their vehicles. Others honked their horns hysterically,
racing their cars in all directions and causing several accidents.
   Vendors in Moslem west Beirut scurried away from their
vegetables stands in Ein Mirreiseh district as mortars exploded
nearby.
   ``Peace didn't last for long. This is God's wrath at us,'' said
a woman carrying bread. She hurried along west Beirut's Hamra
street as shopkeepers lowered their shutters.
   The latest violence erupted after Aoun blockaded illegal
militia-run ports to reinstate tax collection worth $100 million a
year at government harbors along Lebanon's 130-mile Mediterranean
coast.
   In retaliation, militiamen of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt and
their Syrian allies besieged the 310-square-mile Christian enclave
northeast of the capital.
   Aoun, who also leads the Christian Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, has demanded Syria be a full party to a cease-fire,
claiming its soldiers are the main adversary to his 20,000 troops.
Syria keeps 40,000 troops in Lebanon under an Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk Sharaa said in Damascus that
Syria is ``strongly boosting'' the Arab League's cease-fire appeal.
   ``Syria maintains and supports this appeal ... for our Lebanese
brothers to accept a cease-fire and lift the siege,'' he said.
   Acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss, who heads Lebanon's pro-Syrian
Moslem Cabinet, welcomed the cease-fire and urged ``all sides to
comply with the proposed truce out of mercy for the battered
population.''
   Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, does not control a militia and the
22,000-strong predominantly Moslem troops of Brig. Gen. Sami Khatib
have not been involved in the clashes.
   The dual government, which threatens to cement Lebanon's
partition into sectarian cantons, emerged last September after
parliament failed to elect a successor to outgoing President Amin
Gemayel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
