<FIRST>u w AM-US-Afghanistan     04-06 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Names Special Envoy to Afghan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, bowing to congressional
pressure, has chosen Peter Tomsen as a special envoy to the Afghan
rebels battling the Soviet-backed regime in Kabul, administration
sources said Thursday.
   Tomsen, the deputy chief of the U.S. Embassy in Beijing, has not
formally been selected, but sources who spoke on condition they not
be identified by name confirmed he was the choice of Bush and
Secretary of State James A. Baker III.
   The move stops short of offering formal recognition of the
Afghan government-in-exile, but it is seen as a means of broadening
U.S. influence among the long-feuding rebel factions and curbing
Paskistan's clout.
   The post carries the rank of ambassador. Tomsen will be based in
Washington and travel frequently to the region, said an
administration official who spoke on the condition he not be
identified. The name has not formally been announced because it
``hasn't been put through all the administrative hoops yet,'' said
the official.
   The move drew immediate criticism from the Soviet Union. In
Moscow, Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh accused the
United States of ``plans to break off relations with the Afghan
government'' and preparing to recognize a ``self-imposed
government.''
   ``The United States does not want to extinguish the flames in
Afghanistan. They make every effort to topple the government in
Afghanistan,'' Gremitskikh said, repeating Soviet charges that the
administration was failing to uphold the Geneva accords that
oversaw the withdrawal of Soviet troops in February.
   The United States closed its embassy in Kabul several weeks ago,
as the situation in the city deteriorated after the Soviet pullout.
Formal diplomatic ties were not broken, however.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler, who confirmed
the decision about the envoy had been named but refused to identify
him, said the move did not entail a recognition of the rebel's
government-in-exile or establish diplomatic relations with it.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., who pushed a law through Congress
last year requiring the appointment of such a special ambassador,
said he was ``elated'' by the reported decision.
   Humphrey acknowledged that he had backed an Afghan-born Rand
Corp. scholar for the post, Zalmy Khalilzad, who is now a U.S.
citizen, for the job. Khalilzad speaks Afghanistan's two languages,
Dari and Pashtu, which Tomsen does not.
   But the senator said he was pleased that the administration
appeared to be moving toward developing policy for dealing with the
fluid situation in Afghanistan and he hoped the move was a step
toward the eventual recognition
   ``It does raise the credibility of the resistance,'' he said.
   The senator argued that the high-level posting was needed to
curb Pakistan's influence over the rebels, now that the Soviet
troops have withdrawn from Afghanistan and the insurgents are
battling the Kabul regime.
   ``Pakistan's goals _ whatever they are in the region _ may not
wholly be in agreement with our own. The United States needs to
take some new initiative ... we need a policy with momentum ,''
Humphrey said in a telephone interview.
   The United States has funneled support to the rebels through
Pakistan, which has continued to back radical Moslem fundamentalist
rebels over more moderate factions.
   Some U.S. officials have privately expressed concerns about
powerful resistance leaders who advocate restructuring Afghan
society along strict Islamic fundamentalist lines.
</TEXT>
