<FIRST>u i AM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru a0656 04-06 0904</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0656,0924</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ban on Solidarity to be Lifted Immediately</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, ``The agreement ...'' with 2 grafs with more
on registration.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government minister said Thursday the
seven-year ban on Solidarity would be lifted immediately, and Lech
Walesa urged supporters to put their ``political victory'' into
action by organizing nationwide.
   ``The process of legalization of Solidarity should be completed
between April 15 and April 20,'' said Sports Minister Aleksander
Kwasniewski, a chief negotiator for the communist government in two
months of talks with the opposition that concluded Wednesday in a
broad accord.
   Kwasniewski said the Sejm, or parliament, would meet Friday to
enact the agreements on trade union freedoms, economic reforms and
political changes, including creation of the first freely elected
legislative body in the East bloc.
   Walesa, looking relaxed at a news conference after a grueling
week of negotiations, outlined the tasks his independent trade
union faces. But he warned the agreement could lead to disaster if
Poland failed to take advantage of the changes.
   ``The most important task for today is to write applications
immediately all over the country to provincial governors and city
mayors so we get the technical possibility to organize as soon as
possible,'' Walesa said.
   The agreement allows Solidarity to organize on a national,
regional and local level after parliament makes the necessary
changes in the labor law to permit more than one legal trade union
at a workplace.
   On the national level, the union plans to form an organizing
committee as early as this weekend to apply for formal registration
by submitting a new union charter in court, said top Solidarity
adviser Tadeusz Mazowiecki.
   ``Today we as Poland have a great victory, but a political
victory _ a theoretical one which may turn out to be a victory or a
disaster if we are not able to make use of it,'' Walesa said.
   ``If we are not able to work in the economic field to have more,
produce more and better and in the political field to represent
ourselves well ... nice slogans will only stay slogans,'' Walesa
said.
   The government daily Rzeczpospolita called the agreements sealed
by Walesa and Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak, the interior minister, a
breakthrough that created a chance that must not be wasted by
``false solutions, sham ambitions or ignorance of realities.''
   Stanislaw Ciosek, a Politburo member and participant in the
talks, said the agreement was a step toward reforms undertaken by
the Communist Party, but it would not solve all of Poland's
problems.
   ``These reforms have made the prospect of satisfying the working
class much closer,'' Ciosek said. ``In spite of what I said before,
one should not expect that the agreement reached should eliminate
all concerns and troubles.''
   Walesa appeared unconcerned by the apparent lack of reaction by
Poles to the restoration of the Soviet bloc's first independent
trade union, which claimed 10 million members and ignited that
nation's spirit during its 16-month legal existence before being
crushed under martial law in December 1981.
   ``I went on the hotel balcony today and watched people's
behavior. I met with great sympathy, almost everyone waved, but
also with a lot of doubt,'' Walesa said.
   He said the union had trouble before with expectations that were
too high, so today's skepticism is good.
   Walesa said he expected Solidarity to attract 5 million to 7
million members, but that he would like to see at least three
competing trade unions.
   Walesa and his advisers have said the shift in the attitude of
the Polish leadership toward Solidarity is partially due to changes
in the political climate in the Soviet Union.
   Walesa said he would like to see what is happening in the Soviet
Union for himself and added: ``I would not like to disturb
perestroika and reforms. That country is reforming itself as far as
we hear. ... We want to solve our (problems) and not disturb
others.''
   He later flew to his home in the port city of Gdansk, where
Solidarity was founded, and told reporters the union would like to
use the Monopol Hotel in Warsaw as its national headquarters.
   Kwasniewski said the government had urged local and regional
authorities to support the registration process of new unions and
provide them with office space.
   Authorities proposed the talks in August during the year's
second nationwide wave of strikes. When work stoppages appeared
again this year, Walesa appealed for calm to give the negotiations
a chance.
   Both sides have expressed hope the solutions reached at the
talks that began Feb. 6 will repair the economy and revive the
dispirited population.
   In addition to Solidarity, authorities agreed to restore legal
status to the farmers' union Rural Solidarity and the Independent
Students Association, all banned during martial law.
   In exchange, the opposition agreed to participate in June
elections to the 460-member Sejm that guarantee the Communist Party
and its allies a 65 percent majority.
   But at the same time, Poland will have its first democratic
elections since World War II, creating a new 100-member Senate.
   A presidency also will be created, to be elected by the Sejm and
the senate. The president would be elected this year for a six-year
term and the post is expected to go to Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski,
the Communist Party leader, due to his party's dominance in the
larger Sejm.
</TEXT>
