<FIRST>r w AM-Hepburn-UNICEF     04-06 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hepburn-UNICEF,250</SECOND>
<HEAD>3rd World Debt Falls Heavily on Children, Actress Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Third-world debt is imposing its heaviest
burden on millions of children whose countries are cutting social
programs to keep up payments loans from foreign banks, actress
Audrey Hepburn told Congress Thursday.
   Accompanying declining spending by developing countries for
health and education is a more alarming statistic, she said: the
average weight-for-age figure is falling in many of the countries.
   ``In other words, ... the children of the developing world are
paying for the Third World's $1.3 billion debt with their health,
education and even their lives,'' she told the House Appropriations
foreign operations subcommittee.
   ``At least half a million young children have died in the last
12 months as a result of the slowing down or reversal of progress
in the developing world,'' said Hepburn, who is a ``goodwill
ambassador'' for the United Nations Children's Fund.
   UNICEF, she said, is able to use its implicit trust to help
alleviate those conditions in places such as the drought-stricken
Sudan, where aid to starving people has been stalled because of a
civil war.
   ``Everybody trusts you because everybody loves a child,''
Hepburn said in response to a question from chairman David Obey,
D-Wis.
   ``It's something everybody has in common. ... Children may
eventually be the cause of peace in these countries. What they need
most is peace. But they can't wait and UNICEF is taking care of
them.''
   UNICEF is a perennial favorite on Capitol Hill, where lawmakers
have restored some $100 million in cuts proposed by the Reagan
administration over the last four years, according to the
subcommittee's figures.
</TEXT>
