<FIRST>u w AM-US-Poland     04-06 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Poland,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Seeks to Encourage Implementation of Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is preparing a package
of measures designed to encourage Poland's communist authorities to
implement democratic reforms they agreed to this week, officials
said Thursday.
   The package, to be announced as early as Friday, would include
economic and possibly political concessions to Poland, said two
administration officials who spoke on condition they not be
identified. They declined to give specifics.
   A Polish government spokesman said it was asking the United
States to give the green light to loans from the International
Monetary Fund, the World Bank and from other Western governments.
   ``What we want does not lie in the bilateral range of things,
not trade,'' said Polish Embassy spokesman Mierik Miernik.
   Poland's efforts to rebuild its shattered economy have been
hampered by an inflation rate of between 60 and 100 percent, and a
$39 billion foreign debt. The Polish government would like U.S.
support in persuading the Paris Club of bankers and governments to
reschedule repayment of the loans, Miernik said.
   Although the United States lifted the sanctions it imposed after
communist authorities declared martial law in Poland in 1981, it
has been pressuring Western banks and governments against extending
new credits to Warsaw, he said.
   Forty congressmen have also urged the administration to
influence the IMF, World Bank and Paris Club to relieve debt
pressure on Poland.
   The congressmen, including House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho of
California and Republican Whip Newt Gingrich of Georgia, said that
with the reforms in place, ``Poland should maintain a primary
position on America's foreign policy agenda.''
   ``Now that Poland seems on the threshold of monumental reform,
the struggle of the Polish people should not slip down on our list
of priorities,'' said the letter initiated by Rep. William O.
Lipinski, D-Ill.
   One step might be allowing the government's Overseas Private
Investment Corporation to insure investments by Americans in Polish
agriculture or other economic enterprises, said an aide to Lipinski.
   State Department and White House officials have been preparing a
package of conciliatory measures for several weeks, with an eye to
negotiations involving Poland's communist authorities, Solidarity
leader Lech Walesa, representatives of the Roman Catholic church
and others.
   Walesa and Interior Minister Gen. Czeslaw Kiszczak concluded the
talks and announced the accords on Wednesday. They include the
first free elections since the communists took over Poland after
World War II and legalization of the Solidarity trade union after
eight years of suppression.
   State Department analysts, who have scrutinized the agreement,
said they were impressed its constitutional provisions.
   It creates a strong presidency, recreates an upper house of
parliament, and eliminates over time the communists' guaranteed
majority in the lower house of parliament, meaning they ultimately
could lose control of the country, said a State Department analyst
who asked not to be identified.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Wednesday that
President Bush hailed the ``accords that have started Poland on
this new path of reconciliation.''
   ``We feel very confident about the process that is under way in
Poland,'' Fitzwater said. ``Now that we have these accords, we are
considering issues or moves that might be taken which would, in
various ways, foster economic development and help move that
process forward.''
</TEXT>
