<FIRST>r w AM-Drought-Wheat     04-06 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Wheat,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>USDA Says It's Too Early For Drought Relief For Winter Wheat Growers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY MASSEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite pleas for help from Congress, the
Agriculture Department said Thursday it was too early to advance a
new drought relief package to aid winter wheat growers facing
potential losses from dry weather and temperature extremes.
   ``We don't know there is going to be a widespread disaster,''
Ewen M. Wilson, USDA's assistant secretary for economics, told a
House Agriculture subcommittee.
   Frustrated by the wait-and-see approach, a Kansas lawmaker
introduced legislation to extend drought assistance approved last
year by Congress to farmers of winter wheat planted in 1988.
   ``It is my people. We are suffering. We were able to work with
corn country last year. It is our time,'' said Rep. Pat Roberts,
R-Kan., who represents a 58-county district considered one of the
prime wheat-growing regions in the nation.
   According to USDA, the winter wheat outlook is bleak in Kansas,
traditionally the nation's largest producer. At the start of the
month, 70 percent of the Kansas wheat crop was rated poor to very
poor. Kansas normally accounts for 17 percent of total U.S. wheat
production and 35 percent of the nation's hard red winter wheat,
the main bread wheat.
   In testimony to the wheat, soybeans and feed grains
subcommittee, USDA officials conceded that drought could sharply
reduce harvests in portions of the major winter wheat states of
Kansas, Oklahoma, Texas, Nebraska and Colorado. However, they held
hope that spring rains could rescue part of the crop.
   Norton Strommen, USDA's chief meterologist, said the next 30 to
60 days will be critical. He said the 90-day weather outlook
suggested near-normal rainfall in much of the Wheat Belt across the
the Great Plains, although below normal rainfall is expected in the
short term.
   Because the winter wheat crop is developing later than usual
this year, Strommen said, ``we have a mixed picture.''
   ``It's just a little premature to start to write the crop down
to any specific level,'' said Strommen. ``We simply have to watch
and wait for the development and the timing and distribution of
rainfall in the next two months.''
   Lawmakers unsuccessfully pressed USDA to support a new
legislative relief package or extending the 1988 drought assistance
programs to the 1989 wheat crop.
   Wilson said USDA ``doesn't want to do anything precipitous.''
   ``We will have to monitor the situation and see if it rains and
see how bad it is,'' he said.
   For the major winter wheat states, Wilson said, 31 percent of
the overall crop was rated poor to very poor compared to 8 percent
last year at this time.
   According to a ``highly tentative'' projection by USDA, total
1989 wheat production could be about 2.45 billion bushels, a 35
percent boost from last year's drought-reduced harvest.
   At the hearing, John Schnittker, a private agricultural analyst,
estimated a harvest of 2.25-2.3 billion bushels. He warned that a
poor U.S. winter wheat crop would drastically shrink already small
grain stockpiles and pose ``a serious threat to world food
sufficiency and price stability.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
