<FIRST>r w AM-US-Salvador     04-06 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Salvador,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Makes Demands of Victorious Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of Salvadoran rebels
challenged the newly elected Arena party Thursday to declare its
administration a ``government of transition'' or face a deepening
of the nine-year-old war in the Central American country.
   Guadelupe Gonzales of the leftist Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front said the proposal was being announced in
Washington because president-elect Alfredo Cristiani is here for
talks with U.S. officials.
   Francisco Altschul, a representative of the political opposition
commission of the rebel group, said the proposal was presented
Thursday to representatives of Arena and other Salvadoran factions.
   He said he knew of no response.
   Cristiani has a news conference scheduled Friday morning and
will meet with President Bush in the afternoon.
   Asked what would happen if Arena rejects the proposal, Altschul
said, ``We hope it is not rejected. Unless there is a negotiated
settlement of the war, there is only going to be an ungovernable
country; there is only going to be a deepening of the war.''
   Meanwhile in San Salvador the leftist guerrillas attacked the
4th Army brigade headquarters and the headquarters of army
engineers, authorities said. Three soldiers and three guerrillas
were reported killed and 10 people wounded.
   More than 70,000 Salvadorans, most of them civilians, have been
killed during the nine-year war against the U.S.-supported
government.
   The rebels have stepped up attacks recently to protest the
election of Cristiani, a right-wing businessman who was the
candidate of Arena, in an election March 9. Cristiani is scheduled
to take office June 1.
   Altschul told reporters that Arena, named for its initials in
Spanish, ``has made it very clear that it will follow a policy of
massacres and total war and has given no indication of a serious
disposition toward peace.''
   He said the rebels would seek a response from Arena to demands
that it stop assassinations, respect nationalization of banks and
other steps taken by its predecessors and abandon its insistence
that the guerrillas surrender.
   He said this would be ``a first step to start serious
negotiations.''
   ``In order to resolve the problem of the war in a definitive
manner, it is necessary to revise the constitution and for the
future Arena government to declare itself a government of
transition,'' the proposal said.
   It called for elections in which the army would be confined to
barracks and the rebel military forces also kept away from voting
places for three days before, during and after the voting.
   It called for the rebel faction to ``participate directly as a
political force in these elections with our flag and in coalition
with other parties which may be disposed to participate together
with us.''
   It said that commanders and officers implicated in ``political
crimes and massacres which have been causes of the war'' must be
brought to justice.
   The rebels also demanded that U.S. aid be cut off and U.S.
advisors withdrawn.
   Elections would be held within six months after initiation of a
cease fire.
</TEXT>
