<FIRST>u w AM-OilSpill-Congress Bjt   04-06 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill-Congress, Bjt,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush May Order Military to Help Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush may order the military to help
in the long-term cleanup of the massive oil spill in Alaska, it was
disclosed Thursday as the administration underscored its opposition
to a federal takeover of the operation.
   ``There's a lot of military already in Alaska,'' White House
Press Secretary Marlin Fitzwater said, adding that those troops
were the most likely to be tapped.
   Fitzwater said Alaska's congressional delegation had asked
officials to consider using the military _ ``and we are.'' He said
the armed forces could help in washing oil from animals and birds
plus cleaning up rocks and shorelines and then continue in the
long-term effort.
   Asked when the military might begin the work, Fitzwater said,
``Beginning about now.'' He said a final decision was still
pending. ``The concern is, we need a comprehensive way to deal with
this continuing and long-term cleanup.''
   The White House is under pressure to take charge of cleaning up
the largest oil spill in U.S. history.
   ``We've got to have federal control now,'' Sen. Ted Stevens,
R-Alaska, told Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner at the first
of several congressional hearings on efforts to deal with the
nation's worst oil tanker disaster.
   While Stevens was joined by other senators who suggested that
the president order a greater federal involvement in the cleanup in
Alaska's Prince William Sound, Skinner and Admiral Paul Yost, the
commandant of the U.S. Coast Guard, cautioned against turning
control of the effort over to the federal government.
   ``I am not prepared to federalize this spill,'' Yost told the
Senate Commerce Committee, adding that such a move might leave an
opening for Exxon ``to close their checkbook'' and force the
government to assume cleanup costs.
   He said the Coast Guard has just $3 million or so in the fund
that would be used for such a task, only enough for a few days.
   That concern was not shared by Stevens, who said that the
government could still tap an industry disaster fund of up to $100
million to cover the costs and that Exxon likely would not be
relieved of liabilities in any event.
   Nevertheless, Yost said the Coast Guard was planning to assume
greater direction over Exxon Corp. in deciding how to go about the
cleanup, what equipment to use and what the priorities should be.
   ``We're going to do much more coordination and guidance,'' Yost
said, acknowledging that Alaska Gov. Steve Cowper had asked for
greater Coast Guard involvement in a letter received Monday night.
   L.G. Rawls, chairman of Exxon Corp., told the Senate panel that
the petroleum giant ``will continue doing all we can to clean up
and mitigate the spill's effects.''
   ``We're chasing the oil. We're doing what we can,'' said the
Exxon chief executive.
   Meanwhile, a group of Republican congressmen said Bush should
become more directly involved in the matter and put a federal
agency in overall charge of the effort.
   At a news conference called by the House Republican Research
Committee, Rep. Jim Saxton of New Jersey said he has received
offers from people willing to travel to Alaska to help, but has not
found any government agency that can provide information on what
steps such volunteers should take.
   While the debate continued on what steps need to be taken to
protect wildlife, fish and the ecology of Prince William Sound,
officials agreed the early response to the March 24 accident in
which the Exxon Valdez supertanker ran aground, spilling more than
10 million gallons of oil, was largely bungled and probably was
inadequate even if events had run more smoothly.
   William Reilly, administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency, told the Senate panel the petroleum industry's emergency
reaction plan and the environmental impact analysis in connection
with the Alaskan pipeline did not contemplate such a massive spill.
   Skinner said that while all is being done now that can be done
to deal with the spill, the response on the first two days after
the accident was inadequate. ``They hadn't planned for a catstrophe
of this magnitude,'' he told the senators.
   The contingency plan, for example, called for booms to be put
around the stricken tanker within five hours, but the booms were
not in place until 12 hours after the accident and then did not
hold because of strong winds, Yost said.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said the basic response plan was
faulty, noting that when it was developed the largest oil spill
anticipated was 74,000 barrels. The oil that gushed from the Exxon
Valdez was more than three times that amount and came out at a rate
of 50,000 barrels an hour, according to administration officials.
</TEXT>
