<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-MoscowReax     04-06 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Moscow Reax,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Media Praise Visit to London, Twit the British</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Gorbachev Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet media painted a generally glowing picture
Thursday of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's first day in London,
but twitted his British hosts on a few points.
   The nightly news program ``Vremya'' devoted more than 20 minutes
to the visit and reported no disagreement with Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher beyond Gorbachev's friendly correction of her
estimate of how long they had talked.
   A commentary in the government newspaper Izvestia, however,
combined praise for Mrs. Thatcher's recent statement that the Cold
War is over with a review of issues that remain in contention.
   Columnists A. Krivopalov and M. Sturua wrote that each side
questions the other's performance on human rights.
   They said Izvestia's London bureau frequently has its attention
called to British conduct in Northern Ireland and to allegedly
unjust convictions by British courts.
   Krivopalov and Sturua accused Sir Geoffrey Howe, the British
foreign secretary, of ``playing political games.''
   On the 40th anniversary of the NATO, they wrote, Howe ``allowed
himself remarks which clearly carry the flavor of the old days. He
once again spoke about `the Russian bear,' which he said represents
a military threat to the West.''
   In truth, they declared, recent polls indicate most Britons
perceive the Soviet threat as much smaller since Gorbachev came to
power in 1985.
   Izvestia also said the growth of British-Soviet trade ``is
restrained by discriminatory measures introduced by the British
authorities on various Soviet products, by the ban on export to the
U.S.S.R. of contemporary industrial equipment and the newest
technology.''
   Accompanying the complaint was an acknowledgment that the
lethargic and ponderous Soviet financial system also is at fault.
   Despite their differences, Britain and the Soviet Union are part
of a growing consensus that Europe must coalesce into ``one general
European home,'' the paper said, and expressed hope the
Gorbachev-Thatcher meeting would bring progress toward that goal.
   Reports on state television and by the official news agency Tass
covered the visit in detail, from the landing at Heathrow Airport
to a visit by the Soviet leader's wife Raisa to Saint Paul's
Cathedral.
   Tass described Westminster Abbey, which Gorbachev toured
Thursday afternoon, as ``a positive jewel of ancient English
culture.''
   In a report on his stop at a communications firm that does
business with the Soviet Union, the agency said ``British people
are not yet satisfied'' with the rate of growth in trade between
the two countries.
</TEXT>
