<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-DrugTesting     04-06 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Drug Testing,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Terminal Operator To Require Drug-Alcohol Testing On Tankers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operator of the trans-Alaska oil
pipeline terminal announced Thursday that it will immediately
require random drug and alcohol testing on all vessels using the
terminal.
   The action was one of several announced by Alyeska Pipeline
Service Co., a consortium of seven oil companies that owns and
operates the Valdez terminal and the 800-mile pipeline. Alyeska has
been criticized for its slow response to the nation's worst oil
spill.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez took on a load at Valdez on March 24 and
hours later ran aground, releasing more than 10 million gallons of
crude oil into Prince William Sound. The ship's captain, Joseph
Hazelwood, is charged with operating the vessel while drunk.
   Alyeska said in a news release that it would require tanker
owners and operators to institute random drug and alcohol testing.
It also said it would require tugboat escorts for all entering and
departing vessels to a point beyond Bligh Reef, where the Exxon
Valdez ran aground.
   The state this week drafted an emergency order that, if signed,
would require Alyeska immediately to take several steps to correct
problems with its oil-spill response program. Some of those steps,
including the purchase of additional booms, dispersants and other
cleanup equipment, were included in Alyeska's announcement Thursday.
   Dennis Kelso, commissioner of the state Department of
Environmental Conservation, was expected to sign the order, Deputy
Commissioner Amy Kyle said.
   The draft order sharply criticizes Alyeska's initial response to
the spill, saying it failed to comply with its spill contingency
plan and took too long to deploy equipment. The order says
``continued operation of Alyeska's marine terminal and tanker
traffic at the current crude-oil flow rate creates a substantial
risk of an additional oil spill'' in the sound.
   Alyeska said a task force of oil company officials will make
additional recommendations to improve spill response.
   ``We sincerely regret the environmental tragedy in Prince
William Sound and pledge to do everything feasible to prevent
another such accident from happening,'' the news release said. ``A
painful lesson has been learned.''
</TEXT>
