<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2303EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GrainSales     04-06 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain Sales,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy Corn; Chinese, Wheat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has bought more U.S. corn and
China has been sold wheat at subsidized prices, the Agriculture
Department said Thursday.
   Officials said that the Soviet purchase was for 400,000 metric
tons of corn to be delivered this year and that the wheat sale to
China was for 300,000 tons. Both deliveries are scheduled for this
year.
   More than 2.7 million tons have been purchased since the Soviets
rsumed buying U.S. corn on March 28 after a layoff of almost three
months.
   The latest sales brought total corn sold to the Soviets for
1988-89 to almost 13 million tons. Additionally, sales include 4
million tons of wheat, 450,000 tons of soybeans, 1.4 million tons
of soybean meal and 507,400 tons of grain sorghum.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 400,000 tons of
corn woud be about 15.8 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.45 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the latest USDA five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $39 million.
   John J. Reddington, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the wheat was part
of 2 million tons authorized Feb. 27 for China under the Export
Enhancement Program, or EEP.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices to meet foreign competition in
selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   The latest sale boosted to about 8.5 million tons the amount of
wheat sold to China for 1988-89 delivery under EEP.
   Reddington said the latest sales were handled by Garnac Grain
Co. Inc., 50,000 tons; Bunge Corp., 50,000; Bartlett and Co.,
100,000, and Continental Grain Co., 100,000.
   He said the wheat will carry an average subsidy rate of $6.33
per ton, or about 17 cents a bushel. About 910,000 tons are still
available under the current authorization.
   The 300,000 tons of wheat would be about 11 million bushels and,
at recent prices of about $3.96 per bushel, would have a farm value
of around $44 million.
</TEXT>
