<DOCNO> AP890406-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2312EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-GasDecontrol     04-06 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gas Decontrol,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Endorses Ending Last Price Restraints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee voted Thursday to end the
remaining price controls on natural gas in 1993.
   A decade ago, the action of the energy and power subcommittee of
the House Energy and Commerce Committee would have followed battles
between consuming and producing states.
   Memories of those battles led Congress and its committees to
ignore the Reagan administration's almost annual requests for
removal of controls.
   Thursday, it took only 12{ minutes for the subcommittee to
approve, by voice vote and without dissent, the bill sponsored by
22 of its 23 members.
   A previous decontrol episode in 1985 saw prices collapse,
confounding predictions of a pocketbook-bashing ``fly-up'' of
prices. Many analysts now believe gas prices are determined by oil
prices because many industrial users can switch between the two.
   Most believe decontrol will have little immediate effect if
demand does not increase as ceiling prices frequently are well
above spot prices.
   The last major gas pricing battle in Congress came in 1978, when
harsh winters, diversion of gas into unregulated intrastate markets
and soaring oil prices all combined to curtail gas deliveries to
the Midwest and Northeast.
   To encourage new production, Congress enacted several different
prices for gas according to source, such as tight sands or very
deep wells, and permitted those prices to rise with inflation. It
also provided that much of that gas would be decontrolled in 1985,
as it was.
   But gas from existing wells was to remain under price controls.
That gas is a smaller percentage of the supply every year and today
is 25 percent to 30 percent of gas flowing through pipelines,
according to the Natural Gas Supply Association.
   Since 1985, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission has
declared that the ceiling price of certain gas could rise to the
price of the most expensive category.
   That ceiling price, which rises with inflation, is now $2.79 per
thousand cubic feet. The March average spot price in major
producing states, according to the newsletter Natural Gas
Intelligence, was $1.44. Some old gas is sold for 30 cents.
   The bill does not abrogate contracts. Some contracts provide for
market pricing under decontrol but others do not.
</TEXT>
