<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-HazelwoodProfile     04-06 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazelwood Profile,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Best Known Member Of The Class Of '64</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronaut Hoot Wilson was the best-known
member of Huntington High School's class of '64 _ until Capt.
Joseph J. Hazelwood was fired and then arrested for his role in the
nation's biggest oil spill.
   Hazelwood, 42, released Thursday on $25,000 bail, is accused of
being drunk on March 24 when his ship, the Exxon Valdez, ripped its
bottom open and ran aground just 25 miles from Valdez, Alaska,
pouring more than 10 million gallons of crude oil into Prince
William Sound.
   Although Hazelwood had problems with alcohol, his life was
otherwise as obscure as those of his other high school classmates.
   ``He wasn't a wild kid. He was never in any trouble,'' Stuart
Lifson, a member of the class of '64, told Newsday. ``He is a very
inconspicuous person.''
   Hazelwood was raised in Huntington, a Long Island suburb, and
still lives there with his wife and their daughter. He was one of
four children; his father was a captain for Pan American World
Airways.
   During high school, Hazelwood participated in gymnastics and
tennis.
   After graduation, he went to Maritime College and left as a deck
officer on June 5, 1968. Soon after, he began a career with Exxon.
   By the time he was 31, Hazelwood had already received his
master's license, permitting him to run a ship of any size.
   At the time of the oil spill, Hazelwood was one of the youngest
captains in the merchant marine, running one of Exxon's newest
tankers. After the spill, Exxon fired him.
   Ironically, while he held a lofty position on the water,
Hazelwood was barred from driving a car because of a drunken
driving conviction.
   The first sign of his troubles with alcohol came on July 21,
1981, when Hazelwood was charged with driving while intoxicated and
leaving the scene of an accident. He later pleaded guilty and was
fined $510.
   Hazelwood was later sued by a seaman who alleged the captain had
abused him over a period of several years, court papers showed. The
lawsuit, still pending, does not detail the alleged abuse.
   In 1984, Hazelwood's driving license was revoked after he
refused a breath test following another car accident. He entered a
state-required rehabilitation program as part of his sentence in
that case.
   ``I do know that he had a problem with alcohol in the past. I
know he was rehabilitated. Exxon knows it,'' said his mother,
Margaret Hazelwood.
   His drivers license was restored in May 1986, but revoked again
after a September 1988 drunken driving conviction in North Conway,
N.H.
   Hazelwood is charged with operating a ship while drunk, reckless
endangerment and negligent discharge of oil. The misdemeanors carry
a maximum penalty of 2\ years in prison and a $10,000 fine upon
conviction.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
