<SECOND>AM-JDL-West Bank,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radicals Say They Will Send Units To Defend Settlers In West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Mideast, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Jewish radicals announced Thursday
it would send its members to the occupied West Bank to defend
Israeli settlers if Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir orders the
pullout of his troops from the territories.
   The Jewish Defense League said it had been getting calls from
settlers concerned that Shamir, under U.S. pressure, would agree to
pull Israeli troops out of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Shamir is reportedly considering pulling troops out of densely
populated Palestinian areas to ease the tensions that have fueled a
15-month Palestinian rebellion that has resulted in more than 400
Arab deaths.
   An estimated 70,000 Jews, many of them of American origin, live
in small settlements among the 1.3 million Palestinian inhabitants
of the territories. Israeli troops are charged with protecting the
settlers, although most of them also have their own weapons and
some have conducted vigilante activity against Palestinians.
   Michael Shlomich, who identified himself as the East Coast
coordinator for the JDL, said in a telephone call from Boston that
his organization ``will not allow the settlers to be slaughtered by
Arab mobs and terrorists.''
   He said the JDL, which in the 1960s and 1970s allegedly carried
out attacks on Arabs and Russians in the United States, would send
``highly trained people in riot control'' to protect the settlers
if the troops leave.
