<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2313EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-IsraelTrade     04-06 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Israel Trade,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Rejects American-Arab Suit, Upholds Trade Priviliges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. review panel has recommended upholding
Israel's trading privileges with the United States, rejecting a
suit filed by an Arab-American group, sources said Thursday.
   The ruling by the office of the U.S. Trade Representative has
been submitted to President Bush for his approval and an
announcement is expected next week, the agency said.
   A spokeswoman for the trade representative declined to discuss
the panel's findings, but other officials said a complaint filed
against Israeli labor practices by an the American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee last year had been rejected.
   The committee, which lobbies for the rights of Arab-Americans,
last year accused Israel of violating international labor and
union-protection laws for thousands of Palestinians who work in
Israel and in its occupied territories.
   According to U.S. law, Israel stood to lose trading privileges
it enjoys under the General System of Preferences, which grants
dozens of countries the right to export products to the United
States free of duties.
   The United States agreed to investigate the complaint, along
with petitions against Haiti, Liberia, Malaysia and Syria, and held
hearings late last year.
   The trade panel found that Israel had taken steps in recent
months to rectify some violations of workers' rights.
   The panel declined to rule on the complaint about Israeli
practices in the occupied West Bank and Gaza, citing U.S. policy of
not recognizing Israel's legal rights over the predominantly Arab
land, said another source who also spoke on condition of anonymity.
   That ruling was based on a recommendation from the State
Department's legal adviser, said the source.
   Abdeen Jabara, who heads the ADC, said that the very fact that
hearings were held on Israel's labor practices toward Palestinians
``was an important and positive thing because it raises the
consciousness of how Palestinians are treated by Israel.''
   He said the finding that some rights had been violated means
that Israel ``has not been given a clean bill of health.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
