<DOCNO> AP890406-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1804EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-MinorityFaculty     04-06 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minority Faculty,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Law Students Across Nation Protest Shortage Of Minority Faculty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT W. TROTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Students at law schools scattered around the country called a
strike Thursday to protest a lack of minority faculty members.
Fledgling lawyers at Harvard returned to an administration building
they occupied a year ago to renew their demands for faculty
diversity.
   The Harvard ``study-in'' was peaceful; about 125 students,
reading and talking quietly, filled a hallway in the main building.
   ``We've been getting a positive response,'' said Loretta
Martinez, 23, a second-year Harvard student and member of La
Alianza, a Hispanic students' organization. ``The message has
gotten across. There's more of a general awareness. But whether it
will be put into action remains to be seen.''
   At the Boalt Hall School of Law at the University of California,
Berkeley, about 75 students carried signs through halls reading
``This Is Not A White-only Club'' and ``Boycott Justice,''
prompting some professors to come out of their classrooms and
complain about the noise.
   Julie Derwinsky of the Coalition for a Diverse Faculty, based at
Berkeley, said the group mailed organizing materials about a month
ago to student organizations at several dozen schools.
   ``We hope that people realized that law students are concerned
about these issues, that we are all not conservative and hungry for
money,'' she said.
   She said she didn't know how many students participated in
Thursday's action.
   UCLA Law School communications director Ted Hulbert said about
100 students there attended a rally. A student claim that there
were only two minority faculty members was not correct, he said,
because three others are on the tenure track.
   University of California at Davis students scheduled a rally and
an afternoon boycott of classes. The 29-member faculty there has no
minority members.
   University spokesman David Ong said this is the first time in 15
years that there have been no minorities on the law school faculty.
One minority group member resigned unexpectedly last May; a second
turned down the university's offer, he said.
   In Austin, professors at the University of Texas Law School said
attendance Thursday was down between 20 percent and 25 percent, but
it wasn't clear how many students had cut class as part of the
protest.
   Texas Law School Dean Mark Yudof said the school has 54 tenured
or tenure-track faculty members. There are 46 men, two blacks, one
Asian-American, five women and no Hispanics.
   ``I think the students have called attention to a significant
problem at all American law schools,'' Yudof said.
   Kate Chesley, a spokeswoman at the University of Chicago Law
School, said about 20 students had congregated in a lounge and
discussed the situation as part of an ``Awareness Day.''
   At Harvard, students handed out fliers captioned ``Tenured
Hispanic Faculty'' depicting an empty picture frame. Dean James
Vorenberg, however, said the school has made ``great progress in
some areas of recruitment, particularly minorities and women.''
   In May, about 50 Harvard students, mostly black, held an
overnight vigil in Vorenberg's office and listed 12 demands. He
agreed to seven, including the establishment of a fellowship to
encourage blacks to teach there and a broader role for students in
finding prospective minority faculty members.
   Harvard Law School has 61 tenured faculty members; six are women
and three are blacks. There are two tenure-track professors who are
black.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
