<FIRST>r a AM-HudsonSuit     04-06 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hudson Suit,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor's Former Lover Takes Lie Detector Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lie detector test disproves claims by Rock
Hudson's estate that the late actor's homosexual lover had sex with
another man after filing a landmark AIDS lawsuit, an attorney
argued Thursday.
   Attorney Harold Rhoden said the test indicated his client, Marc
Christian, was being truthful when he denied having sex with
Gunther Fraulob, a singer and songwriter who came forward with
claims of an affair after a jury awarded Christian $21.75 million.
   An attorney for Hudson's estate, James Parker Mills, said
results of a lie detector test taken by Fraulob showed he too was
being truthful.
   Mills said Fraulob's test was taken before the estate filed
papers saying his evidence was relevant to the case.
   Mills, who had challenged Christian to take a similar test,
acknowledged that neither test was admissible in court and should
not be considered by Superior Court Judge Bruce Geernaert in
deciding whether to grant a new trial or to reduce the jury's award
to Christian, as requested by Hudson's estate.
   Both sides were in court Thursday for legal arguments on the
request. A hearing is scheduled for Friday.
   Jurors in February found that Hudson engaged in ``outrageous
conduct'' by concealing from Christian that he had AIDS. The
panelists, who had heard seven weeks of often lurid testimony about
the dead star's sex life, said Christian should receive $14.5
million in actual damages and $7.25 million in punitive damages.
   After the verdict, Fraulob of Laguna Niguel filed a sworn
statement claiming he had sex with Christian shortly after
Christian sued in November 1985. Christian contends he was so
traumatized that he has remained celibate since learning Hudson had
AIDS.
   The twist that made Christian's suit so unusual was that he did
not develop AIDS and has tested negative for the disease. In
previous lawsuits, only those who actually contracted a sexually
transmitted disease were able to win damages.
   Christian, 35, sued for emotional distress, saying he had lived
with the fear of coming down with the deadly disease since learning
in 1985 that the movie star had AIDS.
   Hudson, 58, died on Oct. 5, 1985, three months after the public
learned that he had the disease.
</TEXT>
