<FIRST>r w AM-Children'sTV     04-06 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children's TV,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Curb Amount of Commercials on TV Shows for Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in graf 11, bgng ``But Rep.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Backers of a bill to curb the amount of
commercials shown on TV shows for children said Thursday that
broadcasters have stepped up the pitches on such programs since ad
limits were lifted five years ago.
   Kids are being exposed to as much as 42 percent more toy, cereal
and candy advertising per hour than adults, as advertisers target
``a particularly vulnerable audience,'' Rep. Edward Markey,
D-Mass., told a House hearing.
   An independent station in Boston is inserting as many as 14
minutes of commericals into each hour of kids' shows, compared with
an average eight minutes for adult network programs, Markey told
the House Energy and Commerce telecommunications and finance
subcommittee that he chairs.
   ``We have a duty to see to it that this child audience is
protected from wave after wave of exploitive commercials,'' he said.
   Prior to 1984, when the Federal Communications Commission lifted
commercial limits on kids' TV shows, the amount of ads on network
children's programs was at or below the 9{ minute-per-hour rules
that the FCC had established in 1974, Markey said.
   Since 1984, ``commercial time has been on the rise, with
stations at two of the networks now offering as many as 11 minutes
per hour of commercial matter,'' he said.
   Markey said the government must stem ``endless streams'' of TV
commercials on children's shows because broadcasters are not
regulating themselves.
   But Glenn Wright, speaking for the National Association of
Broadcasters, said an NAB survey found children's programs
contained an average of about 8{ minutes of commerical time per
hour.
   He said that ``there does not appear to be a deluge of
commercials raining down upon the viewers of children's
programming.''
   Wright also said program-length commercials made by advertisers
have not done well. ``The child audience has made distinctions
between program content and commercial content and on its own has
avoided a deluge of commercials,'' he said.
   But Rep. Jim Slattery, D-Kan., said it was ``naive'' to think
the marketplace would regulate itself. He said money drives the
television business and that ``about 80 percent of network
programming is unmitigated crap.''
   Slattery said the networks weren't meeting their
responsibilities to children and the government should ``put as
much pressure as possible'' on them.
   Slattery said the bill will not affect responsible broadcasters
``one iota.''
   The bill would impose a limit of 10{ minutes of advertising per
hour on weekends and 12 minutes per hour on weekdays for kid's
shows. The legislation, written in cooperation with NAB and the
Association of Independent Television Stations, also would require
the FCC at license-renewal time to consider how well a broadcaster
has been committed to educational and informational needs of
children in its overall programming.
   Congress passed an identical bill last year but then-President
Reagan vetoed it on constitutional grounds.
   DeWitt Helm, president of the Association of National
Advertisers, told the subcommittee he also thought the measure was
unconstitutional and that less advertising might mean lower-quality
shows.
   ``Program producers must have the flexibility to determine how
best to balance the entertainment needs of the audience with the
financial requirements of good programming,'' Helm said.
</TEXT>
