<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2322EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-CheeseClaims     04-06 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cheese Claims,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Judge Finds Kraft Unintentionally Made False Claims for Cheese</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kraft Inc. unintentionally advertised falsely
that its Kraft Singles cheese slices contain as much calcium as
five ounces of milk and more than imitation cheese, according to a
ruling of a Federal Trade Commission administrative law judge
released Thursday.
   Kraft said it did not believe the ads were misleading and would
appeal the ruling to the full commission.
   One of the challenged ads said: ``Imitation slices use hardly
any milk. But Kraft has five ounces per slice. So her little bones
get calcium they need to grow.''
   The judge, Lewis F. Parker, said the ad implied that the slice
contained as much calcium as five ounces of milk and did not
mention that 30 percent of the calcium in the milk is lost in
processing.
   Also, he said, the ads can be taken as implying ``that imitation
slices which, they state, use hardly any milk, contain less calcium
than Kraft Singles.''
   In fact, almost all imitation and non-dairy cheese contains just
as much calcium as the real thing, he said.
   However, Kraft ``did not intend to make'' misrepresentations and
it was ``debatable'' whether the company should have known that
false claims could be inferred from the ads, he said.
   ``The advertisements ... were developed by Kraft in response to
the success of non-dairy imitation and substitute cheese slices,
and were not intended to convey express deceptive claims.''
   He ordered the company not to misrepresent the nutritional
content of its cheese slices in the future.
   In Glenview, Ill., company spokesman Gene Stevenson said Kraft
was pleased that the judge recognized ``there was no intent on the
part of Kraft to mislead the public.''
   ``Copy testing that we've done demonstrates that consumers do
not receive the implied message'' as stated in Parker's ruling,
Stevenson said.
   Kraft is ``confident that the integrity of the advertising will
be upheld'' by the commission, he said.
   Bruce Silverglade, attorney for Science in the Public Interest,
the advocacy group which asked the commission to look into the
matter in 1985, said he was pleased with the decision.
   ``It may represent a reawakening of the federal government to
problems of misleading health claims in food advertising,'' he said.
</TEXT>
