<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1845EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama     04-06 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sanctions Against Panama Extended 1 Year by Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush extended economic sanctions
against Panama for one year on Thursday, calling the government of
military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega ``corrupt, repressive and
inept.''
   In an executive order, Bush said that the ``actions and policies
of the (Noriega) regime in Panama continue to pose an unusual and
extraordinary threat to the national security and foreign policy of
the United States.''
   Sanctions put in place by the Reagan administration were to
expire on Saturday. Bush notified Congress he was retaining them
for an additional year.
   However, the sanctions could be modified depending on the
outcome of Panama's May 7 presidential election. ``After the
election, we'll take a look at the situation there and see if
there's any cause for change,'' said an administration official who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``If the Panamanian people have a chance to express their will
in a free and open manner, we're confident Noriega will go,'' said
the official. However, he conceced that prospects for a fair
election were uncertain in that Noriega appears likely to control
the process.
   The sanctions include sharp restrictions on U.S. companies that
do business in Panama, a hold on assets of the Panamanian
government in the United State and a prohibitation on tax payments
by U.S. organizations to the Noriega regime.
   ``The objective of administration policy remains support for a
return to civilian constitutional rule and the development of an
apolitical military establishment in Panama,'' Bush told Congress.
   ``Our judgment remains that the root cause of the current crisis
is the fact that the Panamanian people have lost confidence in a
political system widely perceived as corrupt, repressive and
inept.''
   Bush said he would keep the sanctions in place ``as long as
these measures are appropriate.'' They will automatically expire
April 8, 1990, unless he renews them again.
   Noriega, who is accused in a federal drug-running case in Miami,
has been the de facto ruler of Panama since February 1988, when he
orchestrated the ouster of President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   Delvalle had tried to fire Noriega as military leader after
Noriega was indicted in Florida on U.S. drug-trafficking charges.
Noriega denied the charges. Washington continues to recognize
Delvalle as president and imposed the sanctions against Panama in
an effort to force Noriega out.
   The Reagan administration cut off military and economic aid to
Panama in July 1987.
   The administration has amended the sanctions to permit U.S.
businesses with subsidiaries in Panama to pay amounts owed to the
government of Panama _ including taxes withheld from paychecks of
workers in Panama _ into escrow accounts in U.S. banks.
   Bush's message to Congress said that 170 U.S. companies with
subsidiaries in Panama are being notified by letter of these
changes.
   ``Information received from Panama indicates that certain U.S.
firms with operations in Panama may have faiiled to withhold
Panamanian taxes from employee paychecks in possible violation of
the regulations,'' Bush's statement said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
