<DOCNO> AP890406-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1846EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-S&amp;LWithdrawals     04-06 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-S&amp;L Withdrawals,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Customers Withdrew $9.4 Billion from Their Accounts in February</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-S&amp;Ls, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Savings and loan customers withdrew $9.4
billion from their accounts in February, down only slightly from a
record $10.6 billion in January, the government said Thursday.
   The $20 billion withdrawn during the first two months of this
year is more than double the $8.6 billion for all of last year and
puts new pressure on Congress to move swiftly as it begins writing
legislation to close or merge failed S&amp;Ls.
   James Barth, chief economist of the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board, attributed the outflow to the failure of S&amp;Ls to keep pace
with rising interest rates offered by competitors, chiefly money
market mutual funds.
   But, in recent weeks, top administration officials, including
Treasury Secretary Nicholas F. Brady, has been citing the outflow
as evidence of public nervousness that will persist until Congress
adopts President Bush's proposal to spend $50 billion over the next
three years to bail out the industry.
   February marks the 10th straight month of net withdrawals and
the fourth month of withdrawals in excess of $7 billion. Earlier,
from October 1987 though May of last year, billions of dollars
flowed into S&amp;Ls as stock market investors sought the safety of
federally insured accounts.
   Bert Ely, a financial institutions analyst in Alexandria, Va.,
said S&amp;Ls, as a substitute for deposits, were turning increasingly
toward advances from the Federal Home Loan Banks, a trend he called
disturbing.
   Although the 12 regional banks are controlled by the industry,
they borrow in financial markets and relend to S&amp;Ls at low
government-subsidized rates. Advances from the system have
increased by $15.8 billion from October to February.
   ``It disturbs me that the banks are being looked to so heavily
by the thrifts. It represents more and more of a growing government
involvement in the entire industry,'' Ely said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
