<DOCNO> AP890406-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2330EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     04-06 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Report Cites Danger of Guerrilla War In Kosovo Province</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal police report quoted in
the official press on Thursday expressed concern that some ethnic
Albanians could stage guerrilla warfare against federal authorities
in troubled Kosovo province.
   Bloody clashes between ethnic Albanians and security forces left
at least 24 people dead in Kosovo last week, including two
policemen, and 200 injured.
   Ethnic Albanians, who comprise about 85 percent of Kosovo's
population, took to the streets to protest constitutional changes
which they say limit the province's autonomy.
   The changes took effect March 28 and gave Yugoslavia's largest
republic of Serbia more control over Kosovo's judiciary, schools
and police.
   Some ethnic Albanians ``announced they would flee into the
woods'' which indicates Yugoslavia is faced with ``a danger of
separatist guerrilla warfare,'' the state-run Borba daily quoted
the police report as saying.
   According to the report, about 45,000 ethnic Albanians took part
in last week's riots in Kosovo. A state of emergency and curfews
were introduced there in a crackdown against the protests.
   Borba quoted a police officer as saying 16 major fires hit
forests and factories in the province since April 1, and described
the fires as ``terrorist diversions'' by ethnic Albanian
nationalists.
   The Vecernje Novosti newspaper said a major highway leading from
the provincial capital of Pristina to Urosevac was closed for more
than two hours Wednesday because ``unknown people tried to plant
explosives on the road.''
   A Kosovo police statement meanwhile confirmed unofficial reports
that two ethnic Albanian boys were killed on Wednesday.
   It said they were shot by another ethnic Albanian youth playing
with a rifle said to belong to a soldier guarding a military
observation post.
   The statement gave no other details. The incident reportedly
occurred in Malisevo village, about 25 miles southwest of Pristina.
   On the political front, media reports said Thursday that Serbia
rejected a public call for introducing democratic elections with
competing candidates and proposed its Communist Party chief,
Slobodan Milosevic, for the office of the republic's president.
   Serbia's Socialist Alliance, a Communist-run umbrella
organization, on Wednesday turned down a proposal that Milosevic,
the sole official candidate for president, be elected by public
ballot.
   Slovenia, Yugoslavia's most liberal republic, held its first
Western-style general elections last Sunday, featuring two
candidates and a secret ballot for its representative on the
country's collective presidency.
   Janez Drnovsek, a 38-year-old economist advocating closer ties
with the West, a market economy and cuts in the military budget,
was elected by 56 percent of the votes cast.
   He is to be inaugurated as Yugoslavia's next president on May
15, under the country's rotating system in which presidency members
take turns every year at the head of the state presidency.
   Slovenia has led the drive for more democracy in this
Communist-ruled state, and has allowed several non-communist, human
rights and political groups to function freely.
   Serbia, led by hardliner Milosevic, insists on the one-party
system as the main solution to the country's problems.
   ``We will choose (Milosevic) according to valid constitutional
norms,'' said Bogdan Trifunovic, head of the Serbian Socialist
Alliance, according to the Borba newspaper.
   Under the Yugoslav system, the Socialist Alliance in each of the
country's six republics and two provinces is in charge of
nominating candidates for government posts.
</TEXT>
