<DOCNO> AP890406-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2331EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     04-06 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Kill 24 Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil militants on Thursday blew up a
truck carrying Indian troops in northern Sri Lanka, killing at
least 18 of them, military officials said. Six more soldiers were
killed later in a gunbattle with the fleeing guerrillas, residents
said.
   Militants using remote controlled devices detonated explosives
buried in the road as the truck passed over it at Mankulam village,
26 miles north of Vavuniya town, military officials said. At least
five soldiers were injured, they said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   An official of the Indian High Commission, or embassy, in
Colombo said he was unaware of the killings.
   Indian troops, searching for the guerrillas, were ambushed by
the militants and six soldiers were killed in the ensuing gunbattle
at the nearby Maharambakulam village, said residents in Vavuniya
town, 135 miles north of Colombo.
   The residents, who were contacted by telephone, spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   The militants, believed to be members of the dominant Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam group, took away 15 rifles and a light
machine gun after blowing up the truck, officials said.
   India deployed nearly 50,000 troops after Tamil militants
spurned an India-sponsored peace accord signed in July 1987 and
aimed at ending a Tamil insurgency in the northern and eastern
provinces.
   At least 800 Indian soldiers have been killed in the operations
against the rebels, who refused to surrender their arms, saying the
accord did not meet enough of their demands for self rule.
   India sponsored the accord because of the sympathies of its own
60 million Tamils to the rebel cause.
   The 6-year-old Tamil secessionist war and a violent Sinhalese
backlash have claimed more than 12,500 lives.
   The latest violence came barely 24 hours after the government
announced a unilateral one-week cease-fire, beginning Tuesday.
   Foreign Minister Ranjan Wijeratne said Wednesday: ``It (the
cease-fire) will be a unilateral declaration by the government and
will cover military operations by both Sri Lanka and Indian armies
against Sinhalese and Tamil terrorists.''
   The government on Thursday also released 13 political prisoners
as part of a peace proposal offered to Tamils and Sinhalese
militants.
   After receiving a pardon from President Ranasinghe Premadasa,
the prisoners walked out of a maximum-security prison, about three
miles east of Colombo.
   The prisoners were Tamils convicted under anti-terrorist laws
and serving sentences ranging from five to 15 years, said
Velupillai Balakumar, the president of the Eelam Revolutionary
Organization, a Tamil group.
   Last week, Premadasa offered Tamil and Sinhalese militants
unconditional amnesty, seats in Parliament and money for
surrendered weapons if they stopped fighting.
   Neither Sinhalese militants nor the Tamil rebels have responded
positively to the peace overtures.
   On Wednesday, Sinhalese militants called a nationwide strike to
commemorate a failed uprising against the government 18 years ago.
The strike was viewed as a rejection of the peace offer.
   Meanwhile, two opposition leaders said the cease-fire
announcement would not be fruitful unless the government held
negotiations with extremist leaders.
   Sinhalese militants started the current campaign to bring down
the government after the July 1987 peace accord was signed, saying
it gave too many concessions to the minority community.
   The predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million people. Sinhalese Buddhists make up 75 percent
and control the government and the military.
   Tamil militants allege their community is discriminated against
by the Sinhalese in jobs and education.
</TEXT>
