<FIRST>r i AM-SikhKillings     04-06 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sikh Killings,0410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Extremists Kill 10 Including Five in One Family</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists burst into a farmhouse in
Punjab state and riddled the Sikh farmer and four members of his
family with automatic weapons fire as they slept, police reported
Thursday.
   News reports said five other people were killed in separate
incidents by Sikhs waging a terror campaign for an independent
nation in the northern agricultural region, the only Indian state
where the sect is in the majority.
   Ten gunmen entered the farmhouse in Kalchian village, 25 miles
from Amritsar, Wednesday night and opened fire with assault rifles,
said G.S. Mann, a senior police officer in the district.
   He identified those killed as 30-year-old Buta Singh; his father
Joginder Singh, 60; mother Charan Kaur, 55; brother Jarnail Singh,
32, and nephew Natha Singh, 26. He said Joginder Singh's
mother-in-law, Dalwant Kaur, was seriously wounded.
   ``The walls of the room were blood-splattered and the bodies lay
in pools of blood,'' Mann said.
   Most victims of the terrorists are Hindus, but they sometimes
kill Sikhs who do not support their cause.
   Buta Singh was among Sikhs detained in the June 1984 army raid
on Amritsar's Golden Temple, the holiest shrine of Sikhism, United
News of India reported. It said he was released with 137 others in
September 1988.
   The agency said Sikh extremists shot a village headman dead in
the Jalandhar district, 45 miles south of Amritsar, late Wednesday
and later hanged a Hindu priest in a nearby village.
   Another person was hanged Wednesday near Amritsar, bringing to
14 the number killed in that manner since two Sikhs were executed
by hanging Jan. 6 for the assassination of Prime Minister Indira
Gandhi in October 1984.
   She had ordered the raid on the Golden Temple with the purpose
of flushing out extremists who had turned the shrine into a
fortress. At least 1,200 people were killed in the raid.
   Militants began fighting for an independent Sikh homeland in
1982 and the violence has increased every year since. At least 510
people have been killed so far this year in Punjab and neighboring
Haryana state.
   Sikhs, whose faith is rooted in Hinduism and Islam, are only 2
percent of India's 880 million people, although they have a
majority in Punjab. They claim discrimination by Hindus, who make
up 90 percent of the population.
</TEXT>
