<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Libya     04-06 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Libya,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Soviet Confirms Jets to Libya, Denies They Threaten Neighbors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union confirmed Thursday that it
delivered fighter-bombers to Libya last month, but said they were
defensive aircraft and did not have the range to threaten Israel.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said the total
was ``around half a dozen,'' not 12 to 15 as claimed by U.S.
officials.
   The issue appeared to cast a shadow over the otherwise warm,
constructive tone of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's talks with
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   With Washington reports of the bomber sale capturing headlines
in Britain, Mrs. Thatcher asked Gorbachev for an explanation and
got none, her spokesman said.
   Her foreign secretary, Sir Geoffrey Howe, also raised the matter
with his Soviet counterpart, Eduard Shevardnadze, and Shevardnadze
responded by mentioning British arms sales to Saudi Arabia.
   Howe said his government was concerned because Libya is a
terrorist state, said the British spokesman, who spoke on condition
of anonymity.
   Gerasimov told a news conference he did not know about the sale,
but later went on television to confirm elements of the report
while seeking to minimize its significance.
   U.S. Defense Department sources have said the aircraft are SU-24
Fencers, which can fly within an 800-mile radius without refueling,
far enough to reach Egypt and even Israel from existing Libyan
airfields. They say the jets were shipped in crated pieces to the
Libyans aboard Soviet transport planes.
   In interviews on Channel 4 News and BBC-TV, Gerasimov said the
planes, whose type he did not specify, were supplied to Libya under
a 1986 agreement. He said it was ``an old contract,'' not more than
six were sold and they were shipped in pieces.
   ``This is not a long-range bomber,'' Gerasimov said. ``This is a
bomber that you can use for closer activities. Its operational
range is 300 miles.
   ``It's a front-line bomber,'' he added. ``It's for defense only.
You cannot really use it for offensive purposes.''
   The interviewer said the planes could refuel in midair and reach
Israel, to which Gerasimov replied: ``Theoretically maybe, but
Libya has no refueling capacity at all.''
   The sale comes at a time when the Soviet Union is trying to
improve relations with Israel as part of its effort to play a
greater role in Middle East peace efforts.
   Israel condemned the sale. ``We are surprised that the Soviet
Union, which states that it seeks to relieve situations of
confrontations around the world ... is supplying offensive
weaponry'' to Libya, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said, on
condition of anonymity.
   ``This will not add to stability in the Middle East,'' said
Foreign Minister Moshe Arens.
   On BBC television, Gerasimov said the planes were delivered in
March and suggested they would not be operational for some time
because they were delivered ``in crates. ... You must put them
together. It takes time and know-how to do it.''
   He said the sale to Libya ``is really small fry'' campared with
the British contract to sell Saudi Arabia billions of dollars worth
of Tornado fighter-bombers.
</TEXT>
