<FIRST>u a AM-Vietnam-Hospital     04-06 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vietnam-Hospital,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vets Who Built Clinic For Former Enemy Return To Happy Greetings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Vietnam veterans flew home from
Southeast Asia to a greeting of confetti, hugs and kisses Thursday
after building a 14-room clinic for their former enemies with
$50,000 in donated money.
   ``Boy, we didn't get a greeting like this when we came back from
the war,'' said Army veteran Steve Brooks of Santa Cruz, among the
six volunteers who returned to San Francisco International Airport
after nearly four months in Vietnam.
   The veterans, along with about 30 Vietnamese they paid $1 a day
each, erected a one-story, 2,500-square-foot building at Vung Tau,
some 60 miles from Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon.
   The veterans said they watched with pride Saturday while local
politicians made speeches under U.S. and Vietnamese flags in a
champagne-toasted ceremony to mark the finish of the project.
   The unusual mission left Richard Anderson feeling much better
about himself than he did after serving a year in Vietnam with the
Army Corps of Engineers.
   Anderson, 41, was the job foreman on what he and his buddies
called the ``Veterans Vietnam Restoration Project,'' an idea that
originated with a Veterans of Foreign Wars contingent at
Garberville, Calif.
   ``It was,'' he said, ``out of a sense of purpose, to do
something kind for the Vietnamese people,'' he said, but not
because he felt he had hurt them in the war.
   ``I don't lay that personal guilt on myself,'' Anderson
declared. ``But I have problems secondary to that. There was
something about the Vietnamese people I had to do.''
   Anderson said he didn't have to come home from the war to
conclude, as he did, that there was something wrong with U.S.
involvement in Vietnam.
   ``In my first three months in Vietnam I noticed it was a crazy
war and it was wrong and that some day we would have to make up for
it,'' he said.
   The volunteers, who had collected $50,000 in a funding drive
that began last year, were given housing by the Vietnamese
government, Anderson said. But they had to buy their own food and
other necessities.
   They ran into some surprises in building their clinic. Instead
of using concrete blocks they had to use small locally made bricks.
The basic design, which called for a 1,500-square-foot building,
was changed to 2,500 square feet at the insistence of local
politicians.
   And every day, Anderson said, he had to deal with local
officials who had to approve of everything that was to be done.
   ``We brought some tools and experience, but we didn't realize we
couldn't get power to the job site,'' he said. ``We didn't realize
water was rationed so we couldn't mix materials. We didn't realize
everything had to be done by hand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
