<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia 2ndLd-Writethru a0704 04-06 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0704,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Fighting in Namibia; Emergency Meeting Scheduled</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to UPDATE with U.S. reaction. Picks up
2nd pvs, `Chief Inspector...'; INSERT graf after 11th pvs, ``I trust...'.
UPDATING with Crocker leaving for meeting. Picks up 12th pvs, `A Namibian...'
CORRECTING typo in 15th pvs, `The United...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ADIL BRADLOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security forces engaged black
nationalist guerrillas in bitter combat Thursday as South Africa,
Angola and Cuba arranged emergency talks to salvage the
U.N.-sponsored plan for Namibia's independence.
   ``There is a crisis in Namibia,'' said a State Department
official in Washington, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``We've
got a real problem.''
   Chief Inspector Kierie du Rand, a South African who heads
Namibia territorial force, said 42 guerrillas were killed in
clashes Thursday afternoon, including one battle involving scores
of insurgents. An undetermined number of policemen were injured, he
said.
   Government-run South African Broadcasting Corp. said a ``pitched
battle ... raged for several hours'' Thursday between security
forces and about 200 guerrillas.
   Du Rand said at least 252 guerrillas of the South-West Africa
People's Organization and 24 members of the South African-led
security forces have been killed since gunbattles broke out
Saturday, when a cease-fire was supposed to take effect.
   Angola's state news agency quoted SWAPO defense spokesman Peter
Muehihange as saying only 38 guerrillas died in that time and nine
are missing. He said 20 security force members were killed.
   Foreign Minister Pik Botha of South Africa said his government
is committed to the plan to grant independence to Namibia, which
Pretoria has ruled for 74 years.
   South Africa claims SWAPO has sent more than 1,500 guerrillas
into Namibia in violation of an accord requiring the insurgents to
remain at their bases in Angola, at least 100 miles away.
   The South African Council of Churches, led by prominent
anti-apartheid clergymen, said ``the carnage of the last few days''
could have been prevented if the United Nations had denied South
Africa's request to let its forces leave their bases to combat the
guerrillas.
   It said the credibility of the U.N. peacekeeping force was in
doubt.
   A joint South African-Cuban-Angolan commission monitoring the
independence accord scheduled a meeting Saturday to discuss the
crisis. South Africa's President P.W. Botha said U.S. and Soviet
observers would participate.
   ``I trust that the commission will be able to find a peaceful
solution to the very serious situation which has arisen,'' he told
Parliament in Cape Town.
   Chester A. Crocker, the assistant secretary of state for African
Affairs, left Washington on Thursday to attend the commission
meeting.
   A Namibian police official, Chief Inspector Derek Brune,
reported more skirmishes Thursday across the 300-mile front near
the Angolan border. He said the guerrillas have broken up into
small groups and that some fighters were reported as far as 120
miles south of the border.
   Cedric Thornberry, second-in-command of the U.N. contingent,
said the United Nations hoped to have its first infantry battalions
in the battle areas early next week.
   The United Nations has authorized 4,650 troops for the Namibia
operation, but only 921 have arrived. The only forces in the battle
area are about 300 logistical personnel.
   The United Nations accepted a U.S. offer to fly 850 Finnish
soldiers to Namibia. Francois Giuliani, spokesman for
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, told reporters the men
could be arriving over the weekend.
   SWAPO officials said the guerrilla fighters had been inside
Namibia for some time and had no intention of leaving or accepting
a surrender proposal.
   But Thornberry said: ``It was made clear beyond a shadow of a
doubt to SWAPO that it would have to negotiate an additional
element'' to the U.N. plan if it wanted bases inside Namibia.
   The way for Namibian independence was cleared in December when
South Africa, Angola and Cuba signed an accord calling for
withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops who have helped Marxist Angola
battle U.S.-backed rebels.
   Besides granting Namibia independence, South Africa is to end
military aid to the Angolan rebels.
   SWAPO, which has been waging a war for independence for 23
years, is favored to win elections scheduled in November under the
U.N. plan.
</TEXT>
