<FIRST>u a AM-ThinBlueLine     04-06 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thin Blue Line,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyers Leave District Attorney's Office After Adams Flap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE FAHLGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecutor who fought to keep Randall Dale
Adams in jail despite an overturned murder conviction has been
fired by the district attorney, who said his assistant mishandled
the case.
   Two other assistant prosecutors who worked on the case have
resigned, reportedly because they were embarrassed by the state's
bungled attempts to deny the imprisoned man his freedom.
   Winfield Scott, 48, who insulted a colleague and two judges
during a last-minute battle to keep Adams behind bars, was fired by
District Attorney John Vance on Wednesday.
   Vance told the Dallas Times Herald that Scott ``just did not
handle (the Adams case) the way I had told him to handle it. ... He
was convinced he was doing right and I was convinced he was doing
wrong.''
   Several phone calls by The Associated Press to Scott and Vance
were not returned Thursday.
   ``First Tom Landry and now Winfield Scott. Is no icon safe in
Dallas?'' asked Randy Schaffer, the Houston attorney who
represented Adams during appeals of his 1977 capital murder
conviction of a Dallas police officer.
   ``Apparently, the powers that be just perceived that they could
not longer keep him in the office. But I think he was just
following orders,'' Schaffer said. ``I guarantee you if he won the
recusal hearing (to oust state district Judge Larry Baraka from the
case), he wouldn't have been fired.''
   Adams, whose conviction for the 1976 slaying of a Dallas police
officer was overturned last month, was freed March 21 after
spending 12{ years in prison. At one point he came within three
days of execution.
   His case was resurrected with evidence uncovered in a
documentary by Errol Morris ``The Thin Blue Line,'' which strongly
suggested that Dallas officer Robert Wood was not slain by Adams,
but by witness David Harris.
   Acting on Baraka's recommendation, the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals ruled that the original prosecutor suppressed evidence
while at least two witnesses lied on the stand.
   Assistant district attorneys Leslie McFarlane and John Creuzot,
who represented the state in a December hearing on whether Adams
should receive a new trial, announced earlier this week that they
would leave the office by the end of the month. Both said they will
pursue private practices.
   ``It's time for me to move on,'' said Ms. McFarlane, 32, who has
been with the office 5{ years. ``It's time for me to leave.''
   ``It's time to move to greener pastures,'' said Creuzot, 31.
He's been with the office six years.
   But sources who asked not to be identified said both Ms.
McFarlane and Creuzot were embarrassed by the state's efforts to
keep Adams in jail.
   After Baraka granted Adams a personal recognizance bond, Scott
tried to have Baraka removed from the case and succeeded in getting
Adams' bond increased. At a hearing on the motion to oust Baraka
the next day, Scott insulted Baraka, Ms. McFarlane and the judge
who wrote the March 1 opinion overturning Adams' conviction.
</TEXT>
