<FIRST>u i AM-Gorbachev-Raisa 2ndLd-Writethru a0710 04-06 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gorbachev-Raisa, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0710,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet First Lady On Whirlwind Sightseeing Tour of London</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th pvs, `She also...' with 5 grafs to UPDATE with encounter
with schoolboy, quotes. Pick up 6th pvs, ``I'm glad...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gorbachev, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON20</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Raisa Gorbachev, on a whirlwind tour of London on
Thursday, watched a Punch and Judy show and appealed to children to
``let the flowers grow everywhere'' as a symbol of peace.
   Mrs. Gorbachev arrived late Wednesday night from Cuba with her
husband for a two-day visit, their second to London, and did not
seem to mind trading Cuba's hot sunshine for London's chilly rain.
   ``I feel quite fresh after Havana,'' she told reporters at Tower
Bridge during a five-minute stop at the misty River Thames.
   Visiting Prior Weston primary school, she received a bouquet of
red carnations and urged the children to ``tell your grown-up
brothers and sisters, your parents and your friends, that we spoke
about flowers growing throughout the world.''
   Mrs. Gorbachev sealed this wish with a kiss, leaving 9-year-old
Benjamin Robinson pink with embarrassment and adorned with two
bright-red lipstick kisses on his cheeks.
   ``I didn't dislike it. But I didn't like it either,'' Benjamin
said of his close encounter with the Soviet first lady.
   ``You have got a bit of history on your cheek,'' head teacher
Mary Caven told him.
   ``Eventually Mum will make me wash it off,'' Benjamin replied.
   Mrs. Gorbachev also toured the Museum of London, where she
watched a few scenes from a Punch and Judy show and saw an exhibit
commemorating Karl Marx, communism's founding father, who lived in
London and studied the poverty that afflicted the capital in the
19th century.
   ``I'm glad to come and see this great and beautiful city again
where history is in close touch with the present time. I've tried
to see as much as I can,'' she said.
   Mrs. Gorbachev started her sightseeing tour at St. Paul's
Cathedral, Sir Christopher Wren's architectural masterpiece.
   A small crowd of about 100 stood across the street in drizzling
rain as Mrs. Gorbachev arrived.
   At the entrance, 4-year-old Emma Scott presented her with pink
and white flowers. Mrs. Gorbachev picked her up, gave her a kiss
and presented her with a box of Russian chocolates.
   Her mother, Jane Scott, holding the opened box on the church
steps, said that while Mrs. Gorbachev was touring the cathedral,
Emma had already started eating the chocolates.
   ``They're lovely. She's had two,'' said Mrs. Scott, whose
husband is the cathedral's assistant music director.
   After she left, the dean of St. Paul's, the Very Rev. Eric
Evans, said Mrs. Gorbachev had been ``quite fascinated and very
impressed'' by her visit.
   He said Mrs. Gorbachev, an atheist, must have been touched by
the power of God.
   ``I don't think she found Christianity but I hope she found a
few Christians,'' he said. ``I don't think you could come to this
building without something of the glory rubbing off.''
</TEXT>
