<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     04-06 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND PARK, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Someone who called 911 three times and
whined into the receiver sounded to the emergency dispatcher ``like
a kid playing on the phone.''
   The police officer who was dispatched to the apartment Tuesday
was about to summon a locksmith when he peered through a window and
saw the damsel in distress. It was Jenny, a miniature dachshund
puppy.
   ``(The dog) gets up there and dances around the table and hits
that little space bar and dials 911,'' said Officer Pete Renje.
   Jenny's owner, Chris Dolan, who got the puppy last week, has a
telephone with a button that automatically dials 911. The phone
also has a speaker.
   Jenny used both.
   The 911 system displayed the telephone number and address where
the call originated, and dispatcher Lynn Roberson called back. At
first, she got no answer. Then, she got an answering machine. Jenny
called twice more afterward.
   Dolan came home to find a police note on his door, asking him to
move the dog or the telephone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Repairman Charlie Transue has seen some
unusual cases, but no one had ever tried to deposit a hamster in a
telephone before.
   It began when Transue recently received a call telling him of an
``unusual case of trouble.''
   When the telephone repairman reached a convenience store, he
encountered a ``very distraught lady'' and her granddaughter.
   The granddaughter, about 8, had just placed her new pet, an
infant hamster, in the phone's coin-return bucket.
   When she closed the device, the hamster fell or crawled into a
small space just behind it.
   Transue, who works for Southwestern Bell Telephone Co., took the
phone apart and found the tiny creature, apparently unhurt, in the
space behind the bucket.
</TEXT>
