<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1928EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-DefenseInvestigation     04-06 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Defense Investigation,690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Contractor Says He Was Unaware of Bribes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two California executives charged with
bribery and conspiracy in the Pentagon fraud investigation said
Thursday they were unaware that a private consultant their company
had hired was bribing a Navy engineer.
   George H. Kaub and Eugene Sullivan, both former executive vice
presidents at Teledyne Electronics of Newbury Park, Calif., also
said the consultant, William Parkin, had an excellent reputation
for his expertise on government contracts.
   Defense attorney Mark Tuohey asked Kaub about Parkin, a private
consultant that Teledyne Electronics, a division of Teledyne Inc.,
hired to help it secure a lucrative Pentagon contract for hand-held
radar equipment.
   Parkin has admitted paying bribes to a Navy official for inside
information and has testified for the government. Both Parkin and
Navy engineer Stuart Berlin have pleaded guilty in the case.
   Asked Tuohey: ``Did you ever know that Mr. Parkin was paying off
three other people, including Berlin?''
   ``Absolutely not,'' Kaub responded.
   Sullivan concurred in that view.
   Kaub, one of three men on trial in Alexandria federal court, was
the first defendant to take the witness stand, followed by
Sullivan. Also on trial is Dale Schnittjer, who was Sullivan's
successor at Teledyne Electronics.
   The three face charges of bribery, conspiracy, wire fraud and
making false statements. The government claims they knew Parkin and
his associates were paying bribes to Berlin in order to secure the
radar contract.
   But the defense contends the executives were victims of a
conspiracy devised by Parkin.
   The defense is expected to continue Friday, while U.S. District
Judge Richard Williams has indicated closing arguments will be
Monday.
   Under cross-examination, Sullivan and Kaub said they never asked
Parkin about his business partners or sought details about his
operation before Teledyne Electronics hired him.
   ``You have to make an assumption that he was doing legitimate
work,'' said Kaub, noting Parkin worked for a number of well-known
defense contractors.
   Sullivan said Parkin told him that other consultants he had
hired ``didn't want their names revealed'' to protect other
business relationships, so Sullivan never asked.
   Kaub said he signed the contracts with Parkin in November 1985
that called for Parkin to receive $10,000 to help Teledyne
Electronics get permission to bid on the contract. Parkin, a former
Navy official, had a good reputation with Teledyne Electronics and
told officials there that ``he knew how to present himself, to
negotiate, lobby, whatever,'' Kaub said.
   Kaub also said the deal had a subcontract calling for Parkin to
receive $150,000 for future work should Teledyne Electronics be
successful in winning the radar job. The Pentagon awarded the
company the $24 million job in July 1987.
   Although details of Parkin's future work were not spelled out,
Kaub said the arrangement was not a contingency fee, which is
illegal under Pentagon procurement rules.
   Asked if he meant to conceal the $150,000 arrangement with
Parkin, Kaub said, ``Absolutely not. ... If you want to make
something illegal, you should hide it, not put it out in public.''
   Kaub said he had little contact with Parkin between 1985 and
late 1987. The defendant said he talked to the consultant for a
total of about 15 minutes on the telephone and spent about an hour
with him at a hotel near Washington in November 1987.
   At that meeting, Kaub said Parkin gave him two reports that
might be useful to Teledyne Electronics. Kaub said he found only
one contained valuable information while the other was ``just a
bunch of garbage.''
   Parkin has testified that he indirectly paid money to Berlin.
Parkin left government in October 1983 after a 17-year career
during which, he said, he accepted $50,000 in bribes.
   Teledyne Electronics already has pleaded guilty in the
government's investigation of fraud and corruption in the
Pentagon's massive procurement program. More than a dozen people
have pleaded guilty so far.
   In earlier testimony Thursday, Roy Lane, an executive of
Teledyne Inc., said he had known of Parkin's work for at least 20
years.
   ``I gained quite a respect for the man,'' said Lane, explaining
he had known Parkin when the latter was a contracting officer with
the Navy.
   ``I thought he was one of the most competent government
contracting officers,'' Lane said.
</TEXT>
