<FIRST>u a AM-SoCalHeat 1stLd-Writethru a0731 04-06 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-SoCal Heat, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Records Fall As Heat Wave Keeps Grip On Region</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE temperatures for Los Angeles and
San Diego, other regional readings, heat damage to crops, ice sales booming.
Picks up 6th graf: Dr. George ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mercury hit 100 and kept going Thursday
as Southern California sweated out the third day of a
record-breaking heat wave that sent thousands to the beach,
increased power demand and withered strawberries.
   Downtown Los Angeles, where the temperature peaked at 105
degrees Wednesday, registered 103 Thursday afternoon, breaking the
date's record of 91 set in 1932 and tied in 1962. San Diego's 98
made it the hottest April day on record.
   High pressure over the West squeezed warm air out of the
interior toward the populous coast, beating back sea breezes and
turning even the usually balmy beaches into a furnace for thousands
who rushed there instead of work.
   ``It started off with 80 degrees at sunrise and now it's up to
98 in the shade,'' said Santa Monica Beach lifeguard Randy
DeGregori.
   Southern California Edison said power demand to keep up with air
conditioning would beat the April record of 14,282 megawatts set
Wednesday. The Los Angeles Department of Water and Power, the other
major local supplier of electricity, projected an April record need
for 4,700 megawatts by 4 p.m.
   Other hot afternoon readings around Southern California included
110 at Ontario, 108 at El Toro, 107 at Palm Springs, 104 at Long
Beach, 102 at San Bernardino, and 100 at Riverside, Blythe and
Santa Maria.
   Much of the rest of the state shared the warmth, though not the
triple digit readings. San Francisco and Sacramento hit the upper
80s.
   San Diego County grower Fran Hillebrecht watched three acres of
strawberries in Escondido wither in a 105-degree Santa Ana wind.
   ``They're really melting in this heat,'' she said. ``You can't
put enough water on the roots of the plant to keep it from losing
moisture.''
   Conversely, San Bernardino County agricultural biologist Mike
Cohen said early warming of the soil would help summer vegetables
just being planted.
   Since Tuesday, Orange County Ice Co. has sold about 30 tons a
day to food and liquor stores, compared to the five or six tons
normally delivered daily this time of year, said office manager
Jean Mann.
   Dr. George Gellert, a Los Angeles County health official, urged
people to take precautions ranging from simply wearing hats to
spending time in air-conditioned places such as shopping malls and
supermarkets.
   The 61-degree ocean water might deter beachgoers from plunging
in, but they should at least keep splashing themselves, Gellert
said.
   ``People going to the beach and not going into the water are
just exposing themselves to the sun. ... They may be better off
remaining in the shade.''
   Santa Ana winds out of the interior began warming the region
last weekend. By Tuesday, downtown Los Angeles reached 100 degrees,
tying the all-time April record.
   Even normally cool San Francisco felt the heat Wednesday with a
record high of 88, a full 8 degrees above the previous record that
had stood since 1924.
   At 5 a.m. Thursday the mercury had dropped only to 74 in
downtown Los Angeles and 88 at Laguna Peak above Point Mugu in
Ventura County. Even at 3 a.m. hundreds of people could be found
parked along beaches seeking respite.
   SoCal Edison's all-time record power use was last September when
its 3.8 million central and southern California customers used
15,987 megawatts.
   The DWP's all time record was 4,991 megawatts on Sept. 6, 1988.
Tuesday's usage was 4,073 megawatts and Wednesday's was 4,541
megawatts.
   Even if high temperatures remain in the same range, power use
increases over the span of a heat wave because lack of overnight
cooling causes heat buildup in buildings, requiring more power to
start up air conditioning each day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
