<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2137EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-OrganizedCrime     04-06 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Organized Crime,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Urge Delay of Plan to Abolish Crime Strike Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bipartisan group of four senators asked
Attorney General Dick Thornburgh on Thursday to delay any plans to
abolish the Justice Department's Organized Crime Strike Force
Program, saying such a move could ``hamper federal law enforcement
capabilities.''
   ``Given the success of the Organized Crime Strike Force Program
over the past 20 years, we believe that a decision to abolish the
strike forces could hamper federal law enforcement capabilities at
a time when many areas are overwhelmed with organized crime and
illegal drug activity,'' the letter said.
   The letter _ signed by Democrats Edward M. Kennedy of
Massachusetts and Sam Nunn of Georgia as well as Republicans Strom
Thurmond of South Carolina and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania _ was
delivered to the Justice Department after Thornburgh had left for
the day, said aide Dave Runkel.
   Recently, Thornburgh ``has said he was leaning in favor of
merging those offices into the U.S. attorneys' offices,'' Runkel
said. ``He said he felt that would enhance the federal efforts
against organized crime.''
   The U.S. attorneys around the country have recommended _
unanimously, according to Runkel _ that the strike forces ``be
assimilated into the U.S. attorneys' offices.'' The recommendation
is under review by the Justice Department criminal division and is
expected to be forwarded to Thornburgh soon, Runkel said.
   ``A lot of the organized crime business these days is, in fact,
drugs, and when you fence the U.S. attorneys out of those cases,
that doesn't seem to be the right thing to do,'' Runkel said. ``It
seems appropriate to merge them and have one federal prosecutor
rather than two federal prosecutors in the same parts of the
country.''
   There are strike forces in about two dozen major cities around
the country.
   Runkel noted that the strike force in New York was merged with
the U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan several years ago.
   ``Under the past three U.S. attorneys, New York was the most
active in the country in the fight against organized crime,'' he
said.
   The senators noted that Thornburgh has said in speeches and in
testimony before Congress that ``some of the reasons giving rise to
the establishment of organized crime strike forces still apply,
including the need for seasoned prosecutors who can commit the time
necessary to prepare these cases and who are free of daily criminal
docket obligations.''
   The 1988 drug bill, they wrote, included a provision requiring a
comprehensive reorganization study that should be completed in
several months.
   ``A decision as important as this would benefit from the results
of that study,'' the letter said. ``Accordingly, we urge you to
delay any such decision until the appropriate committees of the
Congress have reasonable time to consider your proposal. We pledge
to do so expeditiously.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2203EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0751 04-06 0581</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0751,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians Skeptical Of Bush's Call For Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout, UPDATING with Israeli comment. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Influential Palestinians expressed skepticism
Thursday about President Bush's call for elections in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israeli officials, however, said they were encouraged by the
outcome of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's visit to Washington.
   Shamir told his aides his meeting with Bush Thursday was ``an
excellent meeting, more than I ever expected,'' Israel television
reported.
   Other Israeli reports indicated Shamir disagreed with the
Americans on some issues, notably the U.S. demand to stop Jewish
settlement in the occupied lands.
   Israeli journalists reporting from Washington quoted Shamir as
saying a timetable for discussing the elections idea will be set in
the next few days.
   Israel radio said joint U.S-Israeli teams will be created to
work out concrete proposals leading to elections.
   ``I think that in general, the positive U.S. response to the
elections idea is encouraging and raising hopes,'' Foreign Ministry
spokesman Alon Liel told The Associated Press.
   Some Palestinians expressed the fear that Shamir proposed
elections as a ploy to sidestep the Palestine Liberation
Organization and block its key demand that a Palestinian state be
created.
   ``I believe it's a trick because I don't believe the Israelis
want true peace,'' said Jack Khazmo, editor of the pro-PLO weekly
Al Bayader Assiyasi.
   ``If they did, they would go to an international conference and
accept the idea of land for peace,'' Khazmo said in an interview in
Jerusalem, where his newspaper is published.
   Also Thursday, a Palestinian died of a gunshot wound sustained
in earlier violence, and an Israeli soldier shot and critically
wounded a teen-age protester in Bethlehem, witnesses and Arab news
reports said.
   In other clashes in the occupied lands, troops shot and wounded
at least eight Palestinians.
   Doctors at Jerusalem's Mukassed Hospital said Salem Ismail
Salah, 27, of the West Bank village of Deir Salah, died Thursday of
head wounds sustained during a clash with troops March 30.
   Chanting ``PLO! Israel No!'' about 200 people in Deir Salah
waved outlawed Palestinian flags and followed Salah's coffin.
   His death brings to 420 the number of Palestinians killed since
the uprising against Israeli occupation started in December 1987.
Eighteen Israelis also have died.
   In nearby Bethlehem, reporters watched four soldiers fire live
ammunition to disperse 100 Palestinians who were throwing stones
and bottles.
   One soldier chased 17-year-old Dahoud Khaled Nassar. He knelt on
the ground, took aim, and shot the youth in the head twice from
about 40 yards away.
   An army spokesman confirmed a Palestinian youth was wounded, but
denied a live bullet hit Nassar, who was in critical condition at
Mukassed Hospital. Army regulations permit troops to fire live
ammunition only when their lives are in danger.
   Shamir's election proposal was the main idea he brought to
Washington to help resolve the conflict that has provoked much
criticism of Israeli army methods.
   Leading PLO supporters in the occupied territories did not rule
out elections, but said balloting must be part of a comprehensive
peace plan, including a timetable for negotiations on a final
settlement.
   Jonathan Kuttab, a human rights activist in the West Bank, said
as a prerequisite for elections, Israel would have to lift military
orders banning freedom of expression for the 1.7 million
Palestinians in the occupied lands.
   He said Israel also would have to end detentions without trial
and stop deporting Palestinian activists.
</TEXT>
