<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador 2ndLd-Writethru a0797 04-06 0734</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0797,0754</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Announce Nationwide Offensive; Make New Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout, UPDATING with more on rebel proposal. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels attacked two
major military bases in a nationwide offensive Thursday and asked
the right-wing victors in El Salvador's presidential election to
declare themselves a transition government.
   The rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said its
drive came in response to a surge in repression following the
victory by the Republican National Alliance, or Arena, in March 19
elections. A communique from the rebel general command accused
Arena of sponsoring the repression.
   In a proposal issued separately in Mexico City, the rebels asked
the incoming Arena government for broad talks embracing government,
rebels, the military and all political parties. It said Arena
should declare itself a transitional government until new elections
can be held.
   ``Without negotiations no one can govern El Salvador,'' it
warned.
   There was no immediate reaction to the offer.
   Authorities said at least 10 people died and 12 were wounded at
the 4th Army Brigade headquarters in northern Chalatenango province
and at the army engineers base in Zacatecoluca.
   The Farabundo Marti proposal demanded a massive cut in the armed
forces and an end to U.S. military aid. It came on the eve of a
meeting between President Bush and the Salvadoran president-elect,
Alfredo Cristiani.
   The two are expected to discuss American demands for an improved
human rights situation in El Salvador. The administration expects
to have trouble getting Congress to approve further aid to El
Salvador unless the human rights situation improves here.
   The rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos, discussing the
offensive, said ``Arena is clearly implementing a policy of
capturing popular movement leaders and activists.'' The communique
warned that ``every repressive action will receive a telling
response from us.''
   Arena has been linked to right-wing death squads and security
force extremists that killed thousands of suspected leftists in the
early 1980s. Arena leaders deny any role in the rightist terror.
   Union and student activists have disappeared or been killed
since the March 19 elections. But human rights groups consulted by
The Associated Press said they do not have enough information to
document a postelection surge in rightist violence.
   The national teachers' union, ANDES, on Thursday denounced the
slaying of Cristina Gomez, a 40-year-old union member and teacher
at the capital's John F. Kennedy school.
   A union statement said heavily armed men in civilian clothes
forced her into a dark-windowed Jeep Cherokee when she left school
at midday Wednesday. Her body was discovered with two bullets in
the head that afternoon.
   Dark-windowed Cherokees are a trademark of right-wing death
squads.
   Col. Ciro Lopez Roque, commander of the 4th Brigade in El
Paraiso, 37 miles north of San Salvador, said three soldiers and
three guerrillas died in a predawn attack and five soldiers were
wounded. He said the rebels did not penetrate the brigade's
perimeter, but several mortar shells landed inside.
   Guerrillas also attacked military engineers in Zacatecoluca, 35
miles southeast of San Salvador.
   Col. Benjamin Canjura, the post commander, said seven civilians
were wounded when homemade guerrilla artillery fell short of the
military installation. He said three soldiers were killed pursuing
retreating rebels.
   Canjura and Lopez spoke to the AP by telephone.
   The new rebel proposal, directed to the ``future government of
Arena,'' said Arena could either intensify the war or assume the
role of a transitional government to peace.
   Cristiani said repeatedly the rebels must lay down arms before
negotiations take place, something the Farabundo Marti regards as
tantamount to surrender.
   The Farabundo Marti called for talks on political, military and
economic matters with the Arena government, the armed forces and
all political parties.
   It proposed a negotiated cease-fire, to be followed in six
months by elections for a new president, mayors nationwide and a
constituent assembly to rewrite El Salvador's 6-year-old
consititution.
   The proposal said the Farabundo Marti would participate in
elections as a party in its own right, not as a supporter of
existing parties or coalitions as the rebels suggested in a January
proposal that was rejected.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte, who has terminal liver cancer,
is to hand over power to Cristiani on June 1. Duarte's physician,
Dr. Jose Luis Saca, said Thursday that Duarte's condition had
worsened but he could return to work next week.
</TEXT>
