<DOCNO> AP890406-0195 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0035EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Ravens-Tortoises     04-06 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ravens-Tortoises,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ravens to Die in Effort to Save Desert Tortoise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials plan to shoot
and poison up to 1,500 ravens in the Mojave Desert in an effort to
save the desert tortoise, which is a favorite meal of the predatory
birds.
   Animal damage control officers with the U.S. Department of
Agriculture will kill ravens by injecting hard-boiled eggs with
poison and placing the eggs on elevated platforms where the ravens
will find and eat them.
   The ravens are killing young tortoises by the thousands and
contributing to an alarming decline of tortoise populations in the
desert, said biologists with the U.S. Bureau of Land Management,
the agency that developed the raven control program.
   Bureau of Land Management officials obtained a permit this week
from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service to kill the birds, the San
Bernardino Sun reported Tuesday.
   The birds are protected by the Migratory Bird Treaty Act. The
permit represents the largest sanctioned killing of ravens in the
Western states, said Agent Tom Riley of the Fish and Wildlife
Service.
   National Audubon Society officials oppose the program and local
Audubon officials called it short-sighted and excessive.
   ``I'm a little annoyed at this,'' said Bob McKernan, president
of the San Bernardino Valley Audubon Society. ``In general the BLM
is not doing its job throughout the desert on a variety of levels.
... It bothers me that they are now having to go to these extremes
to eliminate or reduce a population.''
   Roads, dumps, homes, power lines and sewage plants in the desert
have helped boost raven populations 15-fold during the last two
decades, BLM biologists said.
   The $50,000 raven control program, set to begin within the next
two weeks, will last about four months and will be conducted in
three areas, including the Desert Tortoise Natural Area preserve
near California City, said Ted Rado, a wildlife biologist with the
U.S. Bureau of Land Management.
   The bait platforms, at least four feet high, will prevent other
animals such as kit foxes and coyotes from eating the poisoned
eggs, Rado said.
   Ravens die within 24 to 48 hours after eating the poison.
Officials plan to shoot ravens and capture some with nets fired
from cannons to supplement the poisoning program.
   Ravens favor tortoises seven years old and younger because their
fingernail-thin shells are easily punctured with their beaks. As
more and more young tortoises are eaten, fewer reach maturity and
the adult reproductive population shrinks.
   In two studies, BLM biologists attributed 88 percent of tortoise
deaths to ravens. But critics remain skeptical that ravens can
cause so much damage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0196 </DOCNO>
