<FIRST>r i AM-Arafat     04-06 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arafat,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arafat Says Assassination Squads Seek PLO Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PLO chairman Yasser Arafat was quoted
Wednesday as saying assassination squads have been deployed in
European and Arab countries to kill Palestinian leaders.
   The editor-in-chief of the London-based weekly Al-Majalla quoted
Arafat as saying the teams of killers are of different
nationalities, including one Palestinian.
   ``There are three groups, but according to the names available
to me only one person involved is a Palestinian and the rest belong
to other nationalities,'' Arafat was quoted as saying.
   ``There have always been such attempts perpetrated by the
Israelis, international intelligence agencies and Arab agents.''
   There was no elaboration.
   Excerpts from the interview ran in the weekly's Jidda-based,
sister English-language newspaper, Arab News, which is sold in
Manama.
   According to the publication, Arafat said the assassination
efforts were aimed at halting progress after last year's peace
initiative by the Palestine Liberation Organization led to the
United States lifting a 13-year ban on dealing with the guerrilla
organization.
   Arafat also was quoted as saying he did not provide information
to the Americans that could help disclose the identity of the
terrorists who planted a bomb aboard a Pan Am jet which blew up in
December over Lockerbie, Scotland.
   ``We haven't reached such type of coordination with the United
States,'' he said.
   The PLO, he was quoted as saying, was not ready to cooperate
with the United States in combating terrorism under the definition
now being applied to the word ``because it is we who are victims of
state terrorism.''
   The definition has been considered controversial because the PLO
insists any attacks on Israeli military targets are legitimate
resistance, since Israeli forces occupy the West Bank and Gaza
Strip where a Palestinian state is foreseen.
   But Arafat was quoted as stressing in the interview: ``We refuse
to blow up aircraft or kill civilians because these are crimes
against humanity and those responsible for them should receive no
mercy.''
   The report quoted Arafat as saying he believed the dialogue
between the United States and the PLO reflected ``seriousness ...
by the American administration in seeking fruitful results that
would give a strong push to the Middle East peacemaking process.''
   According to the publication, the PLO chief reiterated the
standing PLO request for U.N. forces to replace the Israelis in the
occupied territories. When asked if he would accept the presence of
U.S. forces instead, as an Arafat aide recently suggested, Arafat
was quoted as saying he would have to convene the PLO Central
Council to consider the proposal.
   The Central Council is a liaison body between the PLO leadership
and its legislative body, the Palestine National Council.
   The report said Arafat was interviewed in Tunis before the
Central Council elected him as president of the self-proclaimed
independent Palestinian state.
</TEXT>
