<HEAD>Prosecutor General Announces 65 More Executions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's hard-line Prosecutor General
Mohammad Mousavi Khoeniha announced that 65 drug smugglers will be
executed on Thursday, Tehran radio reported.
   Koeniha also was quoted Wednesday as saying that if smugglers
gave themselves up before getting caught, their sentences would be
reduced.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, quoted Khoeniha as saying that
a strict new anti-narcotics law had been very successful in
stamping out drug smuggling. He said that so far 313 smugglers had
been executed since the law took effect Jan. 21.
   The new law carries the death sentence for possession of even
small quantities of drugs.
   Khoeniha said that ``as long as there is even one drug smuggler
left in the country, the executions shall continue.''
   The new crackdown on drug smugglers is an effort to combat
rampant drug addiction in the country.
