<FIRST>r a AM-JetCrash     04-06 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jet Crash,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fliers Killed in Crash of F111 Over Nevada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two flight crewmen were killed Wednesday when
their F-111 fighter-bomber crashed during war games on the Nellis
Air Force Base bombing range, Air Force officials said.
   The crewmen, whose names were withheld pending notification of
relatives, died when their F-111 crashed about 4:30 p.m. on the
sprawling range north of Las Vegas, said Air Force Maj. Victor
Andrijauskas.
   The crewmen were assigned to a unit operating out of Lakenheath,
England, and were at Nellis participating in Red Flag training
exercises when the crash occurred.
   Andrijauskas said the two-seat jet crashed about 60 miles
southeast of Tonopah, Nev., which is about 200 miles north of Las
Vegas.
   He said the cause of the crash was not immediately known.
   Red Flag training exercises are held several times a year on the
Nellis range, where Air Force crews from around the world are
trained in realistic combat simulations.
   All planes in the Air Force combat inventory during Red Flag
exercises fly on bombing runs or engage in air-to-air combat
against aggressor aircraft with fliers in them who are trained to
fight like Warsaw Pact air crews.
   The F-111 is a medium-range swing-wing aircraft capable of
carrying nuclear weapons. It was used in the 1986 raid on Libya.
