<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-TexasAir Bjt   04-06 0670</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Texas Air, Bjt,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts: Lorenzo Profits Likely From Any Eastern Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Any sale of strike-crippled Eastern Airlines
could eventually hurt the airline and sister carrier Continental
Airlines, but Texas Air Corp. and its chairman, Frank Lorenzo, may
reap millions, analysts say.
   Some analysts believe a sale of Eastern's assets and other
advantages Lorenzo has gained during Texas Air's three years of
ownership of the airline would produce a sizable profit despite
Eastern's heavy losses and long list of creditors. Texas Air bought
Eastern in 1986 for $600 million.
   ``Our position is that he'll come out of the deal all right as
far as Eastern is concerned, but what we are concerned about in the
long term is these airlines' continuing position in the industry,''
Louis Marckesano, an airline analyst for Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc. in Philadelphia, said Wednesday.
   ``I still think there was a potential (merger) there between
Continental and Eastern that could have made a viable carrier in
the '90s. But I think either one of these carriers by themselves
may have a hard row to hoe in the future,'' Marckesano said.
   An investor group headed by former baseball commisoner Peter
V. Ueberroth reportedly was in the fdnesday of
negotiations to buy Eastern from Texas Air, but the deal hit a snag.
   Texas Air agreed last week to sell Eastern's prized Northeast
shuttle operation to New York developer Donald J. Trump for $355
million.
   Analysts said that since Eastern is in bankruptcy reorganizd has creditors
waiting to collect millions, it's still hard to
gauge just how much Texas Air would gain from ae.
   Any Eastern sale would hto be approved by the airline's
unsecured creditors committee, which includes rntatives of
the Eastern unions, and by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton Lifland.
   But Marckesano estimates that Houston-based Texas Air could see
an overall profit of more than $100 million from its three-year
ownership, based on expected proceeds from the sale of Eastern and
from revenues received during its ownership.
   That gain would be on top of the increased value of Ehat Texas Air
acquired from the airline, such as the former
Eastern computerized reservation sys merged with
Continental's to form System One. The system is used by many travel
agencies.
   ``The immediate impact will be that Mr. Lorenzo will get someh out
of it, and I fully expect that, whatever fale
takes, that will be the case,'' said Robertn airline
analyst with Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in Ch
   The amount of profit for Texas Air will depend partly on whether
a buyout includes assumptern's debts, Decker said.
   It also was uncether Lorenzo would use any such profit
to strengthen Continental, which lost $258.1 million in 1987 and
$315.5 million in 1988.
   Continentave Messing declined to comment Wednesday
on thtial effects of an Eastern sale. Texas Air spokesman
Art Kent did not return telephone calls seeking comment.
   Some experts said that even if an Eastern sale raised money to
help pay off Texas Air debt, it might not go too far in helping the
company's remaining operations.
   ``Continental is pretty debt-ridden themselves,'' said Severin
Borenstein, an airst and economist at the University of
Michigan. ``It doesn't look like they're going to start reporting
in the soon, and unless they eventually turn things
around they may nlong for this world.''
   Marckesano also cast doubts on Continental's future.
   ``Just to keep up with wha in companies like Delta
or American or Northwest, where they have $10 (billion) to $20
billion worth of equipt on order, is going to be extremely
difficult,'' Marckesano said.
   ``With Eastern gone maybe they will concentrate on pouring
capital into Continental,'' he said. ``But I don't have much
confidence in the surviving management of Texas Air that they will
do the right thing to make Continental a strong competitor in the
future.''
