<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-GasolineRationing Bjt   04-06 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gasoline Rationing, Bjt,0714</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shell, Chevron Limit Wholesale Gasoline Deliveries Due To Alaska
Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major oil companies have limited gasoline
deliveries to wholesale distributors in Western states in what one
spokesman called the first U.S. gas rationing since the Arab oil
embargo of the early 1970s.
   Spokesmen for Shell Oil Co. and Chevron Corp. said Wednesday
that the rationing was to prevent the hoarding of gasoline in the
wake of the Alaska oil spill.
   Shell spokesman Bill Gibson in Houston, Texas, said in a
telephone interview that is was the first gasoline rationing he
could recall since the Arab oil embargo of 1973-74.
   Gibson said Shell's decision to put a cap on its deliveries to
wholesalers in Washington, Oregon, California, Idaho, Utah, Nevada
and Arizona was a result of excessive buying by those distributors
in the last week.
   ``Some of our Western regional (wholesalers) began buying
excessive amounts of gasoline last week, and this (program) is
strictly in response to that,'' said Gibson, adding he didn't have
specific purchase details immediately available.
   He denied Shell's ``supply management program'' was put into
effect because of shortages in crude supplies.
   He said most of the crude for West Coast Shell refineries,
located at Anacortes, Wash., Martinez, Calif., and Los Angeles,
comes from sources other than Alaska.
   The decision to limit sales to 90 percent of the gasoline the
wholesalers purchased in April 1988 went into effect Monday and
will remain until Shell decides it's no longer necessary, he said.
   He said he did not know why Shell chose 90 percent as its figure.
   The wholesalers rushed to purchase gasoline after the tanker
Exxon Valdez slammed into rocks in Alaska's Prince William Sound on
March 24, dumping more than 10 million gallons of crude in what
became the nation's worst oil spill.
   Chevron began its rationing just three days after the accident
in anticipation of stepped-up gasoline purchases, said company
spokesman Mike Libbey in San Francisco.
   On March 27, Chervon began to limit deliveries to 100 percent of
contract agreements to make sure there'd be enough gasoline to go
around, Libbey said.
   The cost of gasoline in the Seattle area has climbed about 8
cents a gallon in the last three weeks, the biggest hikes having
occurred since the spill.
   Gibson would not comment on whether the 90 percent allotments
helped to increase wholesale and gasoline-pump prices.
   But Libbey said it was clear that the Valdez spill translated
into a 4-cent to 7-cent hike in Chevron's price per gallon to
retailers.
   Major West oast refineries rely heavily on Alaska oil to masoline and
other products. The pipeline from Alah Slope
to Valdez usually carries 2 million barrels of crude a day, but
that was reduced to 800,000 barrels a day after the spill limited
tanker loadings at the port.
   Cclaimed to have no problem with crude supplies to
its major Wesst refineries, in the San Francisco and Los
Angeles areas.
  `Chevron hasn't had to limit refinery activity at all,'' Libbey. ``I
gather from what I hear that the independents (smaller
oil companies) are squeezed more tightly than we a they
don't have the resources we have and room to maneuver.''
   Exxon in Houston said it would not be able to provide
infomation on whether it has a similar gasoline dist effect until sometime
today, and information from other major
il companies wasn't immediately available.
   Shell's deliveries to retail gasoline stations served directly
are not affected by the cap because those stations can't
keep much gasoline in storage, Gibson said.
   He did not know how much of Shell's gasoline in Western states
goes as opposed to retailers.
   Once operations are returned to normal in Alaska, gasoline
prices will start dropping, but not by much, he said. Most of the
increases consumers have seen since the New Year are the result of
a decision last fall by the OPEC nations to limit production. And,
he added, the popular summer driving season is approaching, meaning
demand will stay high and keep prices up.
</TEXT>
