<FIRST>r f BC-ContinentalPickets     04-06 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Continental Pickets,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Members Picket Continental Seattle-Tokyo Route Kickoff Dinner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air travelers will be urged to avoid Continental
Airlines, especially its new Seattle-Tokyo route, regardless of the
outcome of the Eastern Airlines strike, labor leaders said
Wednesday.
   Dozens of members of unions representing pilots, flight
attendants, mechanics, baggage handlers and other employees of
Eastern and other airlines paraded in a steady drizzle outside a
dinner kicking off Continental's Orient route.
   Virtually all, including spouses and children, wore buttons with
a slash through the name of Frank Lorenzo, head of Texas Air Corp.,
the parent company of Eastern and Continental.
   Labor's anti-Continental campaign will continue ``unless there's
some changes in Continental Airlines itself,'' said Tom Baker,
president of International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers District Lodge 751, the main union representing Boeing Co.
production workers.
   ``I would think (labor demonstrators) would have a big impact on
(ridership),'' Baker said.
   Continental is scheduled to begin Seattle-Tokyo service May 31
after wresting control of the route from United Airlines in hotly
contested administrative and court proceedings.
   Pete Runnette, vice president of Continental's international
division, said he would be glad to see an end to the Machinists'
strike against Eastern but insisted it would not affect
Seattle-Tokyo ridership.
   Local business leaders and government officials overwhelmingly
favored United, which has the most flights of any airline at
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, in the route competition, but
``I think that's behind us now,'' Runnette said.
   Nearly 1,000 travel agents, state tourism officials, Port of
Seattle representatives, Chamber of Commerce leaders and other
dignitaries were expected for the lavish dinner at the Museum of
Flight, said Mark Strope, Continental's local station chief.
</TEXT>
