<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest Bjt   04-06 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, Bjt,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Says He Would Not Bust Up Northwest Airlines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock of NWA Inc. rose $3.50 to a
record-high $87.25 a share after oil mogul Marvin Davis said his
$2.62 billion proposal to buy the parent of Northwest Airlines
would not require selling the carrier's main assets.
   ``We do not intend to `bust up' the company, and our planned
financing will not necessitate the sale of any of the company's
strategic assets,'' Davis said in a letter he sent to NWA's board
of directors Tuesday and released to the media Wednesday.
   More than 2.5 million shares of NWA stock changed hands
Wednesday.
   The Los Angeles-based billionaire, whose holdings include real
estate and entertainment properties, owns about 3 percent of NWA's
29.1 million shares and offered to pay $90 a share for NWA stock in
a letter last week to company directors.
   ``With the equity we are prepared to commit and the anticipated
structure of the balance of the financing, the company's projected
cash flow is adequate to service the debt involved,'' the second
letter said.
   Davis said in the letter that his group is ``prepared to
increase the price of our offer in the context of a negotiated
transaction.''
   A spokesman for the nation's fourth-largest air carrier, based
in suburban Eagan, confirmed receipt of the letter, but said the
company would not comment.
   Northwest Chairman Steven Rothmeier has said the directors will
review the offer, but he has not said when.
   The airline has said it intends to remain independent. State
officials have rallied behind the carrier, introducing legislation
intended to thwart a hostile takeover.
   In Washington, Minnesota Gov. Rudy Perpich and Rep. James
Oberstar, D-Minn., met with Northwest representatives Wednesday and
spoke later by telephone with Davis. Afterward, they told reporters
they still opposed the billionaire's offer.
   Perpich and Oberstar, chairman of the House aviation
subcommittee, said they remained concerned that Davis would have to
sell parts of the airline to finance the deal. They said that might
result in layoffs and in Northwest moving its service hub from
Minneapolis-St. Paul International Airport.
   Guy Cook, chairman of International Association of Machinists
District Lodge 143, said he remains ``suspicious'' of Davis' offer
because Davis has not provided specifics about how he would finance
it.
   ``I believe he has a history of buying and selling companies,''
said Cook, who heads the union representing two-thirds of
Northwest's 35,000 employees. ``He has ownership for a period of
time and then he sells it off.''
   Kurt Rivard, a financial analyst for Minneapolis-based Dain
Bosworth Inc., said the increase in NWA's stock price Wednesday
suggests confidence on the part of investors that a higher bid is
on its way.
   ``It could come from Davis, it could come from Northwest, it
could come from somewhere else,'' Rivard said.
   Before Davis made his offer, the company disclosed a separate
group of investors was interested in buying NWA. The identity of
that group, which said it owns 4.9 percent of the stock, has not
been disclosed.
   Davis repeated in his letter an earlier statement that he
intends to expand the airline's domestic and international routes
and keep the headquarters in Minnesota. He also said his plans call
for ``no employee layoffs, work-force reductions or alterations in
seniority schedules.''
   The letter said Northwest management would be retained, but also
said, ``we intend to effect only those management changes required
to improve NWA's performance.''
   Analysts have said a takeover could impair Northwest's fleet
modernization plans because Davis would have to sell assets and
cuts operating costs to service takeover debt. But Davis said in
his letter that the acquisition plan ``in no way calls for the
reduction of the company's present capital investment program.''
   Northwest has discussed profit-sharing and stock ownership plans
with its unions for more than a year. Analysts have said an
employee stock ownership plan could help the carrier defend itself
against a takeover by putting more stock in friendly hands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
