<FIRST>r f PM-GM-AirBags     04-06 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GM-Air Bags,0321</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM To Equip 500,000 1990-Model Cars With Air Bags</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has told Congress it will
install driver-side air bags as standard equipment on 13 models of
its 1990 passenger cars and offer the devices as options on two
other models.
   Robert A. Rogers, GM's director of automotive safety
engineering, told members of a subcommittee of the Senate Committee
on Commerce, Science and Transportation on Wednesday that GM plans
to equip about 500,000 '90-model cars with air bags.
   The federal government required that automakers equip 10 percent
of their 1987-model cars with some kind of passive restraint,
either automatic seat belts or air bags. That requirement rose to
40 percent with the 1989 model year and will reach 100 percent with
1990-model cars.
   Driver-side air bags will be standard equipment on the 1990
Buick Reatta and Riviera; Cadillac Allante, DeVille, Eldorado,
Fleetwood and Seville; Chevrolet Camaro and Corvette; Geo Storm and
Metro convertible; Oldsmobile Toronado; and Pontiac Firebird, GM
said in a news release.
   The devices will be optional on the Oldsmobile 88 Royale and 98
Regency, the statement said.
   All other 1990-model passenger cars will be equipped with
automatic lap-and-shoulder safety belts, GM said. The automaker
said it planned to phase in a passenger-side air bag during the
early 1990s.
   GM currently offers optional driver-side air bags on its 1989
Oldsmobile 88 Royale and 98 Regency and Cadillac DeVille and
Fleetwood models, the statement said. The devices cost about $850
each.
   Chrysler Corp. has said it will equip all of its 1990-model cars
with driver-side air bags. Air bags currently are standard on some
of its Dodge, Chrysler and Plymouth models.
   Ford Motor Co. said it would offer air bags as standard
equipment on 11 of its 1990 car lines. The devices already are
options on Ford Tempo and Mercury Topaz models.
</TEXT>
