<FIRST>u f PM-Drexel-Milken 1stLd-Writethru f0016 04-06 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Milken, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0016,0644</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milken Asks Supreme Court To Consider Appeal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 2-3, Meanwhile, unnamed ... disclosure obligations,
to UPDATE with published reports of negotiations with Drexel client. Picks
up 2nd graf pvs, The petition ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys for Michael Milken have asked the U.S.
Supreme Court to consider removing the judge in charge of the
settlement of insider trading charges against the deposed bond
financier and his former employer, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Meanwhile, unnamed sources quoted by the Wall Street Journal
today said David Solomon, chief investment officer of Solomon Asset
Management, was negotiating with prosecutors to cooperate in the
government's case against Milken. He would be the first Drexel
client to testify against Milken should he become a witness.
   The investigation is believed to focus on allegations of
``parking'' of junk bonds and stocks by Solomon's company,
according to the Journal. When parking occurs securities are bought
with the understanding that they'll be sold back to the original
owner, usually at a prearranged time and price. The process is
intended to hide their true ownership to avoid tax or disclosure
obligations.
   The petition filed Wednesday asks the court to hear their appeal
of a lower court decision allowing U.S. District Judge Milton
Pollack to preside over the Securities and Exchange Commission's
lawsuit against Drexel and Milken.
   Lawyers for Milken and his brother Lowell, who also was named in
the SEC suit filed last September, claim Pollack should be
disqualified because his wife stands to make $30 million from a
leveraged buyout Drexel helped finance.
   They allege the transaction represents a conflict of interest
for Pollack, who must approve any final settlement between Drexel
and the SEC.
   The Milkens were charged last week with a range of criminal
securities law violations in a 98-count racketeering and fraud
indictment that capped a two-year government investigation. A bond
hearing on the charges, in which the government is seeking $1.8
billion in penalties, is set for Friday.
   Michael Milken headed Drexel's California-based high-yield junk
bond division and made a reported $550 million in 1987 before
stepping down after the indictment to prepare his defense.
   The Supreme Court petition came after the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in late February refused to rehear a bid to remove
Pollack from the case. But that court did grant a stay against
Pollack issuing any rulings.
   The SEC settlement is a crucial precondition to resolving
criminal securities fraud charges against Drexel. The firm in
December agreed to pay $650 million and plead guilty to six
felonies to settle the criminal charges with the Manhattan U.S.
attorney's office.
   Negotiations between Drexel and the SEC hit a roadblock last
month over the federal government's demand to fire Milken before
the pact was reached. That condition, though, may be be moot since
Milken has left the firm.
   A majority of the 12-member appeals court rejected a bid to
allow the full panel to hear the case against Pollack. But in a
dissent, four judges said the the case would continue under ``a
cloud'' if Pollack were allowed to preside.
   Both a district court judge and a three-member appeals court
panel also rejected dismissing Pollack.
   ``We're faced with a situation where we are in a litigation with
a potentially adversarial party, namely Drexel, where that party
was responsible for $30 million going to the wife of the judge,''
said Michael Armstrong, attorney for Lowell Milken.
   ``We think that is a perception that merits the judge stepping
aside,'' he said.
   Michael Milken's lawyers also are challenging the criminal fraud
settlement in federal court, saying it violates his rights by
forcing the firm to fire him and withhold his 1988 pay of more than
$100 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
