<FIRST>r f BC-BankMerger     04-06 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bank Merger,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Executive Says NCNB May Raise Bid For C&amp;S</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. said all aspects of its unsolicited
offer for Citizens and Southern Corp. remain open to negotiations,
including the pricetag.
   ``We have the wherewithal to negotiate to the point where C&amp;S is
comfortable ... but only in a face-to-face situation,'' James H.
Hance, chief financial officer of the Charlotte, N.C.-based bank,
said Wednesday.
   Hance said NCNB could raise its offer to $44 a share, $5 more
than the current bid, which was rejected by C&amp;S' board of directors
Monday.
   NCNB offered 1.075 of its shares for each share of Atlanta-based
Citizens and Southern's stock. NBNB's share price closed on the New
York Stock Exchange Wednesday at $34.25, making its C&amp;S bid worth
around $2.3 billion.
   C&amp;S spokesman Dallas Lee said it was up to NCNB to persue the
merger issue. ``I believe the ball is in their court. I think the
C&amp;S board made it clear that C&amp;S is not trying to solicit another
offer.''
   C&amp;S has criticized the NCNB offer, saying the value of that
company's stock may have been inflated by NCNB's purchase of 20
percent of First RepublicBank in Dallas. That bank is now called
NCNB Texas National Bank.
