<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-USAir-Teamsters     04-06 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USAir-Teamsters,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>USAir, Teamsters To Begin Contract Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir has told the Teamsters it would begin
negotiating with the union on a contract for some 4,000 fleet
service workers in 101 cities, according to a newspaper report.
   But the airline hasn't dropped its opposition to the Teamsters,
which narrowly won an election last December to expand its
representation of fleet services workers from 1,900 in four cities
to the entire USAir system, today's Pittsburgh Post-Gazette said.
   USAir told a U.S. District Court in Alexandria, Va., that it
would appeal last Friday's dismissal of a lawsuit it filed
challenging the National Mediation Board's decision to certify the
union as representing the 4,000 workers.
   The nation's seventh-largest airline said through spokesman
David Clark that it would bargain in good faith as it pursues the
suit, which accuses the board of failing to investigate alleged
election improprieties.
   Bill Genoese, director of the Teamster's airline division,
called the company's decision to bargain for all 4,000 baggage
handlers, air freight handlers and catering employees a victory.
   ``For them to come out and say they would recognize 101 cities,
they were eating crow,'' he told a packed membership meeting
Wednesday at a motel near the Greater Pittsburgh International
Airport.
   Prior to the December election, which the Teamsters won by only
a four-vote margin, the union had represented 1,900 workers at
airports in Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Boston and Buffalo, N.Y.
   The election gave the union the right to extend its
representation to 900 former employees of Pacific Southwest
Airlines who lost their Teamster affiliation when the West Coast
carrier was merged into USAir last year, and to another 1,200
previously unorganized workers at smaller USAir stations.
   The Teamsters, currently working under a contract that has been
open for amendment since July 1987, also are asking a federal court
to order USAir to grant the union access to work sites and employee
records and to set up a grievance procedure for those not
previously represented, Genoese said.
   The union is seeking elimination of a two-tier wage system and
retroactive pay increases of 10 percent annually.
   USAir has offered 3 percent wage hikes and some benefit
improvements, according to the union, but wants to maintain the
lower rate scale for workers hired after May 1985.
</TEXT>
