<TEXT>
   The stock market declined broadly today as
investors cautiously awaited monthly statistics on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 6.23 to 2,298.57
in the first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by more than 2 to 1 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 279 up, 604
down and 568 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 21.24 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Interest rates moved up a bit in the government securities
market this morning in advance of the Labor Department report due
out Friday on the employment situation for March.
   Private analysts' estimates call for the data to show a slowing
of employment growth, and perhaps an increase in the unemployment
rate to 5.2 percent from February's 15-year low of 5.1 percent.
   That would tend to corroborate recent evidence that economic
growth has been slowing of late, taking upward pressure off
inflation and interest rates.
   However, investors' concerns lately have focused more on the
possibility of a recession. Brokers also said bond and stock
traders seemed to be leery of any unpleasant surprises in the jobs
report.
   Losers among the blue chips included Minnesota Mining &amp;
Manufacturing, down [ at 66}; American Express, down [ at 32}; Ford
Motor, down \ at 47\, and General Electric, down \ at 44}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .46 to 165.99. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .73 at 329.54.
   On Wednesday the Dow Jones industrial average rose 6.60 to
2,304.80, recouping Tuesday's 6.60-point loss.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 4 on the
NYSE, with 782 up, 607 down and 560 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 165.88 million shares, against 160.68
million in the previous session.
