<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Maxwell     04-06 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Maxwell,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Maxwell Reports Higher 1988 Pretax Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC, the British
conglomerate that acquired Macmillan Inc. last year for $2.6
billion, on Thursday reported its 1988 pretax profits rose 8.7
percent.
   In the year ended Dec. 31, pretax profit rose to 180.4 million
pounds, or $306.7 million, from 166 million pounds, or $282.2
million a year earlier, the company said.
   Profit after taxes and minority interest rose 2.8 percent to
$230.5 million, from $224.06 million the year before, the company
said.
   Earnings fell to 37.5 cents a share from 45.3 cents, a drop of
20.8 percent, because of a 70 percent expansion in share capital
from a rights issue last July.
   Maxwell said its sales rose 27.6 percent to $1.90 billion, from
$1.5 billion a year earlier.
   Chairman Robert Maxwell said last year ``saw the achievement of
our grand strategy of transforming within a few years a practically
bankrupt printing company into one of the big 10 global
communications and information corporations.''
   In addtion to the November takeover of Macmillan, Maxwell
Communication reached agreement in October with U.S. publisher Dun
&amp; Bradstreet to buy the Official Airlines Guide for $750 million.
</TEXT>
