<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1414EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-MustangAnniversary Adv09   04-06 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mustang Anniversary, Adv 09,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Original Pony Car Celebrates 25th Birthday; Still Going Strong</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was the car cool Baby Boomers grooved on.
   The Mustang, Ford Motor Co.'s breakthrough into lightweight,
affordable sports cars, turns 25 this month with an immortalized
place in auto history, making its mark the same way the Beatles
reshaped rock'n'roll.
   Teen-agers dreamed of cruising drive-ins in their new Mustangs
which, like the dreamers themselves, grow older by the year. Some
original Mustang drivers say they don't feel a day older than when
they slid behind the wheel for the first time.
   ``It felt great,'' Stanley Tucker of Montreal remembered about
the day 25 years ago when he drove the first Mustang ever made at
Ford's Dearborn, Mich., assembly plant, where 52 of the cars an
hour still roll off the line.
   Ruby Hummel of East Detroit got into the Mustang love affair
late. But she got her driver's license late, too. She bought a used
'68 Mustang when she got her license in 1973 at age 46.
   ``It makes you feel young,'' she said at a suburban Detroit
Jeep-Eagle dealership where she and her husband were shopping for a
new car. They pulled up in a '66 light blue and white Mustang _ a
car she says she won't trade.
   The nation is dotted with Mustang clubs and Mustang collectors.
About 75 percent of the members in the Performance Ford Club of
America are Mustang owners, said club chairman Charles Crites of
Ashville, Ohio.
   Mustang lovers praise what they call the simplicity of the early
model, promoting an exuberance and free spirit that captivated
young consumers and made Ford's rivals rethink and redesign their
own sporty models.
   The original Mustang, unveiled when Lee Iacocca was president of
Ford, had a base a price of $2,368 and featured a 170-cubic-inch,
six-cylinder engine.
   ``It could be fixed by a general novice person in the back
yard,'' in the early years, Crites said. ``Simplicity has gone out
with cheap gas.''
   Crites said he's owned about 15 Mustangs over the years, and has
three in his collection of 25 cars. His favorite Mustang is the
1969 Mustang Shelby GT 500.
   Like other Mustang buyers, Crites is proud of how he found his
pride and joy. ``In 1970, I went in (to a dealership) to buy a
truck,'' he said. ``I saw the Mustang sitting there for $3,700. I
went back two weeks later and they dropped the price by about
$500.''
   Crites drove it away that day.
   He was one of hundreds of thousands who bought Mustangs during
the early years. Ford formally introduced the car on April 17,
1964, about five weeks after Mustang's Job 1 rolled out of Ford's
Dearborn plant.
   Some purists call the first editions 1964{ models. Ford calls
them '65s.
   The first-year sales projection of 100,000 cars was passed in
four months. Sales increased to its best year in 1966, when 549,400
Mustangs were driven off Ford dealership lots.
   The second generation of Mustangs, called the Mustang II, was
introduced for the 1974 model year. It was a smaller than the '73,
reflecting the need for better fuel efficiency during the oil
crunch of the mid-1970s.
   Mustang sales bottomed out in 1983 at about 117,000 cars,
raising predictions that the car, like an aging television sit-com,
had finally run out of gas. But last year, Ford sold 170,100
Mustangs.
   The 1989 Mustang, which has a four-cylinder engine, has a base
price $9,450. An optional beefed-up 5.0-liter engine capable of 223
horsepower compared with 90 horsepower in the basic engine, is a
popular seller.
   Ford has said it plans to commemorate the Mustang birthday this
April 17 with a low-key event at its Dearborn headquarters but
doesn't plan a special edition of the car and is leaving the hoopla
to others.
   A caravan of 37 Mustangs owned by Europeans is tooling around
the country on what's been billed as the ``American Pony Drive.''
The caravan started March 24 in Jacksonville, Fla., and winds up
May 9 in Baltimore.
   But whether in the United States or overseas, Mustang's design
has been what's attracted buyers.
   ``I just like the way it looks,'' Mrs. Hummel said. ``It's
sporty looking.''
   End Advance for Sunday, April 9
</TEXT>
