<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     04-06 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0345</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices retreated today as investors
cautiously awaited monthly statistics on employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 12.46 to
2,292.34 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 476 up, 824 down and
587 unchanged.
   Interest rates moved up a bit in the government securities
market today in advance of the Labor Department report due out
Friday on the employment situation for March.
   Private analysts' estimates call for the data to show a slowing
of employment growth, and perhaps an increase in the unemployment
rate to 5.2 percent from February's 15-year low of 5.1 percent.
   That would tend to corroborate recent evidence that economic
growth has been slowing of late, taking upward pressure off
inflation and interest rates.
   However, investors' concerns lately have focused more on the
possibility of a recession. Brokers also said bond and stock
traders seemed to be leery of any unpleasant surprises in the jobs
report.
   Losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down [ at
39}; American Express, down { at 32]; Ford Motor, down | at 46~,
and General Electric, down [ at 44~.
   Retailing issues were mostly lower after leading companies in
the industry issued March sales reports that didn't impress the
Street. Sears Roebuck dropped ] to 43~; K mart | to 38{; J.C.
Penney ] to 52|, and The Limited { to 26[.
   Texas Air was unchanged at 13} in American Stock Exchange
activity. The company reached an agreement to sell its Eastern
Airlines subsidiary to a group headed by Peter Ueberroth, the
former baseball commissioner, for about $460 million.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.52 to 165.93. At the Amex, the market value index was down 1.04 at
329.23.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 100.95 million shares with two
hours to go.
