<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-06 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0198</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most futures prices for soybeans and corn were
higher while most wheat prices were lower at the close Thursday on
the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``It was a choppy market, very quiet,'' said Jerry Zusel, CBOT
floor operations manager for Balfour Maclaine Corp. ``It's not an
exciting time down here.''
   Corn prices were supported by the announcement that the Soviet
Union has bought an additional 200,000 metric tons of U.S. corn,
said research director Jerry Gidel of LIT America Inc.
   Reduced domestic demand and increasing supplies from South
America weighed on May soybeans, which were off a penny at the
close, Zusel said.
   Wheat was lower on the lack of fresh export news, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 6} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.97{ a bushel; corn was { cent to
1 cent higher, with May at $2.64} a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3
cents higher, with May at $1.86 a bushel; and soybeans were 1 cent
lower to 4 cents higher, with May at $7.14 a bushel.
