<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1647EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SteelPlant     04-06 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Plant,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Joint-Venture Steel Plant Dedicated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURG, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sprawling steel plant that has been
modernized at a cost of $400 million for use in a joint venture by
a U.S. company and its South Korean partner was dedicated Thursday
while protesters outside burned Korean flags.
   The 80-year-old factory was renovated as part of a pact between
USX Corp. and giant Pohang Iron &amp; Steel Co. of South Korea, and now
has an annual capacity of 1.4 million tons of finished steel
products, mainly material for tin cans, steel-framed furniture and
appliances.
   The USS-POSCO Industries Inc. plant is part of a 500-acre
complex in this community about 50 miles east of San Francisco.
   Former President Gerald Ford, who spoke at the dedication and
flipped the switch to put the gleaming machines and computers to
work, said joint ventures are an inevitable trend in business and
politics.
   Ford commended officials of both companies for ``the vision and
dedication to see the rebirth of the steel industry in
California.'' He recalled that experts had predicted the end of the
U.S. steel industry, but ``fortunately, the pessimists were wrong.''
   The plant, which began operation in 1909 and hasn't been in full
production for almost 20 years, was the scene of a protest by about
500 people, including members of the International Longshoremen's
and Warehousemen's Union.
   They were objecting to the use of non-union labor to handle the
renovation. ``We want people to know how it affects not just the
nation, but the local community,'' said Frank Belleci, an ILWU
member.
   Plant president E. A. Roskovensky, who said the plant does
employ union labor, said the protest stemmed from an ongoing
disagreement over the hiring of non-union contractors after a union
bid came in far over the cost of non-union labor.
   Under terms of a 1986 agreement, USX and Pohang each owns half
the plant and invested $90 million in its rejuvenation. The pact is
similar to the agreement between General Motors Corp. and Toyota
which created New United Motor Manufacturing Inc. in Fremont, Calif.
   The balance of the money invested _ $220 million _ came from
bank financing. Pohang's investment is the largest ever by a South
Korean company in the U.S.
   The plant will be a boon to the local economy, employing some
1,200 people and paying them a total of about $46 million annually.
The venture already has paid some $12 million in state sales taxes.
   Flanking the podium as Ford spoke was a poster showing three
workers and the slogan, ``We're a whole new breed of steel-maker.''
   Asked whether the plant posed a threat to the U.S. steel
industry, USX board chairman David M. Roderick said it wasn't going
to cause ``one iota'' of trouble.
   ``This is a solution ... to keep an American steel presence on
the West Coast,'' he said.
   Gen. Tae-Joon Park, chairman of Pohang, lauded those who put the
deal together despite ``all sorts of odds and difficulties.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0254 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1658EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     04-06 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose in Latest Week to New Record of $301.2 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 465 money market mutual
funds rose by $1.16 billion in the latest week to a new all-time
high of $301.2 billion, the Investment Company Institute said
Thursday.
   The increase from the previous record of $300.04 billion set
last week marked the 13th straight weekly all-time high for the
funds' assets and reflected the growing attraction of such
investments because of rising interest rates.
   The previous record originally was reported as $299.62 billion
but the Washington-based mutual fund trade group revised it upward.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the week ended
Wednesday, assets of 231 general purpose funds rose $573.3 million
to $98.62 billion, assets of 94 broker-dealer funds increased
$462.4 million to $129.39 billion, and assets of 140 institutional
funds rose $128.2 million to $73.18 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 9.08 percent from 9.04 percent the
previous week, said Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade journal
based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose to 8.97 from 8.89 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds
remained unchanged at 31 days, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts rose to 6.61 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.56 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, were unchanged at 5.14 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 9.27
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 9.17 the
previous week. Yields were 9.45 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 9.38
percent; 9.31 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 9.29 percent; and
9.21 percent on 5-year CDs, up from 9.20 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
