<DOCNO> AP890406-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 0803EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Federated Adv09   04-06 1124</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Federated, Adv 09,1170</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv09</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday April 9</HEAD>
<HEAD>Parent of Bloomie's, Burdine's and Other Chains Undergoes Massive
Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can still get a $100 Christian Dior lace
nightgown at Bloomingdale's swank Manhattan store and buy a good
off-the-rack suit from Burdine's in Miami, but their retailing
parent has undergone a wrenching change in the year since a
Canadian developer took it over.
   Federated Department Stores Inc., which owns Bloomie's,
Burdine's and three other big department store chains, is smaller,
leaner and more focused under its new boss, Robert Campeau. It has
fewer stores, fewer employees and a big mountain of debt.
   It has survived predictions that it would become a financial
ruin and retailing disaster.
   But is it a better company today?
   ``That remains to be seen,'' says Pamela Stubing, an analyst
with Moody's Investor Service Inc. Only now, she said, is Federated
emerging from a tumultuous 12-month transition.
   Campeau won Federated after a bitter, two-month fight that
included a bidding war with rival retailer R.H. Macy &amp; Co. Inc. The
takeover cost Campeau $6.7 billion.
   He quickly sold four Federated department store chains and its
discount and specialty stores to help finance the deal.
   Campeau was accused of decimating a fine old retailer, a charge
he'd heard before. In December 1986, he bought Allied Stores Corp.
for $3.4 billion, and since then has sold 18 of its 24 store
divisions.
   Campeau Corp., the umbrella for his retailing and real estate
operations, now owns nine department store companies: Jordan Marsh,
The Bon, Maas Brothers and Stern's from Allied; and Bloomingdale's,
Burdine's, Lazarus, Abraham &amp; Straus and Rich's-Goldsmith's from
Federated. It also owns Ralphs, a Southern California supermarket
chain spun off from Federated.
   Besides selling hundreds of stores, Robert Campeau has cut 9,000
jobs at Federated and Allied, and again been sharply criticized for
heavy-handedness.
   Campeau Corp. President James Roddy said in an interview that
only administrators were laid off and the cuts had ``no effect
whatsoever on the customers.''
   Campeau has done what retailing strategists said Allied and
Federated should have done long before he came along.
   When the developer first announced his offer for Federated,
securities analysts accused then-Chairman Howard Goldfeder of
literally giving the store away by failing to streamline the
company and make it more competitive.
   Campeau has cut annual operating costs at Allied and Federated
by more than $350 million a year, said 13D Research Services, a
Yorktown Heights, N.Y. firm that analyzes stocks and corporation
finances.
   Campeau Corp. stock, now trading in the teens, could go as high
as $66 a share this year, 13D predicted in a report about his
business.
   While analysts agree that Federated and Allied needed
streamlining, they are concerned about its effect on the retailers.
   It's not yet known ``if they have done a good job in cutting
down costs without destroying the stores,'' said Ms. Stubing of
Moody's.
   But just the fact that the layoffs are behind Campeau's
employees has put the company on a better track, said Walter Loeb,
an analyst with Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
   ``Everyone's happier,'' Loeb said. ``The employees are a more
cohesive group.''
   Some anxieties that prevailed a year ago apparently have not
panned out. Many observers said the Federated stores would become
too centralized under Campeau, and lose their individuality and
innovativeness.
   Loeb was reassured a year later, saying, ``Each individual
department store company is standing on its own two feet,'' but
with some direction from the home office.
   Campeau also was accused of buying the companies solely for
their lucrative real estate and the entry that stores like
Bloomingdale's would provide into new shopping malls.
   Real estate, they said, would take priority over good
merchandising.
   Roddy doesn't deny that the companies' properties was the
principal draw for Campeau, as it has been for other
developers-turned-retailers, such as Edward DeBartolo Jr. and
Australia's Hooker Corp.
   ``You acquire shopping centers a lot easier if you acquire the
company,'' Roddy said.
   However, he said, Campeau Corp. is now dependent on retailing
for profit, and the real estate end cannot survive without good
performances from Federated and Allied.
   ``The fact that there is growth in retail sales adds value to
the underlying real estate values within retail,'' Roddy said.
   With that in mind, Campeau has reworked Federated's expansion
plans to concentrate on its star Bloomingdale's division.
   The company aims at opening three new Bloomingdale's a year,
said James Zimmerman, president of Federated and Allied. Campeau
also is adding stores to other divisions and plans to expand or
remodel more than half its 250 stores over the next five years.
   Zimmerman admitted that ``We didn't spend much of spring '88
running the business,'' because executives were busy cutting costs.
   The company has made conservative projections for 1989 partly
because of the sluggish consumer buying of the past two years.
Zimmerman said Campeau hoped for a sales increase of 4 percent,
consistent with industry projects at the start of 1989.
   Campeau's fourth-quarter earnings haven't been announced, but
some analysts expect an improvement from the third quarter, when
Allied and Federated lost a combined $53.5 million. The high cost
of paying the interest on takeover-related debt was partly to blame.
   Unlike most other big retailers, Federated and Allied do not
release their sales figures monthly, making it difficult to assess
their performance.
   One industry analyst, who asked not to be identified, estimated
that despite marginal sales growth for the year ended Jan. 31,
pretax earnings rose 5 percent at Federated and 16 percent at
Allied, thanks largely to cost cuts. Loeb, the Morgan Stanley
analyst, said he expected Campeau to adequately manage the heavy
debt load it took on in acquiring Federated and Allied.
   Concerns about that debt wreaked havoc with its financing plans
last fall.
   Campeau announced in September that Federated and Allied lost a
combined $207 million during the second quarter, when sales slowed.
The next month, Federated's planned $1.15 billion high-yield bond
sale had to be postponed and restructured.
   Published reports said buyers hesitated because of the
retailer's lackluster sales and losses, but Campeau said at the
time the problem was uneasiness in the high-yield bond market
caused by the bidding war in the biggest debt-financed takeover of
all, RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Roddy acknowledged that investors were concerned about Campeau's
debt, but he expressed confidence the company can easily handle its
interest payments.
   The transition at Federated has been rocky, but the company says
it is largely complete, and analysts will be watching see if the
takeover really was a good deal for Robert Campeau.
   Said Ms. Stubing: ``This year is going to be the really telling
year.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday April 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
