<DOCNO> AP890406-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2300EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BankMerger     04-06 0394</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Merger,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>NCNB Wants Chance To Present New Takeover Offer To C&amp;S</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Banking Bids, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NCNB Corp. says it wants to discuss revising its
takeover bid for Citizens and Southern Corp., but C&amp;S officials
said Thursday the North Carolina banking company has done most of
its talking through the news media.
   ``There has been no communication with the C&amp;S board,'' C&amp;S
spokesman Dallas Lee said. ``They (NCNB) are just doing it through
the news media, and it makes it hard for C&amp;S to respond.''
   The C&amp;S board on Monday rejected an offer, made last week by
NCNB, of 1.075 shares of NCNB stock for each share of C&amp;S common
stock. The value of that offer was placed at $39 a share, or about
$2.4 billion.
   James Hance, Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB's chief financial
officer, said Wednesday his company is willing to raise the price
of the offer. He told The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta
Constitution that analysts' predictions that the new offer would be
$44 worth of stock per share were ``in the ballpark.''
   Hance said, however, that an offer would be negotiated only in a
face-to-face situation with C&amp;S.
   Lee said NCNB has not made an effort to set up such a meeting.
   But Lynn Easley, a spokeswoman for NCNB in Charlotte, said
Thursday, ``We have said at every opportunity we are willing at any
time to sit down with C&amp;S. From the very beginning, we have said we
want to sit down.''
   Ms. Easley said she did not know specifically what efforts have
been made to set up a meeting with the C&amp;S board.
   Lee's comments Thursday were not the first to be critical of
NCNB's communication with Atlanta-based C&amp;S. C&amp;S officials last
week said they learned of the original offer through a news release
before letters to the board outlining the proposal were delivered.
   The C&amp;S board, in turning down NCNB's initial offer, said it was
inadequate and possibly would not pass regulatory muster. C&amp;S has
said the value of the NCNB stock may have been inflated by the
North Carolina bank's purchase of 20 percent of First RepublicBank
in Dallas. That bank is now called NCNB Texas National Bank.
   ``I think the C&amp;S board made it clear that C&amp;S is not trying to
solicit another offer,'' Lee said.
</TEXT>
