<DOCNO> AP890406-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1744EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-BankingBids Bjt   04-06 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Banking Bids, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Say NCNB Bid Could Mean Another Protracted Takeover Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Six months after Bank of New York Co. won a rare hostile bid to
acquire rival Irving Trust Corp., the banking industry may see
another big takeover war.
   But although the unsolicited $2.4 billion buyout proposal by
giant NCNB Corp. for Atlanta-based Citizens and Southern Corp. is
in some ways similar to the 13-month battle between Irving and Bank
of New York, the latest deal has some key differences.
   It's bigger, could be more likely to generate opposition from
state and federal regulators and involves two institutions
considered strong financial performers.
   ``I guess I'd have to say it pretty much stops and ends with the
fact that both were unsolicited offers,'' said Rodgin Cohen, a
merger specialist with the law firm Sullivan &amp; Cromwell who is
working for Atlanta-based Citizens.
   Bank of New York's $1.4 billion hostile takeover battle for
Irving wasn't the first hostile bank deal, but it was the largest
of its kind to succeed in a banking industry that traditionally had
relied mainly on friendly deals.
   ``I think the Irving-Bank of New York deal definitely broke the
ice,'' Michael Rosen, a Boston attorney specializing in bank
mergers, said Thursday. ``A lot of people felt that deal was an
aberration. But now it's happening again, which is noteworthy.''
   Citizens' board of directors on Monday rejected the stock-swap
merger proposal by Charlotte, N.C.-based NCNB as inadequate.
   Experts see some similarities between the Bank of New York deal
and the NCNB proposal, but there also are plenty of differences.
   The combination of the two would result in a bank with assets of
around $75 billion, placing it firmly in the top 10 among the
nation's bank holding companies. Bank of New York grew to about $50
billion in assets after the Irving acquisition.
   Also, ``Irving was a mediocre performer that didn't live up to
its potential, whereas Citizens has been a strong performer that is
living up to its potential,'' said James J. McDermott Jr., an
analyst with Keefe Bruyette &amp; Woods.
   NCNB is offering 1.075 of its shares for each of Citizens'
stock, or around $44 a share. The company has hinted it might be
willing to raise its bid by around $5 a share if Citizens agrees to
negotiations. But Citizens' management and many analysts maintain
that even that's too low.
   NBNC stock closed unchanged at $34.25 a share Thursday. Citizens
fdeclined 25 cents to $35 a share.
   Citizens' main criticism of the offer is that the value of
NCNB's stock may have been inflated after NCNB took over the
management of the banks of the First RepublicBank Corp of Dallas
last year with the government's financial assistance. That bank is
now called NCNB Texas National Bank.
   ``The Federal Reserve may look unfavorably upon the acquisition
by NCNB of another bank given the fact that they recently received
federal assistance to acquire First RepublicBank,'' Rosen said.
   Cohen _ who represented Bank of New York in its fight for Irving
_ said Thursday that no negotiations have been held and none are
planned with NCNB. He said the company has not been talking to any
other potential suitor.
   ``It's quite clear Citizens wants to remain independent,'' Cohen
said.
   After Citizens' board rejected NCNB's offer it amended the
company's bylaws to make a takeover more difficult, applying
provisions Georgia's anti-takeover law. Irving relied on a similar
New York law, but lost several key court challenges to the statute.
   Also unlike the Bank of New York-Irving battle, the NCNB
proposal reaches across state lines.
   ``It's likely that there will be a lot more politics involved in
this battle ... (because) it's likely it would result in the
reduction of jobs,'' said Rosen. ``NCNB has a very strong track
record of cutting costs and reducing staff.''
   While NCNB's proposal calls for continuation of Citizens and
Southern's management and independent operations, banking experts
said they were doubtful NCNB would be a hands-off partner.
   ``First RepublicBank is a prime example. After they (NCNB) took
that over they changed the name,'' said Stephen Biggar, an analyst
with Argus Research.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
