<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lapsed into a sluggish decline
Thursday as investors cautiously awaited monthly statistics on
employment.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 12.83 points to
2,291.97.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 3 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
581 up, 842 down and 538 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 146.53 million
shares, down from 165.88 million in the previous session.
Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 173.52 million shares.
   Interest rates moved up a bit in the government securities
market in advance of the Labor Department report due out Friday on
the employment situation for March.
   Private analysts' estimates call for the data to show a slowing
of employment growth, and perhaps an increase in the unemployment
rate to 5.2 percent from February's 15-year low of 5.1 percent.
   That would tend to corroborate recent evidence that economic
growth has been slowing of late, taking upward pressure off
inflation and interest rates.
   However, investors' concerns lately have focused more on the
possibility of a recession. Brokers also said bond and stock
traders seemed to be leery of any unpleasant surprises in the jobs
report.
   Exxon, which said it took full responsibility for the recent oil
spill near Valdez, Alaska, dropped { to 43 in active trading.
   Other losers among the blue chips included General Motors, down
] at 39{; American Express, down ] at 32{; Ford Motor, down | at
46~, and General Electric, down \ at 44}.
   Retailing issues were mostly lower after leading companies in
the industry issued March sales reports that didn't impress the
Street. K mart dropped } to 38]; J.C. Penney ] to 52|, and The
Limited | to 26. Sears Roebuck held steady at 44\.
   Ocean Drilling &amp; Exploration climbed 1\ to 17~. Murphy Oil,
which holds a majority interest in Odeco, said it would propose to
acquire the rest of the shares through an exchange of stock.
   Texas Air slipped \ to 13{ in American Stock Exchange activity.
The company reached an agreement to sell its Eastern Airlines
subsidiary to a group headed by Peter Ueberroth, the former
baseball commissioner, for about $460 million.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $6.98 billion, or 0.24
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .43 to 166.02.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index fell 1.08 to 339.89, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was down .95 at 295.29.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
dipped .10 to 408.20. At the Amex, the market value index closed at
330.08, down .19.
