<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-06 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher; Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was generally higher in listless
trading Thursday as the foreign exchange markets awaited fresh
economic figures from Washington.
   Gold prices advanced slightly. Republic National Bank of New
York quoted a bid of $383.60 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m.
EDT, up 30 cents from late Wednesday's $383.30.
   The dollar moved in a narrow range as many traders in New York
chose to sit out the session and wait for Friday's release of
unemployment figures for March.
   If the report from the Labor Department shows continued economic
strength, the dollar could rise on the expectation that interest
rates will continue to go up. Higher U.S. interest rates are
bullish for the dollar because they make the U.S. currency more
attractive to foreign investors.
   Traders were also cautious ahead of next week's release of U.S.
trade deficit figures for February, said Robert Ryan, a senior
trader with Irving Trust Co.
   A dealer in Frankfurt said the dollar held at the same rate for
five hours during trading there. ``Nothing is happening. ... No one
knows which way the dollar should go,'' he said.
   The dollar began its day in Tokyo, where it closed at 132.15
Japanese yen, up from 131.37 yen. Later in London, the dollar
traded lower at 132.08 yen, but the U.S. currency moved higher in
New York, closing at 132.275 yen, up from 131.555 yen late
Wednesday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.7035 late Thursday, more
expensive for buyers than Wednesday's late $1.7028. But the pound
slipped in later New York trading to $1.7005 from $1.7030 late
Wednesday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's prices, included: 1.8730 West German marks, up from
1.8695; 1.6445 Swiss francs, up from 1.64125; 6.3250 French francs,
up from 6.3090; 1,373.50 Italian lire, up from 1,371.00; and
1.19325 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19075.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with Wednesday's
late rates, included: 1.8700 West German marks, up from 1.8695;
1.6415 Swiss francs, up from 1.6395; 6.3125 French francs, down
from 6.3150; 2.1090 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1125; 1,371.75
Italian lire, down from 1,372.50, and 1.1935 Canadian dollars, up
from 1.1895.
   Gold bullion prices were higher, but traders said there was
little interest in the metal. In London, gold traded at a late bid
price of $384.75 a troy ounce, up from $383.50 on Wednesday. The
late Zurich price was bid at $384.35 an ounce, up from $383.35.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell to $384.05 an ounce from $387.25
Wednesday.
   In New York, a troy ounce of gold for current delivery closed at
$384 on the Commodity Exchange, up 20 cents from late Wednesday's
$383.80.
   Silver bullion traded late in London at a bid $5.82 a troy
ounce, down from $5.83 late Wednesday.
   Silver for current delivery also declined in New York, falling
to $5.800 an ounce on the Commodity Exchange from late Wednesday's
$5.816.
</TEXT>
