<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Drexel 1stLd-Writethru   04-06 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Drexel, 1st Ld-Writethru,0390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say Drexel, Milken Played Helpful Role in Eastern Saga</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 6th graf to specify Drexel's role, picks up 6th
graf pvs, Drexel and...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Ueberroth's deal to buy strike-ravaged
Eastern Airlines got a boost from two sources that have been
getting a black eye from prosecutors: junk-bond powerhouse Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. and its indicted financier, Michael R. Milken.
   Ueberroth, the ex-baseball commissioner, told reporters at a
Thursday news conference to announce the deal with Eastern parent
Texas Air Corp. that Milken called him two weeks earlier and
offered constructive ideas on how to proceed.
   He did not specify what those ideas were but quoted Milken as
strongly advising him to ``focus on the jobs.''
   Ueberroth also put in a good word for Drexel, the nation's
fifth-largest investment banking firm that has played crucial roles
in some of the biggest takeovers of the decade.
   ``Maybe some of you don't want to here this but I think it's
essential,'' Ueberroth said. ``The company _ Texas Air, not us _
retained Drexel Burnham Lambert and they have been helpful in this
transaction on the company side and will be, overall, helpful to
complete the transaction.''
   Under the arrangement outlined by Ueberroth and Texas Air,
Drexel will provide $300 million in debt-financing for the deal,
which has been valued at $464 million.
   Drexel and Milken have been battling negative publicity since
they were implicated in wide-ranging securities fraud by
now-imprisoned speculator Ivan Boesky more than two years ago.
   Drexel agreed to plead guilty to six fraud felony charges in
December, and a grand jury indicted Milken and two others on fraud
and racketeering charges March 29. Milken has asserted innocence.
   Steven Anreder, a spokesman for Drexel, said he was unaware of
Ueberroth's remarks and could not comment further. Officials at
Robinson Lake Lerer and Montgomery, the public relations firm hired
by Milken to speak for him, would not comment.
   Eastern's employees struck March 4 after a prolonged feud with
Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo, whom they accused of stripping
the airline's assets, eliminating jobs and scheming to crush the
unions.
   Eastern sought bankruptcy refuge March 9 and Lorenzo peddled it
for sale.
</TEXT>
