<FIRST>u f AM-SearsSales     04-06 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears Sales,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Pricing Policy Propels Sears' Sales Growth</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Retail Sales Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Retailing giant Sears, Roebuck and Co. Thursday reported robust
sales growth for the first month of its new low-pricing policy but
analysts said it will take many months to judge whether Sears'
determination to beat competitors is paying off.
   Sears said its sales rose 11.9 percent in the five weeks ended
April 1 to $2.97 billion from $2.66 billion in the corresponding
period a year earlier.
   Sales at Sears stores open for at least a year increased a solid
9.6 percent during the five weeks. The industry considers these
same-store sales a better measure of a retailer's performance than
totals that includes the take at newly opened stores.
   Michael Bozic, chairman and chief executive officer of Sears
Merchandise Group, said the March volume turned out even better
than the company had hoped.
   ``Clearly, everyday low prices are well-understood and popular
with the public and we are pleased with the response to our
strategy,'' Bozic said.
   The launch of its ``everyday low price'' program, which was
promoted with an aggressive advertising campaign estimated by
outsiders to have cost about $110 million, definitely brought more
customers into Sears stores.
   Joseph Ronning, a retail specialist with Brown Bros. Harriman,
said the sales growth was a ``reflection of people experimenting to
see what Sears everyday low pricing is like.''
   ``It shows people are going into the stores to find out what's
happening,'' he said.
   One of the strongest points to make about Sears' latest
same-store sales were that they rose 15.4 percent after adjustment
for the loss of 2{ selling days due to Easter and the closing of
Sears' more than 800 stores nationwide for marking down prices in
preparation for the policy switch, Ronning said.
   The markdowns were part of a broad effort by Sears to hoist its
sagging merchandise operation. The retailer also is adding national
brands to its mostly private-label lineup and cutting costs to
recapture lost market share.
   Sears, which maintained its ranking as the country's biggest
retailer with 1988 revenue of $30.3 billion, has watched its market
share shrink this decade as go-go discounters such as Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. and specialty merchants have developed significant
followings among shoppers.
   Industry analysts said the test will be whether Sears manages to
maintain the sales momentum, especially after the fan-fare over the
changes adopted by the 102-year-old retailer dies down. Sears'
advertising already has returned to a more normal level.
   Karen Sack, a retail analyst with Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., said
Sears definitely enjoyed a far better month than many of the other
retailers that reported results on Thursday.
   No.2 retailer K mart Corp., for instance, described its sales as
``disappointing'' and blamed the weather, in part.
   Analysts said some of the weakness in sales at K mart and other
chain stores may have been the result of all the hoopla generated
by Sears policy shift but it is difficult to quantify precisely how
much sales revenue might have been taken away by Sears.
   ``It will really take the better part of a year to determine
whether their new policy is really taking hold,'' Sack said.
   Analysts are awaiting an indication if Sears' bottom line is
benefiting from the reduced prices.
   A Sears spokeswoman said the company has been mum about
predicting any impact on its earnings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890406-0263 </DOCNO>
