<FIRST>u f AM-AmericanExpansion     04-06 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Expansion,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Adds 24 Flights In Eastern's Absence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Taking advantage of strike-hobbled Eastern
Airline's absence in some lucrative markets, American Airlines
announced plans Thursday to add 11 flights in Miami and 13 in the
Caribbean by June.
   The expansion had been part of American's long-term planning,
but the timing was pushed ahead by the Machinists union strike that
has left Eastern flying only about 10 percent of its schedule since
March 4.
   Eastern's potential for returning to full operation with Peter
Ueberroth's group announcing a deal Thursday to buy the Miami-based
carrier didn't bother American.
   ``The likelihood is that Eastern will still be the largest
carrier'' in the region, said Robert Baker, American's senior vice
president for operations. ``None of what we have announced today
will rise and fall on what happens to Eastern Airlines or anyone
else.''
   American is expanding from 20 to 31 flights a day in Miami and
from 45 to 52 flights a day in San Juan, Puerto Rico, adding other
flights from domestic points to the Caribbean and switching to
larger aircraft on 11 Caribbean flights for a total addition of
3,219 seats per day, Baker said.
   Service from Boston, Philadelphia and New Orleans also would be
added if American wins federal and foreign approval for requested
flights to Bogota, Colombia; Guatemala Cit, Guatemala; San Jose,
Costa Rica, and Grand Cayman Island, he said.
   The expansion will give American 94 daily departures from 10
Florida cities, well behind Delta Airlines and Eastern's old
schedule.
   ``American is building here in Miami for the long-term, and
clearly a large part of our future revolves around Florida and the
Caribbean,'' Baker said.
   The Fort Worth, Texas-based carrier has more than 300 aircraft
on order and will have 485 in service as of Friday with the
addition of its newest A-300 Airbus, he said.
</TEXT>
