<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 1851EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-06 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0685</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By MARIO FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices fell sharply Thursday because of concerns
about large supplies, while grain futures finished mixed after
choppy trading.
   On other futures markets, energy prices were mixed, livestock
and meat slumped and precious metals were fairly steady.
   The May contract for cocoa tumbled $50 a ton at mid-session,
then recovered to finish down $35 on the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa
Exchange in New York.
   ``Especially in the nearby months, it was a major loss here
today,'' said Arthur Stevenson, analyst in New York with
Prudential-Bache Securities. ``This is really a depressed market.''
   Traders are seeing ``a negative global supply-demand balance, an
increase in the availability of physical cocoa, especially cocoa
originating in West Africa. And there's a narrowing of cash-futures
prices.''
   It was reported Thursday that Ghana expects to be able to meet
increased demands for its crop.
   Cocoa settled $10 to $35 lower, with the contract for delivery
in May at $1,300 a ton.
   Most futures prices for soybeans and corn were higher while
wheat was mixed on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``It was a choppy market, very quiet,'' said Jerry Zusel, CBOT
floor operations manager for Balfour Maclaine Corp. ``It's not an
exciting time down here.''
   Corn prices were supported by the announcement that the Soviet
Union has bought an additional 200,000 metric tons of U.S. corn,
said research director Jerry Gidel of LIT America Inc.
   While most soybean contracts were higher, reduced domestic
demands and increasing supplies from South America weighed on the
May contract, which was off a penny at the close, Zusel said.
   Wheat was depressed by the lack of fresh export news, analysts
said.
   Wheat settled 2 cents higher to 3} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.00{ a bushel; corn was 1{ cents
to 3\ cents higher, with May at $2.65{ a bushel; oats were 2 cents
to 3} cents higher, with May at $1.86} a bushel; and soybeans were
1 cent lower to 5{ cents higher, with May at $7.14 a bushel.
   Most livestock and meat futures prices were lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``There are a lot of bellies in storage and the cash price is
lower,'' said Dale Benson, a livestock analyst in Chicago with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc.
   He said traders were caught by surprise by a price plunge in the
cattle complex, although there has been a recent trend of ``buying
hogs and selling cattle.''
   Cattle settled .38 cent to .52 cent lower, with the contract for
April at 77.67 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .70 cent lower to
1.20 cents lower, with April at 78.67 cents a pound; live hogs were
.07 cent to .60 cent higher, with April at 39.97 cents a pound; and
frozen pork bellies were .52 cent higher to .40 cent lower, with
May at 34.40 cents a pound.
   Precious metals were steady on the Commodity Exchange in New
York as traders await Friday's national unemployment figures.
   ``It was very quiet, with traders taking a wait and see
attitude. The dollar had little effect,'' said Peter Cardillo of
Josephthal &amp; Co.
   Gold usually moves in the opposite direction of the dollar.
   Gold settled 10 cents to 20 cents higher, with the contract for
delivery in April at $384 a troy ounce; and silver was .2 cent
higher to .5 cent lower, with April at $5.80 a troy ounce.
   Energy futures prices were mixed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange.
   Analysts said the market was pausing after last week's huge
run-up following the Alaskan oil spill disaster.
   Crude oil settled 48 cents higher to 19 cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in May at $19.80 a barrel; heating oil was
.27 cent higher to .41 cent lower, with May at 51.22 cents a
gallon; and unleaded gasoline was 1 cent to 1.88 cents lower, with
May at 64.55 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
