<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0281,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Prices Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs, Meanwhile, the ... to delete cents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures were mostly lower in moderate
trading Thursday, led by falling gasoline prices as oil shipments
in Alaska returned to normal.
   Unleaded gasoline had risen more than 13 cents since the giant
spill off the Alaskan coast on March 24.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, unleaded gasoline for May
delivery dropped 1.88 cents to 64.55 cents a gallon from 66.43 a
gallon on Wednesday. Other contract months were mixed.
   The May contract for heating oil fell .41 cent to 51.22 cents
from 51.63 cents in the previous session, while other contracts
also declined.
   Meanwhile, the May contract for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of crude oil, settled down 19 cents at $19.80 a
barrel.
   Analysts said gasoline prices were in for a technical correction
after soaring in the week following the oil spill and the closure
of the port of Valdez.
   ``Prices reflected mostly a technical change rather than
anything fundamental,'' said Richard Redoglio, energy broker with
Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
   Analysts said oil shipments from the Valdez port exceeded 1.3
million barrels on Thursday while 2 million barrels are normally
shipped.
