<HEAD>Dollar Opened Slightly Lower, Stocks Gain Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar opened marginally lower againt the
Japanese yen Friday while share prices rebounded moderately in
morning trading on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar, which gained 0.78 yen Thursday, opened at 132.10
yen, down 0.05 yen from the previous day's close.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 365.01-point
loser Thursday, gained 55.12 points, or 0.17 percent, during the
first 15 minutes of trading Friday.
   Currency dealers said they expected quiet trading throughout the
day ahead of the release of unemployment figures in the United
States, scheduled for Friday in Washington.
   ``In a general trend, the dollar remains bullish mainly because
of the gap in interest rates between the U.S. and Japan,'' said a
dealer at Sumitomo Bank. ``The unstable political situation in
Japan is also expected to promote the yen's decline for some time.''
   Securities dealers said investors are trying to determine the
direction of the market, after the Nikkei index's sharp drop
Thursday following a nearly 1,800-point gain from the start of this
week.
