<FILEID>AP-NR-04-06-89 2204EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern-Workers     04-06 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Workers,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Employees Celebrate Sale, Say They Will Accept Cuts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jubilant Eastern Airlines strikers cheered and sang
``Take Me Out to The Ball Game'' when an agreement to sell the
carrier was announced Thursday, saying they are ready to tighten
their belts and show the public what they can do.
   Details of the proposed sale to a group led by ex-baseball
commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth are still unclear. The deal would
give Eastern employees a 30 percent share of the airline in
exchange for pay cuts and other union concessions possibly totaling
$250 million.
   If the union leaders approve, the rank and file say they are
willing to live on less to prove they can run an airline better
than Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo. And, they say, they
have shown that an employee's human rights must be respected.
   ``Whatever happens here at Eastern is going to dictate what
happens with the rest of the airlines, and in other industries
too,'' said mechanic Frank Martinez. ``We had been stripped of our
dignity while we were working for Frank Lorenzo _ now we have it
back, and we are going to rebuild the airline.''
   Martinez, whose wife Alice is a flight attendant at Eastern,
said he has no illusions that they can live as well as before the
strike.
   ``It will be painful,'' Martinez said. ``We have to deprive
ourselves of many things we had in the past, but the most important
thing is that we are building for the future.''
   Employees universally blamed Lorenzo's attitude toward workers,
not wage disputes, for the atmosphere of crisis that culminated in
the March 4 stirke. And they said they were glad to see him go.
   ``It looks like mighty Casey has struck out,'' laughed Sal
Fallavollita, an Eastern pilot for 26 years. ``We are ready to
accept concessions _ if that's what the new management wants, I'll
go along with it.''
   Ramp service worker Jose Lorie said the price of the 34-day
walkout was expensive, both to the employees and the airline itself.
   ``We know the airline has been hurt _ how much, we'll have to
find out,'' Lorie said. ``We just have to go out there with the
best possible mentality.''
   Not everyone was ecstatic about the sale, with some saying they
want to see the fine print.
   ``I've seen so much deception that I'm not going to pick up my
tools until I've seen (the contract),'' said Julio Valentine, a
maintenance worker for 23 years. But he said he was willing to make
concessions to Ueberroth.
   Most echoed the sentiments of Stephanie Orent, a mechanic who
rocked her little girl in a stroller as she listened to the excited
chatter at the union hall.
   ``Even if we don't all go back to work, for those who do, it's
the greatest,'' she said. ``Lorenzo's gone, he's gone back to
wherever he came from, and we don't want to see him again.''
</TEXT>
