<FIRST>r f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0348 04-06 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0348,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Share Prices Plunge</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei, comments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices plunged Thursday morning on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange, while the U.S. dollar traded higher against the
Japanese yen.
   The dollar, which opened at 131.93 yen, up 0.56 yen from
Wednesday's 131.37-yen close, inched down to 131.90 yen by late
morning. The currency traded in the range of 131.75-131.98 yen.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 48.54 points to
close a record-high 33,367.09 Wednesday, fell sharply. It finished
the morning session at 33,167.30, down 193.49 points or 0.58
percent.
   ``Most investors have been concerned about the continuous sharp
increases in the market's key index and slowed down their buying,
while others sold issues for profit-taking,'' said a dealer with
Daiwa Securities in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Other dealers said institutional investors, who began
participating actively in the market's bull run in the last several
days, returned to the sidelines Thursday due to concerns over
political instability following news reports of Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita's alleged involvement in a major scandal.
   In currency dealings, investors' demand for the dollar remained
strong, but participants were wary of pushing beyond the 132-yen
range, feari above 133 yen would trigger yen-support
intervention by Japan'central bank, traders said.
   A trader at a commercial bank, ing on condition of
anonymity, said Takeshita's political troubles also were
discouraging yen purchases.
   Takeshita, whose administration is under fire for its links to
Recruit Co., the job informationmerate at the scandal's
center, suffered a major blow Wednesdayts that he had
received $380,000 from the firm ng parties held in May
1987.
   The company came under investigation for suspected bribery after
it was disclosed that it sold hundreds of thousands of unlisted
shares of its real estate subsidiary at discount prices to 159
influential people. The recipients of the netted substantial
profits after over-the-counter trading began.
</TEXT>
